WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en-IN

00:00:00.040 --> 00:00:03.840
How you guys see
different sectors evolving...

00:00:03.920 --> 00:00:07.920
Where can me, as either an investor,

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:12.600
or somebody looking to start my career
as a young man or woman

00:00:12.680 --> 00:00:17.760
have enough tailwinds that it makes sense
to spend the next decade in?

00:00:39.400 --> 00:00:41.280
-[inaudible conversations]
-[Nikhil] Ready?

00:00:41.360 --> 00:00:43.400
Yeah. Yeah, start.

00:00:58.800 --> 00:01:02.320
So, maybe we start with
small introductions,

00:01:02.400 --> 00:01:05.200
maybe two minutes on who you are,

00:01:05.280 --> 00:01:08.000
how you got to be where you are,
and what you're doing now.

00:01:08.080 --> 00:01:09.320
Would you like to go first?

00:01:09.400 --> 00:01:12.240
Sure. You know, I started...

00:01:12.320 --> 00:01:15.600
Well, depending on how far back
you want to go, I was... from India.

00:01:15.680 --> 00:01:17.520
-Why Deedy?
-Why Deedy?

00:01:17.600 --> 00:01:20.080
My real name is Debarghya Das.

00:01:20.160 --> 00:01:21.440
In the city of Calcutta,

00:01:21.520 --> 00:01:24.000
that's not as uncommon a name
as you'd think.

00:01:24.080 --> 00:01:27.000
But even in the city of Calcutta,
where I'm from,

00:01:27.080 --> 00:01:28.120
nobody could say that name.

00:01:28.200 --> 00:01:30.200
So very quickly in high school,

00:01:30.280 --> 00:01:33.080
we had to call me something else,
and my initials are "DD."

00:01:33.160 --> 00:01:35.560
But then that didn't solve the problem
because then you have to explain

00:01:35.640 --> 00:01:37.640
what my name actually is anyway.

00:01:37.720 --> 00:01:40.320
And so, then I just came up
with the moniker Deedy.

00:01:40.400 --> 00:01:43.440
Not Dee Dee, the Dexter's sister.

00:01:43.520 --> 00:01:47.280
And so, I spelt a little bit differently.
And that's what's stuck.

00:01:47.360 --> 00:01:49.640
So that's stuck in high school
and it's been Deedy ever since.

00:01:49.720 --> 00:01:51.560
So what did you study?
When did you come here?

00:01:51.640 --> 00:01:53.040
-What do you do now?
-Awesome.

00:01:53.120 --> 00:01:57.720
2011, got to America for the second time.
I was here as a kid for a bit.

00:01:57.800 --> 00:02:00.840
I went to Cornell.
I studied computer science.

00:02:00.920 --> 00:02:03.000
I did my undergrad and my masters.

00:02:03.800 --> 00:02:07.520
First job was Meta in New York.
Did that for a year.

00:02:07.600 --> 00:02:10.440
Then went to Google in New York,
travelled a little bit.

00:02:10.520 --> 00:02:12.320
So spent some time in Israel, Bangalore.

00:02:12.400 --> 00:02:16.760
And then I was on the founding team
of a company called Glean,

00:02:16.840 --> 00:02:19.320
which is a GC-backed company as well.

00:02:19.400 --> 00:02:21.360
And spent a good four years there.

00:02:21.440 --> 00:02:23.600
Towards the end of my time at Glean,

00:02:23.680 --> 00:02:26.160
I went from doing engineering,
to managing,

00:02:26.240 --> 00:02:28.320
to running their AI product line.

00:02:28.400 --> 00:02:29.440
What did Glean do?

00:02:29.520 --> 00:02:31.800
Glean started
as an enterprise search business.

00:02:31.880 --> 00:02:36.440
I'm happy to dive into what that means.
And then it evolved into

00:02:36.520 --> 00:02:39.360
generally an enterprise assistant
and knowledge finding tool

00:02:39.440 --> 00:02:43.120
for bigger companies to figure out
answers to questions like,

00:02:43.200 --> 00:02:46.200
"What do I do for onboarding?"
Or, "What is our holiday policy?"

00:02:46.280 --> 00:02:49.680
Or even very specific questions about
"What does this person do at the company?"

00:02:49.760 --> 00:02:51.840
And, "How can I find this doc?"
All of that stuff.

00:02:53.680 --> 00:02:58.080
Glean is now, like, $7 billion company.
It's done fairly well so far.

00:02:58.160 --> 00:03:02.040
After four years there,
I decided to try something else.

00:03:02.120 --> 00:03:04.800
My friends would joke,
I, in a span of two years,

00:03:04.880 --> 00:03:09.000
I went from engineering, management,
product, and then venture.

00:03:09.080 --> 00:03:11.480
But I was just looking
for something fun to do.

00:03:11.560 --> 00:03:14.560
And so, I joined Menlo about
a year and a half ago...

00:03:14.640 --> 00:03:16.240
And I'm at Menlo right now.

00:03:16.320 --> 00:03:19.400
And what does Menlo look at specifically?

00:03:19.480 --> 00:03:24.680
So, you know, Menlo, to give a background,
it's been around for quite a bit of time.

00:03:24.760 --> 00:03:27.120
It's a 48-year-old fund.

00:03:27.200 --> 00:03:30.000
We're now investing
out of a $1.5 billion fund,

00:03:30.080 --> 00:03:32.840
but we have, like,
about 7 billion under management.

00:03:32.920 --> 00:03:34.840
Our focus right now is, you know, our...

00:03:34.920 --> 00:03:38.520
Maybe landmark investment today
is we're big investors in Anthropic.

00:03:39.360 --> 00:03:42.000
But our focus right now,
and my focus at least,

00:03:42.080 --> 00:03:47.200
is seed and series A deals for AI,
SaaS infra, sort of all over now.

00:03:47.280 --> 00:03:49.040
Nowadays, everything is a bit of AI.

00:03:49.120 --> 00:03:51.680
But the entire fund
does everything up to, like,

00:03:51.760 --> 00:03:54.520
a series B and sometimes
C's and D's as well.

00:03:54.600 --> 00:03:55.640
-So...
-[Nikhil] Right.

00:03:55.720 --> 00:03:58.720
We also do have a good biotech practice
and a consumer practice,

00:03:58.800 --> 00:04:02.600
and the rest of the stuff we do
is primarily, like, software-adjacent.

00:04:03.280 --> 00:04:06.760
What is the Anthropic story?
Can you summarise for us?

00:04:06.840 --> 00:04:08.920
Oh, my God. What is the story?

00:04:11.880 --> 00:04:14.320
The Anthropic story was...

00:04:14.400 --> 00:04:17.200
I'm probably
not the best person to tell the story,

00:04:17.280 --> 00:04:20.080
but a few people left OpenAI,

00:04:20.160 --> 00:04:25.160
wanted to do a foundational model
company somewhat differently.

00:04:25.240 --> 00:04:27.960
And they built a--

00:04:28.040 --> 00:04:30.000
And both of them
hadn't figured out a business.

00:04:30.080 --> 00:04:32.880
And now, Anthropic
has sort of built a model

00:04:32.960 --> 00:04:35.640
that eventually became
very good at coding.

00:04:35.720 --> 00:04:38.720
And it got a ton of recognition for that.

00:04:38.800 --> 00:04:42.800
And then it's sort of-- Now, Anthropic,
I would say, is a company that's,

00:04:42.880 --> 00:04:45.480
you know, trying to solve AGI,
but they believe they're out there

00:04:45.560 --> 00:04:48.640
is through reasoning, coding,
and things like this.

00:04:48.720 --> 00:04:55.120
They, very distinctly, do not really
do much outside of text-to-text models.

00:04:55.200 --> 00:04:59.440
So less audio stuff, video stuff,
things like that.

00:04:59.520 --> 00:05:01.200
And that's really their primary focus.

00:05:01.280 --> 00:05:04.480
And in terms of a business, they just
serve enterprise customers primarily.

00:05:04.560 --> 00:05:08.600
They do have a consumer app,
but that's not really the prime business.

00:05:09.480 --> 00:05:10.560
Thank you.

00:05:10.640 --> 00:05:12.480
-Would you like to go next?
-Sure.

00:05:12.560 --> 00:05:16.480
I'm Nikunj, I moved to the States
half my life ago.

00:05:16.560 --> 00:05:19.040
Niko and I were just chatting about it--
Seventeen years ago,

00:05:19.120 --> 00:05:20.960
I went to Urbana-Champaign

00:05:21.040 --> 00:05:23.600
to do electrical engineering
and computer science.

00:05:23.680 --> 00:05:26.200
And then I moved to the Bay 13 years ago.

00:05:26.280 --> 00:05:28.560
Now you'll meet-- I don't know
what happens to both of you,

00:05:28.640 --> 00:05:31.760
when new people in their 20s come here,
I feel like a boomer.

00:05:31.840 --> 00:05:33.600
It's like, I legitimately feel old.

00:05:33.680 --> 00:05:35.480
They're like, "When did you move here?"
"Thirteen years ago."

00:05:35.560 --> 00:05:37.440
And they look at me
and they'll start eye rolling.

00:05:37.520 --> 00:05:40.000
-"About three weeks ago."
-Exactly.

00:05:41.160 --> 00:05:43.320
And then, yeah,
I was an operator for 11 years.

00:05:43.400 --> 00:05:45.360
I started my career at LinkedIn.

00:05:45.440 --> 00:05:46.880
I spent two years there.

00:05:46.960 --> 00:05:48.920
And then quickly got the start-up bug.

00:05:49.920 --> 00:05:53.760
Did four start-ups back-to-back
where I was the first PM at a few of them.

00:05:53.840 --> 00:05:57.200
I joined a company called Hall,
which did enterprise communication.

00:05:57.280 --> 00:05:59.960
I joined, and one week later,
Slack launched,

00:06:00.040 --> 00:06:02.000
which was a tough one year.

00:06:02.080 --> 00:06:04.040
-I've heard of that one.
-Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:06:04.120 --> 00:06:06.560
It was-- I picked the...
As venture capitalists say,

00:06:06.640 --> 00:06:08.720
"You picked the right area
but the wrong horse."

00:06:08.800 --> 00:06:11.360
You guys had a great URL back then,
right? Hall.com?

00:06:11.440 --> 00:06:14.000
-We still have Hall.com. Yeah. Yeah.
-Yeah, amazing.

00:06:14.080 --> 00:06:17.400
Atlassian bought the company,
didn't want to go back to a large company.

00:06:17.480 --> 00:06:21.840
And then I joined a company called Shyp
that did first-mile parcel delivery.

00:06:21.920 --> 00:06:24.120
I got really enamoured
by the physical world.

00:06:24.200 --> 00:06:26.600
This was peak Uber days.
Uber was crushing.

00:06:27.320 --> 00:06:30.120
I spent two years there. I really loved,
enjoyed, like, you know,

00:06:30.200 --> 00:06:36.120
how do you build end-to-end products, iOS,
web, but with a large operations angle.

00:06:37.240 --> 00:06:40.000
And then my best friend
worked at Opendoor,

00:06:40.080 --> 00:06:41.240
which is like a real estate company.

00:06:41.320 --> 00:06:43.600
He said, "Why don't you come join
the team there?"

00:06:43.680 --> 00:06:45.400
Can you tell us a bit about Opendoor?

00:06:45.480 --> 00:06:47.320
We were discussing earlier,
but it's interesting.

00:06:47.400 --> 00:06:50.920
Yeah, it's in the news right now
because it's become a meme stock

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:52.880
that's, like, growing really well.

00:06:52.960 --> 00:06:56.280
But I still fundamentally believe
in the mission.

00:06:56.360 --> 00:06:59.480
So I think, unlike other countries
in the world,

00:06:59.560 --> 00:07:03.960
where a transaction cost for buying
or selling a home is 1% or lower,

00:07:04.040 --> 00:07:06.200
in the US, it's 6%.

00:07:06.280 --> 00:07:08.480
Which means
when you're trying to sell a home,

00:07:08.560 --> 00:07:11.680
agents take 6% of the commission.
And that's crazy.

00:07:11.760 --> 00:07:14.280
Residential real estate
is the second largest asset class

00:07:14.360 --> 00:07:15.360
in this country.

00:07:15.440 --> 00:07:18.200
And there's a 6% tax to doing that.

00:07:18.280 --> 00:07:22.040
Which is just mind-boggling to me
as, like, someone looking at the space.

00:07:22.120 --> 00:07:24.640
And so the company was founded
by four founders,

00:07:24.720 --> 00:07:27.840
Keith Rabois, Eric, JD, and Ian.

00:07:27.920 --> 00:07:31.400
And their model was,
"We will buy your home unseen."

00:07:31.480 --> 00:07:34.720
So, every home that's bought and sold
in the country

00:07:34.800 --> 00:07:36.760
is on a register called the MLS.

00:07:36.840 --> 00:07:38.760
And so, using machine learning, they said,

00:07:38.840 --> 00:07:41.400
"Hey, we could figure out
what the true value of this home is."

00:07:41.480 --> 00:07:43.600
So you enter an address,
answer a few questions,

00:07:43.680 --> 00:07:47.360
and we give you an all-cash offer
to buy the home in one minute.

00:07:47.440 --> 00:07:50.120
Which is very different than
you having to stage your home

00:07:50.200 --> 00:07:52.800
and list your home
and pay an agent a transaction fee.

00:07:52.880 --> 00:07:55.680
In one minute, you get that fee. So...

00:07:55.760 --> 00:07:57.920
And Opendoor held the inventory,
they owned it.

00:07:58.000 --> 00:08:00.160
Opendoor held the inventory.
So, yeah, we'd buy the home,

00:08:00.240 --> 00:08:03.760
we would refurbish it,
and then we would buy--

00:08:03.840 --> 00:08:06.720
From the buyer perspective, you could
enter any home anytime you want.

00:08:06.800 --> 00:08:09.600
And you can buy the home.
All online, all transactional.

00:08:09.680 --> 00:08:12.240
It was a great journey. I...

00:08:12.320 --> 00:08:14.480
Some of my formative learnings
came from there.

00:08:14.560 --> 00:08:16.280
I spent four years there.

00:08:16.360 --> 00:08:18.280
Had to like, you know,
sort of come 2020,

00:08:18.360 --> 00:08:20.520
had to fire 35% of the company.

00:08:20.600 --> 00:08:22.560
And then we went IPO six months later.

00:08:22.640 --> 00:08:25.680
Yes, craziest six months of my career.

00:08:26.640 --> 00:08:28.160
But then I only like doing early stage.

00:08:28.240 --> 00:08:31.400
So I joined a company called Meter
which does networking hardware.

00:08:31.480 --> 00:08:33.440
-I'm meeting him tomorrow.
-Anil?

00:08:33.520 --> 00:08:35.080
-Yeah.
-Yeah. He's...

00:08:35.160 --> 00:08:37.080
-Yeah, he's amazing.
-Yeah.

00:08:37.160 --> 00:08:39.680
I wish I get the opportunity
to back people like him.

00:08:39.760 --> 00:08:41.800
GC did a big round there as well,
I think.

00:08:41.880 --> 00:08:43.360
-Recently, yeah.
-[Nikhil] Yeah.

00:08:44.440 --> 00:08:46.440
Yeah, it's a ten-year overnight
success story.

00:08:46.520 --> 00:08:48.520
Company's been around for ten years.
Two brothers--

00:08:48.600 --> 00:08:49.960
So tell us a bit about Meter.

00:08:50.040 --> 00:08:52.440
Yeah. So similar to Opendoor

00:08:52.520 --> 00:08:56.800
where, you know, there's so much friction
in the home buying and selling journey.

00:08:56.880 --> 00:08:59.920
Today, if you want to equip a space
like this for Internet,

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:02.720
it takes six different entities to do it.

00:09:02.800 --> 00:09:05.800
There's the Internet service provider,
there's a hardware maker,

00:09:05.880 --> 00:09:07.360
there's a cabling installer.

00:09:07.440 --> 00:09:10.000
There's like, you know,
other things you have to do.

00:09:10.080 --> 00:09:12.120
And then you have to maintain
the networks over time.

00:09:12.200 --> 00:09:16.240
And imagine doing that for like a 10,000
square feet, 100,000 square feet space.

00:09:16.320 --> 00:09:18.240
And so, companies have to pay CapEx.

00:09:18.320 --> 00:09:21.480
You're paying tens of thousands of dollars
in hardware upfront.

00:09:21.560 --> 00:09:23.640
And you get nothing on day zero.

00:09:23.720 --> 00:09:26.080
So Meter's completely
transformed the model

00:09:26.160 --> 00:09:28.920
where you pay nothing upfront,

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:30.680
all the hardware is Meter's.

00:09:30.760 --> 00:09:33.560
And you just pay per month
per square feet.

00:09:33.640 --> 00:09:37.760
And they take care of all the hassle
and also the maintenance.

00:09:37.840 --> 00:09:40.880
So you just, like, point to a space
and Meter takes care of everything.

00:09:40.960 --> 00:09:43.680
I did ten years of start-ups by then.

00:09:43.760 --> 00:09:47.880
And so, I was just looking
to figure out a way,

00:09:47.960 --> 00:09:52.000
how can I help founder in the plural
rather than a founder singular?

00:09:52.080 --> 00:09:54.360
And I wasn't sure
if I wanted to do investing.

00:09:54.440 --> 00:09:57.320
So I was very lucky
that the Khosla Ventures team

00:09:57.400 --> 00:10:00.200
and Vinod, especially, were very kind
to have me there for a year.

00:10:00.280 --> 00:10:02.920
I was very open.
"I don't know anything about investing."

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:05.040
I've done angel investing,
but that's very different.

00:10:05.120 --> 00:10:07.840
Spent a year there and really enjoyed it.

00:10:07.920 --> 00:10:10.680
Their team is exceptional.
I can only say good things.

00:10:10.760 --> 00:10:13.760
But decided I only wanted to be
part of a small fund.

00:10:14.920 --> 00:10:16.840
Only doing seed in series A.

00:10:16.920 --> 00:10:20.400
Each investment is like, you know,
very few investments a year.

00:10:20.480 --> 00:10:22.320
Like I have a more concentrated sample.

00:10:22.400 --> 00:10:24.640
So I just joined a new fund
called FPV Ventures

00:10:24.720 --> 00:10:26.280
about a couple of months ago.

00:10:26.360 --> 00:10:29.040
-How big is the fund?
-Fund is about five...

00:10:29.120 --> 00:10:32.000
It's a fund tube. It's $525 million.

00:10:32.080 --> 00:10:34.680
We primarily would focus on series A,

00:10:34.760 --> 00:10:38.360
but we'll do some seed in series B
depending on the founders.

00:10:38.440 --> 00:10:41.480
Right. And is there like a sector focus?

00:10:41.560 --> 00:10:44.600
No, very generalist. And that's what
attracted me towards the fund.

00:10:44.680 --> 00:10:48.800
Our Fund 1 has everything from biotech,
quantum computing,

00:10:48.880 --> 00:10:51.480
AI chip design to consumer content.

00:10:51.560 --> 00:10:55.760
Very much-- FPV stands for
Founder's Point of View.

00:10:55.840 --> 00:10:58.240
And we mostly care about the founder
and the team that we meet.

00:10:58.320 --> 00:11:00.200
[Nikhil] Nice.

00:11:00.280 --> 00:11:02.360
-And how old are you, Nikunj?
-I'm 34.

00:11:02.440 --> 00:11:03.880
And Deedy's 32?

00:11:03.960 --> 00:11:05.240
Thirty-two.

00:11:05.320 --> 00:11:07.480
-You're married?
-I'm married, two kids.

00:11:07.560 --> 00:11:09.720
-And Deedy?
-Not yet.

00:11:10.600 --> 00:11:13.880
-Okay.
-New Yorker state of mind, yeah.

00:11:13.960 --> 00:11:15.400
-Yeah.
-Hopefully soon.

00:11:15.480 --> 00:11:17.360
I have people watching this,
eligible bachelor.

00:11:19.160 --> 00:11:20.600
You live in New York?

00:11:20.680 --> 00:11:23.080
I used to live in New York, now I'm here.

00:11:23.160 --> 00:11:25.960
Yeah. New York is probably a better city
to be single in.

00:11:26.040 --> 00:11:27.720
It's not probable, it is 100%.

00:11:30.120 --> 00:11:32.040
What are you gonna do about it?

00:11:32.120 --> 00:11:35.120
-Niko, how old are you?
-I'm 40.

00:11:35.200 --> 00:11:37.000
-Okay.
-So I'm a little bit older, yeah.

00:11:37.080 --> 00:11:38.760
Yeah. Tell us about yourself.

00:11:38.840 --> 00:11:42.440
I spend all of my time
with technical young founders.

00:11:42.520 --> 00:11:48.080
Like my real passion is to obsess
with technical founders

00:11:48.160 --> 00:11:50.040
who are building products for themselves.

00:11:51.200 --> 00:11:53.120
I'm originally from Greece.
Made in Greece.

00:11:53.200 --> 00:11:55.280
Grew up between Greece and the UK.

00:11:55.360 --> 00:11:59.360
Have been in this part of the world,
Silicon Valley, since 2009

00:11:59.440 --> 00:12:02.080
when the App Store was about one year old.

00:12:02.160 --> 00:12:08.320
Got lucky, upon graduating from Stanford
to join General Catalyst.

00:12:08.400 --> 00:12:11.800
I spent a bulk of the previous
15 years there.

00:12:11.880 --> 00:12:17.200
And have been mostly investing in
first-time founders who have bold ideas.

00:12:17.280 --> 00:12:19.080
They're the customers
of their own products

00:12:19.160 --> 00:12:20.240
from all over the world.

00:12:20.320 --> 00:12:23.320
I split time between here and New York.

00:12:23.400 --> 00:12:25.440
And is there a sector that you look at?

00:12:26.240 --> 00:12:28.600
I used to look more into consumer stuff,

00:12:28.680 --> 00:12:32.760
but then what happened is,
over the last few years,

00:12:32.840 --> 00:12:36.880
made a hard turn towards
very young founders, Gen Z-ers.

00:12:36.960 --> 00:12:40.840
-[Nikhil] Right.
-And a lot of them have been AI curious.

00:12:40.920 --> 00:12:44.960
And most of the interesting ones the last
few years were, like, enterprises.

00:12:45.040 --> 00:12:47.600
-Right.
-I wouldn't care less about the sector.

00:12:47.680 --> 00:12:52.720
For me, if you're as smart as you sound
at like 16, 19, 23, 25,

00:12:52.800 --> 00:12:54.720
how much smarter can you be in five years?

00:12:54.800 --> 00:12:58.240
Because the idea will change,
the product will change,

00:12:58.320 --> 00:13:01.040
the market will evolve.
And what do I nail?

00:13:01.120 --> 00:13:06.280
Pre-seed or seed, my own perspective
on the product or the market.

00:13:06.360 --> 00:13:08.000
I'm not that smart.

00:13:08.080 --> 00:13:11.200
Is that also Neeraj's team?
Do you work with Neeraj?

00:13:11.920 --> 00:13:17.000
Neeraj joined us
with the Venture Highway team

00:13:17.080 --> 00:13:18.160
a couple of years ago.

00:13:18.240 --> 00:13:19.840
Yeah, I have worked with Neeraj,
of course.

00:13:19.920 --> 00:13:22.160
Yeah. Hemant and Neeraj
are really good friends.

00:13:22.240 --> 00:13:25.600
-They're awesome, yeah.
-We end up hanging out a lot.

00:13:25.680 --> 00:13:27.720
-Also because they have India connection.
-Awesome people.

00:13:27.800 --> 00:13:29.560
-Absolutely.
-Great people.

00:13:29.640 --> 00:13:31.000
Great people.

00:13:31.080 --> 00:13:34.200
So, what I was looking for today

00:13:34.280 --> 00:13:38.320
is we seem to be at some kind
of a crossroad

00:13:38.400 --> 00:13:44.440
where the rate of change seems to have
gone up in the world around us.

00:13:46.040 --> 00:13:50.480
I allocate money.
I don't know what I would call it.

00:13:50.560 --> 00:13:54.360
Private equity, venture capital,
whatever the term might be.

00:13:55.120 --> 00:13:59.280
And I've been in the US
for a large part of the last two months

00:13:59.360 --> 00:14:02.440
trying to get allocation
to different companies here.

00:14:02.520 --> 00:14:05.920
So I'll share with you which those
companies are along the way,

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:10.160
and maybe we can debate them together,
and if it's the right valuation or not.

00:14:10.240 --> 00:14:13.560
But more importantly,
I want to arrive at...

00:14:14.800 --> 00:14:19.280
how you guys see
different sectors evolving.

00:14:19.360 --> 00:14:21.600
Not today, but ten years from now.

00:14:22.280 --> 00:14:25.920
Where can me as either an investor

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:31.040
or somebody looking to start my career
as a young man or woman

00:14:31.120 --> 00:14:35.600
have enough tailwinds that it makes sense
to spend the next decade in?

00:14:36.560 --> 00:14:38.320
Yeah? Interesting exercise?

00:14:39.160 --> 00:14:41.560
-Sounds fabulous.
-Yeah, that's great.

00:14:42.400 --> 00:14:45.840
Okay, so should we start with--

00:14:45.920 --> 00:14:51.800
Maybe I'll go one by one
and ask you guys to name one sector

00:14:51.880 --> 00:14:55.920
that you should absolutely
stay away from as an investor

00:14:56.000 --> 00:14:59.320
or as somebody starting up
for the next decade.

00:14:59.400 --> 00:15:00.760
Let's start with Deedy.

00:15:00.840 --> 00:15:02.720
Wow, you put me on the spot.

00:15:06.240 --> 00:15:08.640
You know,
this is a hard question to answer

00:15:08.720 --> 00:15:11.080
because I have such a venture lens
on this.

00:15:11.160 --> 00:15:14.560
And, you know, when you invest
as a venture capital fund,

00:15:14.640 --> 00:15:18.480
there are certain attributes of a business
you're always looking at

00:15:18.560 --> 00:15:21.920
when you need a certain return profile
for this investment to make sense.

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:29.200
So, typically sectors
that are really tough to invest in

00:15:29.280 --> 00:15:32.160
are very high-CapEx sectors.

00:15:32.240 --> 00:15:34.880
And it's not to say that those businesses
are not good businesses.

00:15:34.960 --> 00:15:38.800
They're phenomenal businesses
in some cases, but it's just not...

00:15:38.880 --> 00:15:44.760
it does not have the return profile
that most venture investors want.

00:15:44.840 --> 00:15:47.080
And there are exceptions to that,

00:15:47.160 --> 00:15:49.960
and there are certain ways
it can be very different.

00:15:50.040 --> 00:15:55.360
But broadly, I would say it's hard
to disentangle myself from that bias.

00:15:55.440 --> 00:15:57.160
Like, usually when you're buying up, like,
I don't know,

00:15:57.240 --> 00:15:58.920
you're buying up tons of real estate.

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:01.000
That's, I mean,
Opendoor is a separate story.

00:16:01.080 --> 00:16:06.080
But then it's a tough thing to invest in,
for example, as a venture capitalist.

00:16:06.160 --> 00:16:08.080
-Forget the venture lens.
-Okay.

00:16:08.160 --> 00:16:11.680
Just as an investor or somebody
starting a job in an industry,

00:16:11.760 --> 00:16:15.280
which do you think has been most
headwind in the next ten years?

00:16:16.040 --> 00:16:18.680
Like, somebody e-mails you
from a particular industry,

00:16:18.760 --> 00:16:21.080
you'll be like,
"Okay, I'm not going to open this e-mail."

00:16:22.200 --> 00:16:27.400
I mean, I don't think I have a very strong
bent against any particular industry.

00:16:27.480 --> 00:16:32.320
I'm trying to say, like, all industries
are actually pretty important.

00:16:32.400 --> 00:16:34.880
There are some that are maybe
falling now,

00:16:34.960 --> 00:16:38.360
but it's impossible to know
how they would do in ten years.

00:16:38.440 --> 00:16:40.840
Right? Like, I'll give you an example,

00:16:40.920 --> 00:16:43.560
maybe it's probably not really gonna
answer your question.

00:16:43.640 --> 00:16:46.080
But if you take something
like manufacturing,

00:16:46.160 --> 00:16:47.440
which is a pretty traditional industry,

00:16:47.520 --> 00:16:51.520
which may not have much takers
in the venture community,

00:16:51.600 --> 00:16:53.760
there are some fantastic
manufacturing businesses

00:16:53.840 --> 00:16:57.040
that are going to be built,
especially in the next ten years,

00:16:57.120 --> 00:17:00.400
that have a whole other set
of interesting problems to solve.

00:17:00.480 --> 00:17:03.480
Like, how do you solve a labour problem?

00:17:03.560 --> 00:17:06.320
How do you manufacture
in certain countries?

00:17:06.400 --> 00:17:07.800
Can you even do that?

00:17:07.880 --> 00:17:10.960
What does tariffs mean for manufacturing
in different places in the world?

00:17:11.040 --> 00:17:14.440
So, I think there's interesting businesses
in all sectors.

00:17:14.520 --> 00:17:16.760
It's really hard-- And I don't know if...

00:17:16.840 --> 00:17:20.000
I'm curious actually what you guys think,
is often when--

00:17:20.080 --> 00:17:22.120
You have to have an open mind
as an investor

00:17:22.200 --> 00:17:24.280
to hear out the idea in a certain sector,

00:17:24.360 --> 00:17:27.960
because often it's from the places
you least expect it

00:17:28.040 --> 00:17:30.400
that an interesting idea shows up.

00:17:30.480 --> 00:17:33.200
-So you don't have a sector bias really.
-Not really.

00:17:33.280 --> 00:17:35.440
I can hit you
with some of the pithy lines of like,

00:17:35.520 --> 00:17:37.560
"Oh, who knows what's going to happen
to software engineering?"

00:17:37.640 --> 00:17:42.040
But, like, it's not really a bias
against a sector.

00:17:42.960 --> 00:17:46.040
It's just so hard to tell in the future
what's gonna happen.

00:17:46.120 --> 00:17:49.080
-Nikunj?
-Yeah, I don't think...

00:17:49.160 --> 00:17:52.400
I think some...

00:17:53.080 --> 00:17:59.080
some industries don't have
the exponential rate of progress

00:17:59.160 --> 00:18:02.120
that you need to be a venture capital--

00:18:02.200 --> 00:18:05.640
A business that can attract
venture capital.

00:18:05.720 --> 00:18:09.360
And so, I think those... you have to
realise like, venture capital is like...

00:18:09.440 --> 00:18:12.880
I think we should not fixate upon
the term "venture capital."

00:18:12.960 --> 00:18:15.120
But then I don't think...
I think every industry is interesting.

00:18:15.200 --> 00:18:18.440
Let's say you have a hundred bucks,
or hundred dollars.

00:18:18.520 --> 00:18:20.600
Where would you put it?
It's a very binary outcome.

00:18:20.680 --> 00:18:22.240
And where would you not put it?

00:18:24.400 --> 00:18:29.840
I think anything that is not technology,
like, forward, I would not put it.

00:18:29.920 --> 00:18:33.840
But that's my bias because I've been
an engineer and been here 17 years.

00:18:33.920 --> 00:18:36.600
But does that mean that you can't make
money of a traditional...

00:18:36.680 --> 00:18:39.920
Like, my dad's in textile industry.
He's doing really well.

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:42.320
Like, you know.
But what I put a hundred dollars

00:18:42.400 --> 00:18:44.880
or would I put a dollar there?
Probably not.

00:18:44.960 --> 00:18:47.600
Because I just don't understand
that business really well.

00:18:47.680 --> 00:18:49.960
And he's surrounded by like
mills and other...

00:18:50.040 --> 00:18:53.680
Those are all traditional businesses
with very little technology.

00:18:53.760 --> 00:18:56.120
They're still all printing money.

00:18:56.200 --> 00:18:58.560
But it's... it is a bias.

00:18:58.640 --> 00:18:59.840
This is why we can't...

00:18:59.920 --> 00:19:01.800
I can't disassociate
venture capital or technology

00:19:01.880 --> 00:19:03.360
from the way I view the world.

00:19:03.440 --> 00:19:05.480
-Right.
-Because that's what I understand.

00:19:05.560 --> 00:19:08.560
You put me in a traditional business--
Put me in my dad's business,

00:19:08.640 --> 00:19:11.440
I will like, you know,
bankrupt the business the next day.

00:19:11.520 --> 00:19:13.400
Because I don't get the whole...

00:19:13.480 --> 00:19:16.720
-But I do think, like--
-Are tariffs helping your dad?

00:19:17.840 --> 00:19:18.960
I mean, it doesn't hurt.

00:19:19.040 --> 00:19:22.520
Most of his customers are Indian,
most of the mills are in India.

00:19:22.600 --> 00:19:24.400
So it doesn't really affect him at all.

00:19:25.440 --> 00:19:27.280
But I think from a...

00:19:28.440 --> 00:19:31.640
So I think, for me, it's very hard to
disassociate technology or venture capital

00:19:31.720 --> 00:19:34.240
from, like, how I would invest
because that's what I do.

00:19:34.320 --> 00:19:36.480
And that's how I view the world.

00:19:36.560 --> 00:19:38.720
But to... to Deedy's point, actually,

00:19:38.800 --> 00:19:42.040
AI has actually made most industries
that were uninvestable

00:19:42.120 --> 00:19:43.400
suddenly investable.

00:19:43.480 --> 00:19:45.240
-For example?
-For example,

00:19:45.320 --> 00:19:48.480
like any industry that's collecting
large amounts of data

00:19:48.560 --> 00:19:52.600
was like, you know, prior... prior...
like, you wouldn't invest in them

00:19:52.680 --> 00:19:56.440
because you were like, "Oh, there's no
clear way for you to understand this data.

00:19:56.520 --> 00:19:58.560
No clear way
to take action on this data."

00:19:58.640 --> 00:20:01.160
Now, that's become
an actual, like, asset.

00:20:01.240 --> 00:20:03.160
Because now you can either
fine-tune models

00:20:03.240 --> 00:20:05.600
or you can actually do
something interesting with them

00:20:05.680 --> 00:20:08.320
that suddenly unlocks...

00:20:08.400 --> 00:20:11.040
unlocks value out of those.

00:20:11.120 --> 00:20:14.600
And... 2021,
interest rates spiked up a lot.

00:20:14.680 --> 00:20:17.360
And ChatGPT launched at the end of 2021.

00:20:17.440 --> 00:20:19.560
It was the literal perfect intersection.

00:20:19.640 --> 00:20:22.640
Because when interest rates rised up,
everybody's cost went up.

00:20:22.720 --> 00:20:25.800
Everybody's cost went up
means everybody wants efficiency.

00:20:25.880 --> 00:20:27.280
Everybody wants efficiency,

00:20:27.360 --> 00:20:29.960
what is the only boat that is lifting,
like, you know?

00:20:30.040 --> 00:20:31.520
What is the only tide
that's lifting all boats?

00:20:31.600 --> 00:20:32.720
It's AI.

00:20:32.800 --> 00:20:36.160
So factories are now asking and coming
and begging for solutions.

00:20:36.240 --> 00:20:37.520
That never used to happen before.

00:20:37.600 --> 00:20:39.960
Long sales cycles,
nobody wanted to invest there.

00:20:40.040 --> 00:20:42.160
Agriculture: People were like, you know--

00:20:42.240 --> 00:20:44.640
Traditional industry,
nobody wants to touch.

00:20:44.720 --> 00:20:46.360
You were like,
"What's the tailwind there?"

00:20:46.440 --> 00:20:50.840
And so, all of those industries
that felt a little bit archaic,

00:20:50.920 --> 00:20:52.800
a little bit that,
"Hey, nobody wants to touch",

00:20:52.880 --> 00:20:56.520
suddenly, the buyer's waking up saying,
"Hey, I want a solution."

00:20:56.600 --> 00:20:59.920
And so people are rising to the occasion
and building things.

00:21:00.000 --> 00:21:03.760
And I actually push, I mean,
I'm on the opposite spectrum of Deedy.

00:21:03.840 --> 00:21:05.880
High CapEx is actually OK.

00:21:05.960 --> 00:21:07.680
Because there's ways to finance it.

00:21:07.760 --> 00:21:11.040
And we're finally finding a way
that everything is getting cheaper.

00:21:11.120 --> 00:21:13.560
Robotics is a good prime example of that.

00:21:13.640 --> 00:21:16.440
But I don't think CapEx
is the big problem anyway.

00:21:16.520 --> 00:21:19.000
It's just, like, can you find
a tailwind in that industry?

00:21:19.080 --> 00:21:21.000
And that's what makes it good
for venture capital.

00:21:22.440 --> 00:21:24.600
It's very hard to, like, dissect the two.
I wouldn't know.

00:21:24.680 --> 00:21:26.360
I don't know what I would do
without technology.

00:21:26.440 --> 00:21:30.360
So interest rates going down now
will have the opposite effect?

00:21:31.680 --> 00:21:34.720
I don't think we're going to go back to
ZERP era any time soon.

00:21:34.800 --> 00:21:37.280
So, interest rates might go down
like 50 bips.

00:21:37.920 --> 00:21:39.760
But it doesn't change
the outcome that much.

00:21:39.840 --> 00:21:41.160
The genie is unlocked.

00:21:41.240 --> 00:21:44.760
Once you get used to high efficiency,
why would you do?

00:21:44.840 --> 00:21:47.840
And then if you look at
what Gen Z wants to do now,

00:21:47.920 --> 00:21:51.280
they don't want to work
as a dishwasher in a restaurant.

00:21:51.840 --> 00:21:55.360
They want to be the next influencer
or build the next business.

00:21:55.440 --> 00:21:57.120
How are you going to replace that labour?

00:21:57.920 --> 00:21:59.840
Technology is the only way
you can do that.

00:21:59.920 --> 00:22:02.560
Whether it's factory workers
or it's back-office workers,

00:22:02.640 --> 00:22:04.760
whether it's, you know, dishwasher.

00:22:04.840 --> 00:22:06.800
This is the only way that you can do it.

00:22:06.880 --> 00:22:09.400
And that's great,
because suddenly, that area that

00:22:09.480 --> 00:22:11.520
was not investable before
has suddenly become.

00:22:11.600 --> 00:22:14.560
Because everyone's a buyer
is not going to do it asking for it.

00:22:14.640 --> 00:22:16.040
Interesting. Niko?

00:22:16.920 --> 00:22:20.200
So as an investor,
a real estate investor,

00:22:20.280 --> 00:22:26.240
I would just like to avoid anything
that's super, super, super hot.

00:22:26.320 --> 00:22:28.000
As an early investor.

00:22:28.080 --> 00:22:31.960
If it's something
that everyone is going after,

00:22:32.040 --> 00:22:36.520
if it's an idea that's getting
tried now 100 times,

00:22:36.600 --> 00:22:39.560
it's probably too late, you know,
as a very early investor.

00:22:39.640 --> 00:22:42.160
Of course, the founders matter the most

00:22:42.240 --> 00:22:45.080
as we all have agreed here already.

00:22:45.160 --> 00:22:48.160
So if you think this is the founder
or the team

00:22:48.240 --> 00:22:49.640
that are going to defy the odds,

00:22:49.720 --> 00:22:51.680
they're going to out-execute everyone else

00:22:51.760 --> 00:22:55.600
in a very capital-intensive
labour-intensive business,

00:22:55.680 --> 00:22:56.680
go for it.

00:22:56.760 --> 00:22:59.960
Otherwise, anything that
at the very early stage,

00:23:00.040 --> 00:23:03.560
ten companies going after it,
it's probably too late.

00:23:03.640 --> 00:23:07.800
In today's universe,
I would avoid doing anything in China,

00:23:07.880 --> 00:23:09.480
as somebody who is US-based.

00:23:09.560 --> 00:23:11.840
That's not a controversial statement.

00:23:11.920 --> 00:23:13.920
Ten years from today?
A lot might happen.

00:23:14.000 --> 00:23:15.760
And, you know, a lot might change.

00:23:17.360 --> 00:23:20.560
And Niko, what is too hot today
that everybody is going after?

00:23:21.160 --> 00:23:23.320
Do you want to give some ideas?

00:23:23.400 --> 00:23:24.840
There's so many.

00:23:24.920 --> 00:23:26.360
Reinforcement learning.

00:23:27.080 --> 00:23:28.080
OK.

00:23:28.160 --> 00:23:31.000
Reinforcement learning environments
is a hot space.

00:23:32.440 --> 00:23:34.760
Reinforcement learning as a service
is a hot space.

00:23:34.840 --> 00:23:37.120
How about some AI code gen tools?

00:23:37.200 --> 00:23:39.320
-AI code gen is...
-App builders.

00:23:40.040 --> 00:23:42.000
-App builders, yeah.
-Receptionists.

00:23:43.200 --> 00:23:44.200
AI receptionists.

00:23:46.040 --> 00:23:48.960
Multiple applications
of voice for, you know,

00:23:49.040 --> 00:23:52.280
the same sort of
ten things are pretty hot.

00:23:52.360 --> 00:23:53.800
I mean, it's honestly amazing.

00:23:53.880 --> 00:23:56.360
You know, when you open up
your email as a venture capitalist,

00:23:56.440 --> 00:23:59.800
you know, your X or any other
inboxes you have.

00:23:59.880 --> 00:24:04.000
Like, honestly, nine out of ten
inbound requests you receive,

00:24:04.080 --> 00:24:06.200
they all sound the same.

00:24:06.280 --> 00:24:11.000
Like, if you're trying to do something,
is to break the pattern of like everything

00:24:11.080 --> 00:24:12.240
sounding the same

00:24:12.320 --> 00:24:14.960
and try to find something that's like,
"Huh, maybe this is different."

00:24:16.400 --> 00:24:18.800
Of course, it's hard
to decide, yes or no,

00:24:18.880 --> 00:24:21.640
to take a meeting without
knowing the founders.

00:24:21.720 --> 00:24:23.600
That's why, you know, warm intros matter.

00:24:23.680 --> 00:24:26.200
Or like, founders
that don't have a resume

00:24:27.080 --> 00:24:29.400
could be the ones
that could thread the needle.

00:24:30.360 --> 00:24:34.640
Because a lot of the very young founders
for like 16, 18, 23,

00:24:34.720 --> 00:24:37.680
they might not even be on LinkedIn
because Gen Z is not on LinkedIn.

00:24:37.760 --> 00:24:40.920
Or if you go there,
have plenty of random internships.

00:24:41.000 --> 00:24:45.120
And some of my favourite, you know,
social media posts that I love seeing

00:24:45.200 --> 00:24:50.160
are like the NVIDIA CEOs
before NVIDIA, you know?

00:24:50.240 --> 00:24:52.320
-Dennis. He was a busboy.
-Dennis.

00:24:52.400 --> 00:24:53.840
And you see some of this and you're like,

00:24:53.920 --> 00:24:56.040
"Yes, how can I find one of those people,"

00:24:56.120 --> 00:24:57.320
you know?

00:24:57.400 --> 00:24:58.840
-Right.
-Yeah.

00:24:58.920 --> 00:25:01.120
Which are some of the popular
companies which are doing

00:25:01.200 --> 00:25:04.360
the things you said, AI code gen,
reinforcement learning?

00:25:05.680 --> 00:25:07.080
AI receptionist?

00:25:07.720 --> 00:25:09.000
Name some names?

00:25:10.320 --> 00:25:13.760
I mean, there's Anthropic
doing AI code gen,

00:25:13.840 --> 00:25:14.840
but they're pretty good at it.

00:25:16.400 --> 00:25:18.240
-It's also Cursor, right?
-Biased.

00:25:18.320 --> 00:25:19.720
-There's also Cursor.
-Cursor.

00:25:19.800 --> 00:25:22.160
Cursor's also doing AI code gen,
of course.

00:25:22.240 --> 00:25:26.360
So these are both fairly successful
companies, at least so far.

00:25:26.440 --> 00:25:28.280
What else can we talk about?

00:25:28.360 --> 00:25:33.200
AI receptionist,
voice applications for the same.

00:25:34.360 --> 00:25:36.880
I mean, there's... I can't even
remember some of these names,

00:25:36.960 --> 00:25:40.840
but I mean,
it's not trivial to find a hot space.

00:25:40.920 --> 00:25:45.960
I mean, you just have to go on,
like, say the YC list.

00:25:46.040 --> 00:25:48.800
