00:31:22.160 --> 00:31:24.000
And it's just us coding, basically.

00:31:26.320 --> 00:31:27.320
Nikunj?

00:31:27.400 --> 00:31:32.720
I think the recent news that everybody
was jumping on was that, you know,

00:31:32.800 --> 00:31:37.360
OpenAI won the IMO Gold and then
DeepMind also did that as well.

00:31:37.440 --> 00:31:41.600
I think that was interesting, but I think
a lot of people missed in the details was,

00:31:41.680 --> 00:31:47.360
OpenAI also had this competition
where they just barely came second,

00:31:47.440 --> 00:31:52.240
where they had a single model
running for ten hours straight,

00:31:52.320 --> 00:31:55.280
with no direction whatsoever.

00:31:55.360 --> 00:32:00.480
And it was able to reason, figure out,
plan, go ahead, ten steps back.

00:32:00.560 --> 00:32:03.640
But for ten hours straight,
it was able to do something.

00:32:03.720 --> 00:32:05.800
And I think that's just like blew my mind,

00:32:05.880 --> 00:32:09.480
that shows like what
the future capabilities will be,

00:32:09.560 --> 00:32:12.560
where we're no longer, like,
you know, we already,

00:32:12.640 --> 00:32:15.240
even if we stop all AI development today,

00:32:15.320 --> 00:32:17.760
these models are already phenomenally good

00:32:17.840 --> 00:32:20.800
to think and reason and give us

00:32:20.880 --> 00:32:24.200
interesting solutions
for a long period of time.

00:32:24.280 --> 00:32:26.560
And that's like mind-blowing to me
that we've already reached here

00:32:26.640 --> 00:32:30.560
and everybody's kind of just like,
"Whoop-di-la", walking away next.

00:32:30.640 --> 00:32:36.200
And so imagine you can throw these models
at like problems for ten hours straight,

00:32:36.280 --> 00:32:38.880
like, you know,
whether it's the bare minimum

00:32:38.960 --> 00:32:42.560
of doing research
on Deedy's every tweet on Twitter

00:32:42.640 --> 00:32:48.160
to like, studying thousand
technical papers by the best researchers

00:32:48.240 --> 00:32:50.640
and trying to find hidden
connections between them.

00:32:51.840 --> 00:32:53.680
And it's... I think that's mind-blowing.

00:32:53.760 --> 00:32:57.120
I think this was not the case
even two years ago.

00:32:57.200 --> 00:33:00.600
That's why agents, AI agents sucked,
is because they couldn't reason,

00:33:00.680 --> 00:33:01.720
they couldn't understand.

00:33:01.800 --> 00:33:04.560
And in two years,
just with the models getting better,

00:33:04.640 --> 00:33:06.680
all of these things are now unlocked.

00:33:06.760 --> 00:33:11.600
Where, you know, whether it's research
on the biotech space to like, you know,

00:33:11.680 --> 00:33:14.080
astronomy, like we'll be able
to find new stars.

00:33:14.160 --> 00:33:16.800
I think we haven't even
touched the frontier,

00:33:16.880 --> 00:33:18.520
what these models can do.

00:33:18.600 --> 00:33:23.200
And then we're only limited by like,
compute energy and like, essentially data,

00:33:23.280 --> 00:33:26.640
which I think, continue
to be the three modes that

00:33:26.720 --> 00:33:28.960
kind of continue along
with models perspective.

00:33:29.040 --> 00:33:30.040
Anything else?

00:33:31.360 --> 00:33:34.440
I think we just,
you know, I think everybody

00:33:34.520 --> 00:33:37.680
talks about AGI and ASI
as this like one moment.

00:33:37.760 --> 00:33:41.480
I think my hot take would be like,
AGI is kind of already here,

00:33:41.560 --> 00:33:44.040
but like humans, like,
when we take a Waymo ride,

00:33:44.120 --> 00:33:46.360
the first time, it's mind-blowing to us.

00:33:46.440 --> 00:33:49.640
And then the next time you just kind of
like on your phone checking Twitter.

00:33:49.720 --> 00:33:51.520
I think we're already there
with these models today,

00:33:51.600 --> 00:33:55.880
but these models are smarter
than most humans already.

00:33:55.960 --> 00:33:59.880
And we've kind of just been like,
"Whatever", kind of like walked away.

00:33:59.960 --> 00:34:02.440
And I think this is why
