00:35:36.960 --> 00:35:38.680
like, will self-driving cars
make it to India?

00:35:38.760 --> 00:35:42.200
-Or will it be able to?
-Let's say a robot has to make a sandwich.

00:35:42.280 --> 00:35:44.880
-Yeah.
-Does it have to train on some visual data

00:35:44.960 --> 00:35:47.240
that will be a job for someone else?

00:35:48.080 --> 00:35:49.360
The training part?

00:35:49.440 --> 00:35:51.200
-Yeah.
-It depends.

00:35:51.280 --> 00:35:53.400
There's a couple of different ways
that people do it.

00:35:53.480 --> 00:35:55.920
There's this whole technique
called Sim-to-Real where,

00:35:56.000 --> 00:35:58.240
you know, you try to simulate
it as much as you can.

00:35:58.320 --> 00:36:00.360
But then it's impossible
to simulate the physical world

00:36:00.440 --> 00:36:03.120
and then you typically
get other sources of data.

00:36:03.200 --> 00:36:06.120
And yes, there are some,
as far as I understand,

00:36:06.200 --> 00:36:07.560
maybe you know more,

00:36:07.640 --> 00:36:11.520
here are labellers that will label
this data in various companies.

00:36:11.600 --> 00:36:15.400
And those labellers can be sometimes
in India, sometimes elsewhere. Yeah.

00:36:15.480 --> 00:36:18.920
In Philippines, like, I mean,
that's where Scale's biggest market.

00:36:19.000 --> 00:36:23.360
Like, there are towns where it's almost
like a night and day difference.

00:36:23.440 --> 00:36:26.120
There are towns
where it's like light all night.

00:36:26.200 --> 00:36:30.560
