But it's especially stark, even if you go
as far as South Korea,

00:39:17.320 --> 00:39:19.440
in two generations,

00:39:19.520 --> 00:39:23.720
that country may be like a tenth
or less of the population it is today.

00:39:24.600 --> 00:39:26.080
It's really bad.

00:39:26.160 --> 00:39:27.720
But that has anything to do with AI?

00:39:27.800 --> 00:39:31.080
It has a lot to do with the economy
and it has a lot to do with AI.

00:39:31.160 --> 00:39:32.160
How?

00:39:33.080 --> 00:39:36.360
I mean, I'd love to explore this
with all of you guys.

00:39:36.440 --> 00:39:37.880
It's not a very well-formed thought

00:39:37.960 --> 00:39:40.440
and I'm not an expert
in this by any means.

00:39:40.520 --> 00:39:43.000
But a lot of economic growth

00:39:43.080 --> 00:39:48.120
is subtly tied in
with the growth of the population.

00:39:48.200 --> 00:39:50.200
The growth of consumption overall.

00:39:50.280 --> 00:39:54.120
I mean, AI is no good unless you have
somebody using something at the other end.

00:39:55.800 --> 00:39:58.240
Transactions have to be done
for economic value

00:39:58.320 --> 00:39:59.720
for everyone to be prosperous.

00:39:59.800 --> 00:40:03.800
And so if we see a world where
there's this rapid decline in population,

00:40:03.880 --> 00:40:05.320
what does that mean for the economy?

00:40:05.400 --> 00:40:07.680
What does that mean for, like,
clothing stores?

00:40:07.760 --> 00:40:09.480
Are you going to be able
to sell clothing any more?

00:40:09.560 --> 00:40:10.960
Or are you going to sell much less?

00:40:11.040 --> 00:40:13.680
What happens to the stock
of that business?

00:40:13.760 --> 00:40:14.760
So I don't know.

00:40:14.840 --> 00:40:18.760
I think that's a less explored problem,
but it's going to be a slow burn.

00:40:18.840 --> 00:40:21.120
But it's something that, you know, has...

00:40:21.200 --> 00:40:23.840
The transactions have to go up
for productivity to go up?

00:40:23.920 --> 00:40:25.920
What if the value of the transaction goes?

00:40:26.640 --> 00:40:27.640
It's possible.

00:40:28.560 --> 00:40:34.920
I think the amount that productivity,
there's an economic definition,

00:40:35.000 --> 00:40:36.760
I guess, and then just
the general definition.

00:40:36.840 --> 00:40:41.320
To go up, to counteract this effect
is, I think, somewhat unrealistic,

00:40:41.400 --> 00:40:43.240
but again, I'm not an economist.

00:40:43.320 --> 00:40:44.520
So I don't know.

00:40:44.600 --> 00:40:50.360
And how does AI exaggerate
birth-rate decline?

00:40:50.440 --> 00:40:53.480
I don't think necessarily
has anything to do with AI.

00:40:53.560 --> 00:40:57.240
-I think there is a...
-There is a very clear chart.

00:40:57.320 --> 00:41:01.800
Like, essentially, 2009,
it started declining.

00:41:01.880 --> 00:41:04.840
We all know what launched in 2009,
which was the iPhone.

00:41:04.920 --> 00:41:11.240
So it's not AI as much like our addiction
to digital media and phones in general.

00:41:11.320 --> 00:41:12.400
And AI will be--

00:41:12.480 --> 00:41:14.600
People are having less kids
because of iPhones.

00:41:14.680 --> 00:41:17.880
I mean, there's no...
You can't directly...

00:41:17.960 --> 00:41:19.680
You can't directly point to it, right?

00:41:19.760 --> 00:41:22.280
There's no research that is that clear.

00:41:22.360 --> 00:41:24.680
But it is, like, 2009 across the world.

00:41:24.760 --> 00:41:26.040
And it's because, like, we're just

00:41:26.120 --> 00:41:29.360
becoming more and more
dependent on our digital...

00:41:29.440 --> 00:41:33.440
Our emotional needs are being satisfied
by more on the digital side,

00:41:33.520 --> 00:41:35.640
whether it's, like, you know,
us watching YouTube shorts

00:41:35.720 --> 00:41:37.880
versus going to a bar
to, like, date someone.

00:41:37.960 --> 00:41:41.720
And I think AI will accelerate
this problem for sure.

00:41:41.800 --> 00:41:44.440
Like, again, I do think we're...

00:41:44.520 --> 00:41:48.520
we're confiding more in ChatGPT
than we talk to, like, our closest humans,

00:41:48.600 --> 00:41:50.520
including, like, our own partners.

00:41:50.600 --> 00:41:54.000
And I do think that has happened.

00:41:54.080 --> 00:41:58.360
And there's no... there's no way that
you can ever draw a direct line,

00:41:58.440 --> 00:42:03.040
but the trend is clear starting
when the mobile phone came out.

00:42:03.120 --> 00:42:07.960
Young people now have less sex
because they're addicted to their phone.

00:42:09.080 --> 00:42:13.120
And, you know, they don't even
know how to interact with another human,

00:42:13.200 --> 00:42:16.640
especially in the...
in the post-COVID world.

00:42:16.720 --> 00:42:18.440
You could see it with younger people

00:42:18.520 --> 00:42:21.800
who missed out on school for,
like, a year or two.

00:42:21.880 --> 00:42:23.160
And they were having a hard time

00:42:23.240 --> 00:42:25.960
interacting with other people
in the offline world.

00:42:27.320 --> 00:42:29.280
So when you have, you know, less sex

00:42:29.360 --> 00:42:31.840
or you end up having it
much later in life,

00:42:31.920 --> 00:42:35.240
and you get a lot of the dopamine
from digital experiences,

00:42:35.320 --> 00:42:38.760
what does it mean, you know, for like,
the fertility rate,

00:42:38.840 --> 00:42:44.200
what does it mean for a lot
of the vice-powered industries

00:42:44.280 --> 00:42:46.960
in a world where, in the US and the West,

00:42:47.040 --> 00:42:49.320
and then you have Ozempic
doing really well?

00:42:49.400 --> 00:42:52.800
What does it mean for suppressing
other vices beyond those, like, you know,

00:42:52.880 --> 00:42:54.600
excessive, you know, eating?

00:42:54.680 --> 00:42:55.920
So that stuff is, like, very interesting

00:42:56.000 --> 00:42:58.360
to just think about, like,
the secondary effects

00:42:58.440 --> 00:43:00.280
that are very hard to imagine.

00:43:00.360 --> 00:43:03.880
Because, for example, you know,
like, the go-back to tech with AVs, right?

00:43:03.960 --> 00:43:05.400
If AVs are everywhere,

00:43:05.480 --> 00:43:08.080
what does it mean, you know,
for the economy around gas stations,

00:43:08.160 --> 00:43:10.120
or Costco, or, like, you know,

00:43:10.200 --> 00:43:13.160
anyone who's applying stuff
to parking lots?

00:43:13.240 --> 00:43:15.280
I have no idea, you know?

00:43:15.360 --> 00:43:17.640
There might be, in this country,
amazing businesses, you know,

00:43:17.720 --> 00:43:22.680
that are supplying products and services
to these hub verticals.

00:43:24.400 --> 00:43:27.280
And, yeah, the rate is dramatically
accelerating.

00:43:27.360 --> 00:43:30.560
For the first time,
there is a new form of intelligence,

00:43:30.640 --> 00:43:32.960
that is going to be on par,

00:43:33.040 --> 00:43:34.720
or, over time,
superior to a lot of the stuff

00:43:34.800 --> 00:43:37.400
that we as humans, you know, can do.

00:43:37.480 --> 00:43:41.160
So, you know, if you can borrow ideas from
the world of sci-fi, what does it mean?

00:43:41.240 --> 00:43:44.360
Does it mean that we're going to
somehow fade in the background?

00:43:44.440 --> 00:43:48.320
We're going to be, like, the same way
that we have pets or cats and dogs.

00:43:48.400 --> 00:43:52.240
Right now, AI will love us,
and will feed us.

00:43:52.320 --> 00:43:57.600
AI will assume the means of production,
will have universal basic income.

00:43:57.680 --> 00:43:59.880
We'll be happy. Maybe we'll start
having more sex. I don't know.

00:43:59.960 --> 00:44:02.640
Maybe the NBA will have 10,000 teams.

00:44:02.720 --> 00:44:06.320
Maybe everyone will be a supermodel,
do sports, or become a poet.

00:44:06.960 --> 00:44:08.440
But then, all the important decisions

00:44:08.520 --> 00:44:11.560
around running the world,
allocating resources.

00:44:11.640 --> 00:44:16.280
This new form of intelligence is going
to make these decisions, take over.

00:44:17.480 --> 00:44:20.160
And, you know,
there's going to be the new species

00:44:20.240 --> 00:44:22.160
that write the history books.

00:44:22.240 --> 00:44:23.240
Who knows?

00:44:23.920 --> 00:44:26.200
It's a bit like a democracy

00:44:27.520 --> 00:44:31.520
and a smarter, benevolent,
maybe benevolent dictator on top.

00:44:31.600 --> 00:44:32.680
Yeah.

00:44:32.760 --> 00:44:34.120
Is it important that we are making

00:44:34.200 --> 00:44:36.960
the decisions if something smarter
is more capable?

00:44:37.040 --> 00:44:39.880
There are a lot of questions that,

00:44:39.960 --> 00:44:42.680
you know, this question
raises here, right?

00:44:42.760 --> 00:44:46.480
One of the good news is that AI is still
today's powered with electricity.

00:44:46.560 --> 00:44:49.120
So, if we're unhappy,
we'll unplug it and we're good, right?

00:44:49.200 --> 00:44:51.680
Because the battery technology
is not that sophisticated,

00:44:51.760 --> 00:44:53.520
you know, and during, yeah...

00:44:55.440 --> 00:44:57.920
But, yeah, it does matter a lot, you know,

00:44:58.000 --> 00:45:03.480
who are the creators of this super
powerful pieces of software and systems.

00:45:03.560 --> 00:45:08.320
Because if they themselves, you know,
are all made of the same cloth,

00:45:08.400 --> 00:45:10.000
and they have group think.

00:45:10.080 --> 00:45:11.720
They won't be able to cover

00:45:11.800 --> 00:45:16.080
a lot of the different voices

00:45:16.160 --> 00:45:20.560
that humans from all over the planet
and different backgrounds might have.

00:45:21.560 --> 00:45:24.560
And, unfortunately,
you know, for the world,

00:45:24.640 --> 00:45:26.840
tech is moving really quickly.

00:45:26.920 --> 00:45:29.000
Policy cannot catch up.

00:45:29.080 --> 00:45:32.040
Like the hardest thing, honestly,
that we face right now

00:45:32.120 --> 00:45:34.640
is even if you're like a PhD in AI,

00:45:34.720 --> 00:45:37.160
working for one of the foundation

00:45:37.240 --> 00:45:40.560
model companies,
you can't keep up with the pace.

00:45:40.640 --> 00:45:42.720
This is the single hardest thing.

00:45:42.800 --> 00:45:45.880
So, imagine being, you know,
like a policy maker

00:45:45.960 --> 00:45:49.320
or somebody who thinks
about that stuff all day long.

00:45:50.640 --> 00:45:51.760
How do you keep up?

00:45:53.040 --> 00:45:55.720
And, you know, the tech is improving in
the background.

00:45:56.560 --> 00:45:58.480
This is really tricky.

00:45:58.560 --> 00:46:01.240
Do you personally believe
the world will get there?

00:46:01.320 --> 00:46:04.040
Where we've become like cats and dogs
in the background?

00:46:04.120 --> 00:46:06.600
I don't want to believe in that world,

00:46:06.680 --> 00:46:10.240
but is there a scenario
that this might happen?

00:46:10.320 --> 00:46:11.720
Yes, there's a scenario
that this might happen.

00:46:11.800 --> 00:46:13.640
But I think
I have the more optimistic take,

00:46:13.720 --> 00:46:17.160
which is like, see,
since the Industrial Revolution,

00:46:17.240 --> 00:46:19.800
humans have just
known to increase efficiency.

00:46:19.880 --> 00:46:21.680
It's like singular, you know.

00:46:21.760 --> 00:46:23.880
Now it makes sense that you worked
at Khosla Ventures.

00:46:24.960 --> 00:46:28.520
Every year, productivity is going up
a couple of percent.

00:46:28.600 --> 00:46:30.440
And even the internet, you know.

00:46:30.520 --> 00:46:32.680
But the point being
is, like, we've always found a way

00:46:32.760 --> 00:46:35.280
to do more, jobs have come and gone.

00:46:35.360 --> 00:46:37.680
Typewriters used to be a thing,
no longer a thing.

00:46:37.760 --> 00:46:40.480
The pace is accelerating, but the pace
has always been accelerating.

00:46:40.560 --> 00:46:43.640
Maybe it's just an exponential curve,
and that's why we're feeling

00:46:43.720 --> 00:46:45.880
that we're on the roller coaster
on the edge,

00:46:45.960 --> 00:46:47.720
and that's why we're feeling it.

00:46:47.800 --> 00:46:50.560
But I think I believe
in an abundant future,

00:46:50.640 --> 00:46:53.320
where I believe actually,

00:46:53.400 --> 00:46:56.560
like, we'll have more time to do
more leisureful activity.

00:46:56.640 --> 00:46:58.440
The work day might go down

00:46:58.520 --> 00:47:01.120
from 12 hours a day to 6 hours a day,

00:47:01.200 --> 00:47:04.880
and that means we have more time
for art and music and entertainment

00:47:04.960 --> 00:47:08.480
and you know, like,
spending time with, like, our loved ones.

00:47:08.560 --> 00:47:09.800
That's my take on the decision.

00:47:09.880 --> 00:47:11.680
That's like the abundance scenario.

00:47:11.760 --> 00:47:13.640
-It's already happening today.
-It's already happening today.

00:47:13.720 --> 00:47:15.240
-It'll take way more, right?
-Yeah, yeah.

00:47:15.320 --> 00:47:19.080
Before you were behind the steering wheel,
now you are reading, you know,

00:47:19.160 --> 00:47:21.280
this is Twitch...

00:47:21.360 --> 00:47:24.960
But this also happened 2,000 years ago,
say, the Greek society,

00:47:25.040 --> 00:47:27.720
not everybody had to work
because they were doing so well.

00:47:28.480 --> 00:47:29.720
Philosophy was a thing,

00:47:29.800 --> 00:47:33.160
where people sat
and spent their lives philosophising

00:47:33.240 --> 00:47:36.440
what they should believe in,
what they should not believe in.

00:47:36.520 --> 00:47:38.200
Maybe the world goes there, no?

00:47:38.280 --> 00:47:41.440
It will, yeah, there will be 10,000 teams
in the NBA, as I said.

00:47:41.520 --> 00:47:44.080
We're all going to be
philosophers and poets.

00:47:44.160 --> 00:47:45.600
Maybe we'll have a lot more sex,

00:47:45.680 --> 00:47:49.280
and we can live like our own
version of Brian Johnson.

00:47:49.360 --> 00:47:50.920
It will live for like 2,000 years.

00:47:51.800 --> 00:47:53.000
Might very well happen.

00:47:53.080 --> 00:47:56.760
I'm a bit more apprehensive
on the abundance situation,

00:47:56.840 --> 00:48:00.200
because I think the abundance narrative--

00:48:00.280 --> 00:48:02.760
There will always be certain people
with less resources.

00:48:02.840 --> 00:48:06.800
And as long as you have less resources,
you will want more resources.

00:48:06.880 --> 00:48:11.560
And so the abundance mindset,
I think, is a luxury of a few.

00:48:11.640 --> 00:48:14.320
And there is no way
you can convince somebody

00:48:14.400 --> 00:48:17.720
who grows up from a, I don't know,
poverty-stricken family in India.

00:48:17.800 --> 00:48:19.440
-You can't convince somebody--
-Before you go ahead...

00:48:19.520 --> 00:48:20.720
Yeah?

00:48:20.800 --> 00:48:24.720
Does abundance hit proportionately

00:48:24.800 --> 00:48:27.040
to the modes of capitalism
when there is abundance?

00:48:27.120 --> 00:48:29.800
Absolutely. That's what history
has time and again told us.

00:48:29.880 --> 00:48:31.280
If you read my favorite book,

00:48:31.360 --> 00:48:34.400
Capital in the Twenty-First Century
by Thomas Piketty.

00:48:34.480 --> 00:48:38.520
Every time there is growth
and development, inequality increases,

00:48:38.600 --> 00:48:42.160
I don't think there's very many situations
where that's not the case.

00:48:42.240 --> 00:48:44.240
But he makes a case
for that doughnut economics.

00:48:45.000 --> 00:48:47.440
The marginal utility of money
beyond a point.

00:48:47.520 --> 00:48:48.880
-Yes.
-That's what's done.

00:48:48.960 --> 00:48:50.720
That's correct. And...

00:48:50.800 --> 00:48:52.920
But despite that, I mean,

00:48:53.000 --> 00:48:56.440
I think still think we have
a very far gap to fill before,

00:48:56.520 --> 00:49:00.600
you know, the entirety of society
is above the point

00:49:00.680 --> 00:49:02.960
where the marginal amount
of money means nothing.

00:49:03.040 --> 00:49:05.440
And we see it in a little bit, right?

00:49:05.520 --> 00:49:08.600
There are people who... I mean,
I think about this all the time.

00:49:08.680 --> 00:49:09.720
But also think about this.

00:49:09.800 --> 00:49:13.880
You were just saying fertility rates
are dropping such that

00:49:13.960 --> 00:49:17.280
countries and two generations will have
one-tenth the number of people there.

00:49:17.360 --> 00:49:19.200
So that changes everything too, right?

00:49:19.280 --> 00:49:20.800
-Yeah.
-But let's talk about that.

00:49:20.880 --> 00:49:22.840
What if we have the artificial womb?

00:49:22.920 --> 00:49:25.680
And just have a baby through a surrogate.

00:49:25.760 --> 00:49:28.680
I mean, I'm in my early 40s,
my wife is in her early 40s,

00:49:28.760 --> 00:49:30.080
honestly, it's fucking amazing.

00:49:30.160 --> 00:49:33.480
I think we need to make
having kids cool again.

00:49:33.560 --> 00:49:35.720
-Yes.
-It's not as much about incentives.

00:49:35.800 --> 00:49:37.960
But it's more about the narrative.

00:49:38.040 --> 00:49:41.120
So if we're all to become
a lot more religious...

00:49:41.200 --> 00:49:42.480
Hmm.

00:49:42.560 --> 00:49:46.040
This perhaps would mean that you would
get married, you know, earlier.

00:49:46.120 --> 00:49:50.960
This would probably mean that
for the religion to propagate,

00:49:51.040 --> 00:49:53.320
you would have more kids earlier.

00:49:53.400 --> 00:49:55.440
-Yeah.
-So one of the reasons, for example,

00:49:55.520 --> 00:49:57.280
why in Latin America?

00:49:58.040 --> 00:50:01.400
The fertility rates decline
is some of the steepest in the world.

00:50:01.480 --> 00:50:04.680
It's because Catholicism
in many of these countries

00:50:04.760 --> 00:50:08.880
is not as cool as it used to
be in the previous decades.

00:50:08.960 --> 00:50:12.480
So would you bet on religion making
a comeback because it ought to?

00:50:12.560 --> 00:50:14.480
-I think it is making a comeback.
-It's coming back.

00:50:14.560 --> 00:50:17.960
Yeah. And part of the reason
is after, like, 15 years,

00:50:18.040 --> 00:50:21.160
of being stuck on a small screen,

00:50:21.240 --> 00:50:23.400
and after, you know, 20 years of going to,

00:50:23.480 --> 00:50:26.520
Equinox, Barre-Bootcamp
or whatever, you know,

00:50:26.600 --> 00:50:29.760
these institutions are for you,
depending on where you live.

00:50:30.480 --> 00:50:33.040
You're trying to find other places
that have a meaning.

00:50:33.120 --> 00:50:36.040
By the way, there might be an AI religion
that gets formed.

00:50:36.120 --> 00:50:37.800
-Mm-hmm.
-Who knows.

00:50:37.880 --> 00:50:44.280
That is gonna fulfill the emotional
needs that some humans might have.

00:50:44.360 --> 00:50:46.760
But yeah, I do think religion
is making a comeback.

00:50:46.840 --> 00:50:48.840
I think it's all about
a search for meaning.

00:50:48.920 --> 00:50:51.800
That's where, like,
I go back on the abundant side.

00:50:51.880 --> 00:50:54.520
Search for meaning
eventually ends up coming

00:50:54.600 --> 00:50:56.960
with people and the byproducts of people.

00:50:57.040 --> 00:51:00.040
Not from a kite's perspective
but whatever you end up doing.

00:51:00.120 --> 00:51:03.520
And I think if...
going back to the poverty side,

00:51:03.600 --> 00:51:05.560
like, I think we live in a place

00:51:05.640 --> 00:51:08.960
where more people die of, like,
calorie surplus than negative.

00:51:09.040 --> 00:51:12.040
I think that's now... that's why
Ozempic is doing so well.

00:51:12.120 --> 00:51:14.480
Like, obesity is the number one killer
rather than...

00:51:14.560 --> 00:51:16.920
I know that's not what
you were trying to say.

00:51:17.000 --> 00:51:20.600
But I think, going back to that point,
we already live in an abundant future.

00:51:20.680 --> 00:51:23.560
Where I don't think...
and the income disparity I agree with.

00:51:23.640 --> 00:51:25.280
That is my number one fear.

00:51:25.360 --> 00:51:27.320
But I don't know
what the solution there is.

00:51:27.400 --> 00:51:30.640
Because UBI experiment has been tried.

00:51:30.720 --> 00:51:34.440
It'll be interesting to see as that gap
goes bigger, what happens.

00:51:34.520 --> 00:51:36.520
Yeah, I actually agree
with all of your points.

00:51:36.600 --> 00:51:39.320
My only difference is
the search for meaning

00:51:39.400 --> 00:51:42.520
in the Maslow Hierarchy of Needs,
is after a couple of other things.

00:51:42.600 --> 00:51:44.840
-Sure.
-And it's not always just about...

00:51:44.920 --> 00:51:49.000
It's about...
I think human's own perception of status.

00:51:49.080 --> 00:51:50.280
-Sure.
