If you're like an immigrant yourself,
or you're somebody affluent,

01:18:02.840 --> 01:18:04.640
of course, do care a lot about it.

01:18:06.040 --> 01:18:08.080
-Yeah.
-Every society

01:18:08.160 --> 01:18:10.680
in the past that has achieved
pinnacle status

01:18:10.760 --> 01:18:12.800
has always shifted to arts and culture

01:18:12.880 --> 01:18:17.800
as their way to spend time,
whether it's sports or something else.

01:18:17.880 --> 01:18:21.480
And in America, it's a very
sports-oriented culture more than it is

01:18:21.560 --> 01:18:23.480
an education-oriented culture,
like you said,

01:18:23.560 --> 01:18:25.760
I don't know too many, you know.

01:18:25.840 --> 01:18:28.320
Can I ask you guys to give it a rating?
One to ten.

01:18:28.400 --> 01:18:29.640
-This one.
-Yeah.

01:18:29.720 --> 01:18:31.440
The education one?

01:18:32.640 --> 01:18:33.960
Eight or nine.

01:18:34.040 --> 01:18:35.040
Okay.

01:18:35.680 --> 01:18:37.760
-Same?
-I'm like a ten.

01:18:37.840 --> 01:18:40.640
You come from a country
that's on the up and up?

01:18:40.720 --> 01:18:41.720
Yeah.

01:18:41.800 --> 01:18:43.960
Okay. Nikunj?

01:18:44.040 --> 01:18:45.680
Outcome-focused education, yeah.

01:18:46.400 --> 01:18:49.320
-It'll be the... it is the future.
-Number?

01:18:49.400 --> 01:18:50.680
Nine.

01:18:50.760 --> 01:18:52.280
Okay.

01:18:52.360 --> 01:18:56.280
Secondary markets for private companies
will become a big thing.

01:18:56.360 --> 01:18:57.440
Ten.

01:18:59.400 --> 01:19:01.760
Again, these are moments
in time, right?

01:19:01.840 --> 01:19:07.680
Because there are moments when regulators
and incentives are aligning

01:19:07.760 --> 01:19:11.600
for public markets to be open

01:19:11.680 --> 01:19:14.640
and to welcome companies
at a much earlier stage.

01:19:14.720 --> 01:19:17.240
There are other moments
that this is not the case.

01:19:17.320 --> 01:19:22.360
So, at the moment, you know,
we're living during a time

01:19:22.440 --> 01:19:28.640
where a lot of the value is captured
by private investors on the way up.

01:19:28.720 --> 01:19:32.960
Like, you now see quite a few companies
that are worth $100 billion plus.

01:19:33.600 --> 01:19:36.480
Whereas back in the day, you know,
this was not the case.

01:19:36.560 --> 01:19:38.880
Like when Facebook went public
and was valued,

01:19:38.960 --> 01:19:40.760
and they won over $100 billion.

01:19:40.840 --> 01:19:45.440
I think they were the first ones ever,
you know, to do that in 2012.

01:19:46.280 --> 01:19:49.400
And could you also argue that, tomorrow,

01:19:49.480 --> 01:19:52.000
a lot more really large companies

01:19:52.080 --> 01:19:56.520
will want to avoid a circumvent
taking retail money

01:19:56.600 --> 01:19:59.280
because they'll have to be over-regulated
if they do?

01:20:00.080 --> 01:20:04.000
If indeed, you know, they have to be
over-regulated and they have a choice

01:20:04.720 --> 01:20:07.240
because they can get funding
from other places,

01:20:07.320 --> 01:20:08.720
yeah, they might avoid.

01:20:08.800 --> 01:20:11.800
But if we bring down
the regulatory constraints

01:20:11.880 --> 01:20:15.080
or capital from other sources
becomes more scarce,

01:20:15.160 --> 01:20:16.200
this could be an option.

01:20:16.280 --> 01:20:19.600
For me, somebody who lives in the U.S.,

01:20:19.680 --> 01:20:22.560
it's actually sad
that the retail investor,

01:20:22.640 --> 01:20:28.000
the pension funds, the low fees, ETFs,

01:20:28.080 --> 01:20:31.760
cannot have access to some of this wealth,
you know, sooner or rather than later.

01:20:31.840 --> 01:20:35.560
It's sad, 100%. But I don't think
it's changing anytime soon, right?

01:20:37.400 --> 01:20:40.720
At the moment, it looks like it's not
going to change anytime soon, yeah.

01:20:41.560 --> 01:20:43.800
Yeah, it's like eight or nine.

01:20:43.880 --> 01:20:46.480
There's this access.

01:20:47.640 --> 01:20:51.160
I think if you think about, like,
imbalance in the future or disparity,

01:20:51.240 --> 01:20:53.920
like, access becomes the primary thing

01:20:54.000 --> 01:20:56.720
that only a few people have,
and that's the sad aspect.

01:20:56.800 --> 01:20:58.560
And access will be gatekept.

01:20:58.640 --> 01:20:59.800
Yeah, access will be gatekept.

01:20:59.880 --> 01:21:05.080
And I think that's the sad aspect,
but do I see it changing anytime soon?

01:21:05.160 --> 01:21:07.320
No. Incentives are just not aligned.

01:21:07.400 --> 01:21:09.280
Do you guys
want to rate the statement? Niko?

01:21:10.280 --> 01:21:13.240
Secondary markets, secondary markets,
marketplaces.

01:21:13.320 --> 01:21:15.600
They're gonna be strong forever.

01:21:15.680 --> 01:21:17.480
For the next 10 years.

01:21:17.560 --> 01:21:19.520
Yeah, I think so. Five. Yeah.

01:21:19.600 --> 01:21:21.520
-Five?
-Yeah.

01:21:21.600 --> 01:21:23.320
-Deedy.
-I'd say ten.

01:21:23.400 --> 01:21:25.280
-Ten?
-I don't see it changing.

01:21:25.360 --> 01:21:28.360
-Nikunj?
-Let's split the middle. Take seven.

01:21:28.440 --> 01:21:30.880
I think I don't...
I think it'll change.

01:21:30.960 --> 01:21:33.480
I think it'll change in the...
start of next decade.

01:21:34.720 --> 01:21:37.440
The world will be older and sicker.

01:21:38.600 --> 01:21:42.600
Wellness, hospitalisation, longevity,
great sectors to be in.

01:21:42.680 --> 01:21:45.440
I think they're two different statements,
in my opinion.

01:21:45.520 --> 01:21:46.760
[Nikhil] Explain.

01:21:46.840 --> 01:21:49.040
I don't think you...

01:21:50.240 --> 01:21:53.680
I don't believe the world
will be older and sicker.

01:21:54.480 --> 01:21:55.720
Why not?

01:21:55.800 --> 01:21:59.000
I mean, we're constantly improve--

01:21:59.080 --> 01:22:04.160
First, I believe, as Deedy mentioned,
biotech is the application area

01:22:04.240 --> 01:22:08.960
where I do believe us discovering
new things will be the most...

01:22:09.040 --> 01:22:11.240
Like, literally, one sector
where we'll discover the most things

01:22:11.320 --> 01:22:13.320
where AI will be useful, it's biotech.

01:22:13.400 --> 01:22:16.000
And I think that will help transform

01:22:16.080 --> 01:22:19.240
most of the common diseases, why we die.

01:22:20.400 --> 01:22:24.360
Ozempic is already doing it with
obesity, which is a huge factor.

01:22:24.440 --> 01:22:25.960
So, I do think we'll live longer,

01:22:27.040 --> 01:22:28.360
and, like, healthier.

01:22:29.480 --> 01:22:30.840
But I do think
that will take investments...

01:22:30.920 --> 01:22:33.280
Longer and...

01:22:33.360 --> 01:22:34.960
That is agreed. World will be older.

01:22:35.040 --> 01:22:36.680
If you live longer, world will be older.

01:22:36.760 --> 01:22:38.280
-Yeah, so that's why I said older--
-Sicker?

01:22:38.360 --> 01:22:39.800
No, and not sicker. Yeah.

01:22:39.880 --> 01:22:43.400
And then, average, like, if we think about
median happiness years...

01:22:43.480 --> 01:22:46.560
Let's put it, like,
in a philosophical way.

01:22:46.640 --> 01:22:49.520
No, I'm more thinking how many people
are sick at one point of time,

01:22:49.600 --> 01:22:51.560
'cause money can be made
by treating them.

01:22:54.480 --> 01:22:56.200
-You wanna answer that?
-Go for it. Yeah.

01:22:56.280 --> 01:22:59.400
I was gonna be pretty strong on this one.

01:22:59.480 --> 01:23:03.200
I mean, just, again, this is a side-effect
of birth rate decline.

01:23:03.280 --> 01:23:05.080
So, it's birth rates decline,

01:23:05.160 --> 01:23:09.840
the demographic imbalance will switch
to having more older people.

01:23:09.920 --> 01:23:12.280
I think, yeah, Nikunj, you're right.

01:23:12.360 --> 01:23:14.960
I mean, you have to debate the baseline
of what "sicker" means, but...

01:23:15.040 --> 01:23:16.640
Yes. Yeah.
That's what I was thinking, too.

01:23:16.720 --> 01:23:19.320
Generally, if you're talking about
the world being sicker

01:23:19.400 --> 01:23:22.520
because there are more older people,
and older people are generally sicker,

01:23:22.600 --> 01:23:24.440
yeah, I mean, that is factual.

01:23:24.520 --> 01:23:26.920
Also, we've just come out of COVID.

01:23:27.000 --> 01:23:29.040
After many, many decades,
we had something like that.

01:23:29.120 --> 01:23:30.200
Maybe there'll be more.

01:23:30.280 --> 01:23:33.800
Perhaps, but even without that,
I would say the world is...

01:23:33.880 --> 01:23:35.200
Older people get sicker.

01:23:35.280 --> 01:23:37.320
People will be older,
therefore, people will be sicker.

01:23:37.400 --> 01:23:40.280
And then longevity, wellness,
and all of that... very important.

01:23:40.360 --> 01:23:42.520
Also, because of how connected we are
right now,

01:23:42.600 --> 01:23:47.040
when something transmissible
comes about next,

01:23:47.120 --> 01:23:49.440
we'd all get it much faster
than we did historically.

01:23:49.520 --> 01:23:51.160
-That's why I say "sicker".
-Oh, yeah.

01:23:51.240 --> 01:23:54.080
I was sitting with somebody
from Moderna last week,

01:23:54.160 --> 01:23:57.200
and they were saying
we got really close with bird flu,

01:23:57.280 --> 01:23:59.640
but the world has gotten to a point,

01:23:59.720 --> 01:24:03.240
where if I have something
which is moderately infectious,

01:24:03.320 --> 01:24:07.480
the odds of the last person in the world
not catching it are low today.

01:24:07.560 --> 01:24:11.640
But I think we'll be able to come up
with an antidote faster,

01:24:11.720 --> 01:24:13.640
and distribute it faster also.

01:24:13.720 --> 01:24:16.480
I think that's the corollary
that I don't think we get, like...

01:24:16.560 --> 01:24:19.520
COVID would have been
much worse without mRNA.

01:24:19.600 --> 01:24:23.080
A lot of these things that didn't exist,
like, 10, 15 years ago.

01:24:23.160 --> 01:24:24.920
And I think that pace
is only going to accelerate.

01:24:25.000 --> 01:24:26.920
So that's what I was trying to understand.

01:24:27.000 --> 01:24:30.280
I think the acceleration
of us making things better.

01:24:30.360 --> 01:24:33.960
Let me put it more specifically,
I think the ambiguity goes away.

01:24:34.040 --> 01:24:36.280
In 2035,

01:24:36.360 --> 01:24:40.560
I'm reviewing the portfolio
that is being invested in today.

01:24:40.640 --> 01:24:43.440
Will the business of treating sick people
have done well by then?

01:24:43.520 --> 01:24:44.880
I think we're rating that.

01:24:46.840 --> 01:24:52.080
I mean, in the US, it's already, what,
19% of US GDP goes in healthcare.

01:24:52.160 --> 01:24:53.360
That number will go up?

01:24:53.440 --> 01:24:54.640
Hundred percent!

01:24:54.720 --> 01:24:56.520
-Yeah, that.
-Yeah.

01:24:56.600 --> 01:24:59.160
The number will go up.
Does it mean it's a good business?

01:24:59.240 --> 01:25:00.240
Yes, exactly.

01:25:00.320 --> 01:25:05.160
Because, like,
if you are in healthcare services or...

01:25:05.240 --> 01:25:08.960
you run hospital stuff,
most of them are not great businesses.

01:25:10.560 --> 01:25:13.880
However, you know, if you find ways
to bend the cost curve...

01:25:13.960 --> 01:25:17.800
Oh, my God, amazing.
All the trends are on your side.

01:25:17.880 --> 01:25:19.800
-Yeah.
-[Nikhil] Yeah.

01:25:19.880 --> 01:25:22.520
I suspect there are better businesses
outside of the US,

01:25:22.600 --> 01:25:25.880
because the US has a problem
which is very unique to itself.

01:25:25.960 --> 01:25:27.240
Right. That's right.

01:25:27.320 --> 01:25:29.520
Like, the multiples of hospital companies
in India

01:25:29.600 --> 01:25:31.320
are like, a hundred times, profit.

01:25:32.880 --> 01:25:35.080
Especially if you've been able
to build a brand around it.

01:25:35.160 --> 01:25:37.880
Would you like to rate this, Niko?
Older, sicker world.

01:25:39.000 --> 01:25:42.240
I think older, yes.

01:25:42.320 --> 01:25:45.560
Sicker... It's a definition thing,
but, like, no.

01:25:45.640 --> 01:25:50.240
Is this market going to become
much bigger between now and 2035?

01:25:50.320 --> 01:25:51.960
Yes. It's like a nine, you know.

01:25:53.920 --> 01:25:55.320
Nine.

01:25:55.400 --> 01:25:57.080
-Nikunj?
-Yeah. Eight.

01:25:58.840 --> 01:26:00.240
Senior living.

01:26:00.320 --> 01:26:02.760
This is something we invested in,
funnily enough.

01:26:04.360 --> 01:26:06.760
Me and Hemant did this deal together.

01:26:07.840 --> 01:26:09.640
We did a couple in senior living.

01:26:09.720 --> 01:26:10.720
Were you a part of that?

01:26:11.360 --> 01:26:13.560
I'm aware of it,
but I was not part of it, no.

01:26:13.640 --> 01:26:15.160
-Yeah.
-Thoughts?

01:26:15.840 --> 01:26:19.320
The world will be older...
senior living, affluent senior living.

01:26:19.400 --> 01:26:24.160
Well, some of the fastest growing cities
in the US are the villages in Florida.

01:26:24.240 --> 01:26:26.040
So, if there's something to be said,
you know,

01:26:26.120 --> 01:26:28.720
about that model expanding
to other countries...

01:26:30.960 --> 01:26:36.440
I think, you know, this one has,
like, very awesome long-term prospects.

01:26:36.520 --> 01:26:40.640
And especially in the developing world,
as people become...

01:26:40.720 --> 01:26:42.160
more affluent,

01:26:42.240 --> 01:26:43.960
their kids are fewer,

01:26:44.040 --> 01:26:47.120
they don't live with them,
but they move for economic opportunity

01:26:47.200 --> 01:26:49.960
in other parts of the country,
or other parts of the world,

01:26:50.960 --> 01:26:55.280
you need, as you age,
to be close to other elderly people,

01:26:55.360 --> 01:27:00.960
and/or individuals
who are going to be able to help you.

01:27:01.040 --> 01:27:04.320
This particular deal that we did together
is a company called Primus.

01:27:05.160 --> 01:27:07.960
And the data he was showing us is,

01:27:08.040 --> 01:27:12.280
if a 70-year-old man or woman
is at his facility,

01:27:12.360 --> 01:27:15.160
which is a very affluent, like,
high-end senior living facility,

01:27:16.560 --> 01:27:19.800
the quality of life and...

01:27:20.920 --> 01:27:24.680
the longevity of their life
goes up by a significant premium

01:27:24.760 --> 01:27:26.240
because they have community.

01:27:26.320 --> 01:27:27.320
That's right.

01:27:27.400 --> 01:27:29.360
And he showed me
this really crazy research.

01:27:29.440 --> 01:27:31.560
Like, when my dad was sick,
I got him a nurse.

01:27:31.640 --> 01:27:34.160
So then, he didn't have to do anything.
He didn't have to move.

01:27:34.240 --> 01:27:36.920
Somebody was doing everything for him.

01:27:37.000 --> 01:27:39.640
That's the worst thing you can do
for your parent.

01:27:41.280 --> 01:27:42.400
It's very counter-intuitive.

01:27:42.480 --> 01:27:45.920
But, I think, just that community...

01:27:46.000 --> 01:27:50.760
having to play with someone,
having some competition being organised,

01:27:50.840 --> 01:27:54.160
playing memory games, walking,
all of that,

01:27:54.240 --> 01:27:58.840
with like-aged people changes everything.

01:27:58.920 --> 01:28:02.000
Absolutely, yes.
So, if you read about Blue Zones,

01:28:02.080 --> 01:28:03.720
which are, like,
the different parts of the world

01:28:03.800 --> 01:28:09.440
where they have the highest percentage
of people who are 100 years old-plus,

01:28:09.520 --> 01:28:12.160
the... shared trait

01:28:12.240 --> 01:28:16.120
that they all have to demonstrate
is community.

01:28:16.200 --> 01:28:19.320
So, like in Okinawa in Japan
and Ikaria in Greece,

01:28:19.400 --> 01:28:21.520
and, like, you know, other parts...

01:28:21.600 --> 01:28:23.880
You're somebody, you know,
who's 100 years old,

01:28:23.960 --> 01:28:26.440
your kids might be dead or incapacitated,

01:28:26.520 --> 01:28:30.560
but because, every day, you know,
in your village, you're socialising,

01:28:30.640 --> 01:28:32.440
and you feel like
you have responsibilities,

01:28:32.520 --> 01:28:33.880
this is what keeps you going.

01:28:33.960 --> 01:28:35.800
We rate this highly in India

01:28:35.880 --> 01:28:40.720
even though there is such a big
societal stigma about senior living.

01:28:40.800 --> 01:28:47.000
I think the misconception one has
is at a certain point, with your parent,

01:28:47.080 --> 01:28:50.480
you're almost being selfish
by keeping them at home

01:28:50.560 --> 01:28:55.680
versus allowing them to
make more choices of their own.

01:28:55.760 --> 01:28:56.760
-Right.
-Yeah.

01:28:56.840 --> 01:28:59.160
It's a hard thing, especially in India,
to overcome.

01:28:59.240 --> 01:29:00.360
I don't know how it's in Greece.

01:29:00.440 --> 01:29:01.440
Same.

01:29:01.520 --> 01:29:04.520
But, because in Greece, again, you know...

01:29:04.600 --> 01:29:05.880
the standard of living went up,

01:29:05.960 --> 01:29:10.000
and then the cost of living,
cost of labour also went up,

01:29:10.080 --> 01:29:13.760
what saved a lot of families

01:29:13.840 --> 01:29:18.000
was, like, Eastern European labour talent

01:29:18.080 --> 01:29:21.200
that visited the country
and stayed there as illegal immigrants,

01:29:21.280 --> 01:29:23.080
and then got legalised.

01:29:23.160 --> 01:29:26.600
But, in the beginning, you know,
if you had your kid,

01:29:26.680 --> 01:29:32.960
your elderly parents sent to,
like, a senior living facility,

01:29:33.040 --> 01:29:34.480
everyone would look down on you.

01:29:34.560 --> 01:29:38.480
So, the preferred choice was to have
somebody from Georgia or Romania,

01:29:38.560 --> 01:29:39.880
you know, do the work for you.

01:29:39.960 --> 01:29:42.840
But then, you realised all the stuff
that you mentioned,

01:29:42.920 --> 01:29:47.560
you know, that your dad or mom
wouldn't interact with anyone else.

01:29:47.640 --> 01:29:50.320
The cognitive decline would be faster.

01:29:50.400 --> 01:29:54.080
So, now, you know,
after 30 years of doing what I said,

01:29:54.160 --> 01:29:59.200
some of the much better
senior living businesses

01:29:59.280 --> 01:30:01.760
are looked at more nicely...

01:30:01.840 --> 01:30:03.440
or favourably.

01:30:03.520 --> 01:30:05.480
You guys want to comment on senior living?

01:30:05.560 --> 01:30:07.200
Would you send your parents?

01:30:08.920 --> 01:30:10.880
It's a tough one.

01:30:10.960 --> 01:30:12.440
I would...

01:30:12.520 --> 01:30:15.440
There is some bias against it,
as you said,

01:30:15.520 --> 01:30:18.360
but, you know, maybe that
decision will change over time.

01:30:18.440 --> 01:30:20.680
I think it depends on
what they want to do as well.

01:30:21.480 --> 01:30:24.320
I do think, in my particular case,
I'm lucky

01:30:24.400 --> 01:30:27.280
that they have a good community already
at home.

01:30:27.360 --> 01:30:29.920
So, that does solve
a bunch of the problems,

01:30:30.000 --> 01:30:32.200
but, you know, who knows how this goes.

01:30:32.280 --> 01:30:33.480
But, generally, on your question...

01:30:33.560 --> 01:30:36.520
you know, in the US, very much.

01:30:36.600 --> 01:30:39.560
In the rest of the world, slightly less.

01:30:39.640 --> 01:30:41.600
Just because
there's different dynamics,

01:30:41.680 --> 01:30:45.400
social, intercultural dynamics
in different parts of the world.

01:30:45.480 --> 01:30:47.760
There is also taboo,
things like that.

01:30:47.840 --> 01:30:49.360
So I'm not as sure.

01:30:50.040 --> 01:30:51.760
But, in America, yeah.

01:30:51.840 --> 01:30:53.440
-Nikunj?
-Yeah, I think...

01:30:54.520 --> 01:30:57.160
It's not a question
of me sending our parents,

01:30:57.240 --> 01:30:59.160
like, my parents, luckily...

01:30:59.240 --> 01:31:01.400
My parents and my grandparents
live together.

01:31:01.480 --> 01:31:03.880
And I think that's nice, like,
from a community standpoint.

01:31:03.960 --> 01:31:06.160
And that's very rare,
not many people have that.

01:31:06.240 --> 01:31:08.000
Yeah, we're very lucky that...

01:31:08.960 --> 01:31:11.600
everybody likes each other.

01:31:12.880 --> 01:31:14.000
But...

01:31:14.080 --> 01:31:16.320
it's not a question
of me sending my parents or not.

01:31:16.400 --> 01:31:18.000
It's a question of, like...

01:31:18.080 --> 01:31:20.480
-Them choosing to go.
-...them choosing what to do.

01:31:20.560 --> 01:31:22.200
At the end of the day, we all...

01:31:22.280 --> 01:31:24.320
We're three brothers
who all live in separate houses.

01:31:24.400 --> 01:31:25.480
They live in their own house.

01:31:25.560 --> 01:31:27.120
And what they-- what do they want to do?

01:31:27.200 --> 01:31:29.800
I think it makes sense, like, I...

01:31:30.920 --> 01:31:34.320
I think, both, from a community
standpoint, but from a...

01:31:34.400 --> 01:31:37.600
as labour gets more expensive, like,
economies of scale standpoint as well,

01:31:37.680 --> 01:31:41.920
it just makes sense
for more people at the same stage in life

01:31:42.000 --> 01:31:43.040
to live together.

01:31:43.120 --> 01:31:45.600
Would you guys like to rate the statement?
Niko?

01:31:45.680 --> 01:31:46.760
Senior living?

01:31:47.760 --> 01:31:49.320
I'm like a nine.

01:31:49.400 --> 01:31:50.400
Eight.

01:31:51.200 --> 01:31:52.200
Yeah. Nine.

01:31:52.880 --> 01:31:56.840
Unless there are infectious diseases,
like COVID, you know...

01:31:56.920 --> 01:31:57.920
Yeah. I get that.

01:31:58.000 --> 01:31:59.880
...senior living facilities
are going to do really well.

01:31:59.960 --> 01:32:03.480
Yeah. Some of these, like,
one of them-- With Primus,

01:32:03.560 --> 01:32:05.040
their plan is to have golf carts,

01:32:05.120 --> 01:32:09.920
and you drive around inside
the community. It's by a lake.

01:32:10.000 --> 01:32:12.880
It's not like living
in polluted Bombay or...

01:32:12.960 --> 01:32:14.800
-It's not.
-It makes a huge difference.

01:32:14.880 --> 01:32:17.360
Like, just the air quality alone
changes so much.

01:32:18.640 --> 01:32:20.960
It's air quality
that's one of the biggest killers.

01:32:21.040 --> 01:32:22.880
-Yeah.
-In, like...

01:32:22.960 --> 01:32:24.520
in the world.

01:32:24.600 --> 01:32:27.760
And one of the reason why
people are having, like, liver failures

01:32:27.840 --> 01:32:31.840
is because of the air pollution,
you know, where they live.

01:32:31.920 --> 01:32:35.880
Yeah. That's one of
the biggest risk factors for--

01:32:35.960 --> 01:32:38.680
like, health risk factors for life
in the world.

01:32:38.760 --> 01:32:43.200
So, any technology
that's helping alleviate air pollution,

01:32:43.280 --> 01:32:47.080
or making, you know, gasoline cars,

01:32:47.160 --> 01:32:50.600
and other such things, you know,
that's prevalent will do really well.

01:32:52.320 --> 01:32:53.920
The next one is content.

01:32:54.640 --> 01:32:57.920
The theory we were discussing is...

01:32:58.000 --> 01:33:01.240
with search being disrupted
in the manner that it is,

01:33:01.320 --> 01:33:05.600
and people, let's assume,
use Google a lot lesser,

01:33:05.680 --> 01:33:09.320
or any kind of search platform
that is throwing up ads...

01:33:09.400 --> 01:33:12.040
And if anyone wants to build a brand,

01:33:12.120 --> 01:33:13.960
social media might exist in some form,

01:33:14.040 --> 01:33:18.080
but Google Ads and the likes of that
will not work.

01:33:18.160 --> 01:33:21.560
So, to be able to build a brand,
you have to...

01:33:21.640 --> 01:33:24.320
be able to hold attention,

01:33:24.400 --> 01:33:27.600
one way or another,
through some form of content.

01:33:27.680 --> 01:33:30.120
And video is working right now. So...

01:33:31.960 --> 01:33:37.640
The alpha between a brand that does well
and a brand that doesn't do well,

01:33:37.720 --> 01:33:40.640
content is going to be
the biggest differentiator.

01:33:40.720 --> 01:33:41.720
Thoughts?

01:33:41.800 --> 01:33:43.000
-That's the premise?
-[Nikhil] Yeah.

01:33:44.440 --> 01:33:46.560
I very much agree with that.

01:33:46.640 --> 01:33:51.480
And, like, for every generation,
if you know how to speak,

01:33:51.560 --> 01:33:57.880
whatever the medium
where content gets viewed as fluently,

01:33:57.960 --> 01:33:59.120
you can do really well.

01:33:59.200 --> 01:34:01.920
So, for example,
there is, you know, that...

01:34:02.000 --> 01:34:06.200
Spanish olive oil... Graza...
I forget what it is,

01:34:06.280 --> 01:34:08.240
you know, that became, like...

01:34:08.320 --> 01:34:11.640
a 70 million dollar-plus business
in a couple of years,

01:34:11.720 --> 01:34:15.200
just because they know
how to appeal to young people.

01:34:15.280 --> 01:34:17.040
Or, like, are you, today, Haikyuu?

01:34:17.120 --> 01:34:19.000
Do you know how to speak X?

01:34:19.080 --> 01:34:20.080
You'll do well.

01:34:20.160 --> 01:34:25.040
Are you a young consumer founder
who knows how to speak TikTok?

01:34:25.120 --> 01:34:26.120
You will do well.

01:34:26.200 --> 01:34:27.240
Yeah.

01:34:27.320 --> 01:34:30.240
And, you know, in a few years,
it will be something else.

01:34:30.320 --> 01:34:31.880
I don't know what that will be,

01:34:31.960 --> 01:34:34.160
but whoever knows
how to play that game well,

01:34:34.240 --> 01:34:35.480
this is golden.

01:34:35.560 --> 01:34:37.560
Attention is all you need.

01:34:37.640 --> 01:34:39.880
-[Nikunj chuckles]
-I think Deedy is doing well at that.

01:34:39.960 --> 01:34:41.600
-[Niko] Absolutely.
-[laughter]

01:34:41.680 --> 01:34:43.880
You're doing pretty well yourself.

01:34:43.960 --> 01:34:48.200
What are you going to pivot into
with all this attention that you have?

01:34:49.120 --> 01:34:53.600
I don't do content for, you know,
any practical purpose,

01:34:53.680 --> 01:34:56.640
which is why I never went
into things like videos...

01:34:56.720 --> 01:34:59.040
It's like saying I don't make money
of any practical purpose.

01:34:59.760 --> 01:35:01.560
No, no, it's not the same.

01:35:01.640 --> 01:35:04.480
It's like, I, you know...

01:35:05.240 --> 01:35:10.080
Everyone's presumably got an education
with some goal of having some job.

01:35:10.160 --> 01:35:12.720
There's other reasons to do it,
but having something...

01:35:12.800 --> 01:35:15.680
But I genuinely don't think
I ever did anything online

01:35:15.760 --> 01:35:19.080
to get an audience or to have money
or to have anything.

01:35:19.160 --> 01:35:22.120
Otherwise, I mean,
what I would tell people is, like,

01:35:22.200 --> 01:35:24.440
"Yeah, if you want to do content
just for that purpose,

01:35:24.520 --> 01:35:26.960
then you would--
there's always easier ways to do it.

01:35:27.040 --> 01:35:30.160
You do humour, you do hot topics,

01:35:30.240 --> 01:35:33.040
you do very debatable,
questionable things."

01:35:33.120 --> 01:35:35.560
And, I mean, some would argue
I have done some of that,

01:35:35.640 --> 01:35:36.880
but not much.

01:35:36.960 --> 01:35:40.280
I think that kind of content
gives you a different kind of attention.

01:35:40.360 --> 01:35:43.760
The kind of content
you're creating gives you...

01:35:43.840 --> 01:35:44.840
trust.

01:35:44.920 --> 01:35:46.760
-Relevancy.
-Relevance.

01:35:46.840 --> 01:35:47.840
In a way, trust.

01:35:47.920 --> 01:35:49.160
When I first started,

01:35:49.240 --> 01:35:52.320
one of my first kinds of things
I would post about is just immigration.

01:35:52.400 --> 01:35:54.080
And the only reason I would do it

01:35:54.160 --> 01:35:56.560
is because I found myself
telling all my friends

01:35:56.640 --> 01:35:58.160
the same thing over and over again.

01:35:58.240 --> 01:36:02.200
So, I'm like, "Let me just write it down,
and then you can go read that."

01:36:02.280 --> 01:36:04.600
And so, I don't see it as...

01:36:04.680 --> 01:36:07.360
For me, at least,
it was never meant to be a business.

01:36:07.440 --> 01:36:09.960
But, to the statement, I mean...

01:36:10.040 --> 01:36:12.360
Niko definitely knows about this trend,

01:36:12.440 --> 01:36:16.000
but there's so many of these
like 16, 17, 18-year-old kids

01:36:16.080 --> 01:36:19.040
who, out of nowhere,
they come up with an app.

01:36:19.120 --> 01:36:20.200
But I think they're been brilliant.

01:36:20.280 --> 01:36:22.840
I was doing a call with Sam Altman,
and he told me the same thing.

01:36:22.920 --> 01:36:24.200
I was like,

01:36:24.280 --> 01:36:26.880
"What should young people do?"

01:36:26.960 --> 01:36:30.040
He said most of them look like
they want to be influencers,

01:36:30.120 --> 01:36:31.920
but I think
they have the best idea ever.

01:36:32.000 --> 01:36:34.560
Being influencers was the best idea ever?

01:36:34.640 --> 01:36:36.400
By creating content, because you're...

01:36:37.520 --> 01:36:39.120
capturing attention.

01:36:39.200 --> 01:36:42.680
And if the attention can age...

01:36:42.760 --> 01:36:46.000
I don't mean tenure
in the sense of, it becomes old,

01:36:46.080 --> 01:36:47.520
but as you grow older,

01:36:47.600 --> 01:36:50.720
if your viewers grow with you
in age as well...

01:36:52.200 --> 01:36:53.760
you keep their attention
for a long time...

01:36:53.840 --> 01:36:55.920
Like, look at Taylor Swift.
It's insane, right?

01:36:56.000 --> 01:36:57.680
-Amazing.
-Yeah.

01:36:57.760 --> 01:37:00.560
She could soon be the richest person
in the world, I wouldn't be surprised.

01:37:02.440 --> 01:37:04.560
But then, what I was going to say
on the app one was,

01:37:04.640 --> 01:37:06.560
it's not even them
trying to be influencers.

01:37:06.640 --> 01:37:09.960
It's them actually figuring out
how to do their own marketing strategy

01:37:10.040 --> 01:37:12.640
at an almost nothing cost, right?

01:37:12.720 --> 01:37:15.200
What they will do is,
they'll pay off people to...

01:37:15.280 --> 01:37:18.240
they'll pay off other people
to make Discord... sorry, on Discord

01:37:18.320 --> 01:37:19.840
to make TikTok videos,

01:37:19.920 --> 01:37:23.760
and then have, like,
some commission-based agreement.

01:37:23.840 --> 01:37:28.080
And then these apps are making millions of
millions of dollars of money, of revenue,

01:37:28.160 --> 01:37:31.960
and they're sitting at home,
in their parents' garage,

01:37:32.040 --> 01:37:34.680
going like, "OK, well, I've made
all this money and I've spent nothing."

01:37:34.760 --> 01:37:37.080
So, I think
it's not them being influencers.

01:37:37.160 --> 01:37:40.160
It's them figuring out
how to tap into the ecosystem

01:37:40.240 --> 01:37:42.160
to get distribution
for the thing that they've built.

01:37:42.240 --> 01:37:43.720
Because what they identify,

01:37:43.800 --> 01:37:45.360
at least, the examples
I'm talking about...

01:37:45.440 --> 01:37:47.880
What they've identified is,
all of these apps look the same,

01:37:47.960 --> 01:37:49.520
the only thing that matters is
distribution.

01:37:49.600 --> 01:37:50.720
So, let me go to the app store,

01:37:50.800 --> 01:37:53.440
figure out all the apps
that are basically commodity,

01:37:53.520 --> 01:37:56.320
make my own,
and then figure out distribution.

01:37:56.400 --> 01:37:57.760
That's my...

01:37:57.840 --> 01:38:00.280
-Storytelling matters, right?
-Storytelling matters.

01:38:00.360 --> 01:38:02.680
We're all suckers for amazing stories.

01:38:02.760 --> 01:38:06.360
So, whoever knows how to tell a story
in a very compelling way,

01:38:06.440 --> 01:38:08.400
and get a lot of attention for it

01:38:08.480 --> 01:38:13.200
because they speak the language
of wherever stories gets heard

01:38:13.280 --> 01:38:14.800
at that moment in time,

01:38:14.880 --> 01:38:16.320
this is super powerful.

01:38:16.400 --> 01:38:17.440
[Nikunj] I'll take the other side.

01:38:17.520 --> 01:38:21.440
I think, in the last three years,

01:38:21.520 --> 01:38:24.920
there's been almost too much attention
on attention.

01:38:25.000 --> 01:38:27.960
While I agree content
helps you grab attention,

01:38:28.040 --> 01:38:30.200
and attention spans are declining,

01:38:30.280 --> 01:38:32.120
I think there's too much empty calories.

01:38:32.200 --> 01:38:34.080
I mean, same audience...

01:38:34.160 --> 01:38:36.840
I think we need to look more
from the lens of...

01:38:36.920 --> 01:38:40.240
Let's say,
Nikunj tomorrow is starting a...

01:38:41.240 --> 01:38:44.360
chocolate brand,
or a T-shirt brand, or any kind...

01:38:44.440 --> 01:38:46.200
Most of an economy is consumption,
right?

01:38:46.280 --> 01:38:49.920
60–70% of money spent in the US
is on QSR response.

01:38:50.000 --> 01:38:53.720
Say you start a fast-food restaurant
in America.

01:38:53.800 --> 01:38:55.440
How do you find your audience,

01:38:55.520 --> 01:38:56.800
if not for content?

01:38:56.880 --> 01:39:01.400
So, my push there is,
like, there's two legs to a stool.

01:39:01.480 --> 01:39:03.480
There's too much attention on attention,

01:39:03.560 --> 01:39:05.080
just like, can you get people in the door?

01:39:05.160 --> 01:39:08.320
But what is your way?
Let's say, Nikunj tomorrow starts selling

01:39:08.400 --> 01:39:09.800
some version of McDonald's.

01:39:09.880 --> 01:39:12.480
The best way is to have the best product.

01:39:12.560 --> 01:39:14.920
Even then, how are you discovered?

01:39:15.000 --> 01:39:17.200
Like how, traditionally,
everything has been discovered,

01:39:17.280 --> 01:39:18.280
which is word of mouth.

01:39:18.360 --> 01:39:20.760
I think there is still power in that.

01:39:20.840 --> 01:39:23.720
Like, you know...
I'll give you a good example.

01:39:23.800 --> 01:39:26.680
Swati is a restaurant in Ahmedabad
and Bombay as well.

01:39:26.760 --> 01:39:27.760
[Nikhil] Swati Snacks. Yeah.

01:39:27.840 --> 01:39:32.280
Same food. I go there every year and eat.
It's always full.

01:39:32.360 --> 01:39:35.120
And they've spent $0 on marketing,
forever.

01:39:35.200 --> 01:39:37.640
Even in today's day and age
where there's a million restaurants,

01:39:37.720 --> 01:39:39.200
that restaurant is full,

01:39:39.280 --> 01:39:42.840
every day, by 5.30 pm or 9 pm.

01:39:42.920 --> 01:39:44.840
And because the product
is still phenomenal.

01:39:44.920 --> 01:39:46.480
But what are the odds of that?

01:39:46.560 --> 01:39:48.440
For every Swati that succeeded...

01:39:48.520 --> 01:39:51.160
I don't think-- That's why I said
there's two legs to a stool.

01:39:51.240 --> 01:39:53.360
I think there's far too much attention
on attention,

01:39:53.440 --> 01:39:54.680
especially in today's economy.

01:39:54.760 --> 01:39:57.040
Everybody wants
a Twitter-viral launch video.

01:39:57.120 --> 01:39:59.480
But the product fucking sucks.

01:39:59.560 --> 01:40:00.800
And I don't think that lasts.

01:40:00.880 --> 01:40:02.200
Like, you look at the churn numbers,
right?

01:40:02.280 --> 01:40:04.080
Yeah, the product has to be good,
regardless.

01:40:04.160 --> 01:40:06.000
No, but that has changed.

01:40:06.080 --> 01:40:08.680
Nowadays, there's so much attention
on attention

01:40:08.760 --> 01:40:11.080
that people are discounting
building a good product.

01:40:11.160 --> 01:40:14.840
Where, kind of what Deedy said,
in a white-labelled world,

01:40:14.920 --> 01:40:18.440
where you just have to build an
OK product, and just distribution matters,

01:40:18.520 --> 01:40:20.560
I think that will peter out
in the long run.

01:40:20.640 --> 01:40:22.680
Won't the quality of...

01:40:22.760 --> 01:40:26.840
With increased productivity
by virtue of AI,

01:40:26.920 --> 01:40:30.600
won't the quality of a product
get democratised, to a large extent?

01:40:31.400 --> 01:40:33.840
I don't know.
I think it's the 10% problem.

01:40:33.920 --> 01:40:36.280
The last mile problem
will forever be there.

01:40:36.360 --> 01:40:39.440
This is why Jiro still builds
the same sushi, 80 years later,

01:40:39.520 --> 01:40:41.440
and, like, you know, continues to do it.

01:40:41.520 --> 01:40:42.840
I think-- I do believe...

01:40:42.920 --> 01:40:44.800
This is why I'm taking the opposite side.

01:40:44.880 --> 01:40:46.520
I think there's too much attention
on attention.

01:40:46.600 --> 01:40:48.040
And do you think
you need eyeballs, right?

01:40:48.120 --> 01:40:49.240
If nobody comes to the restaurant,

01:40:49.320 --> 01:40:51.280
then what's the point
of building a restaurant?

01:40:51.360 --> 01:40:54.400
But I think the product
needs to be phenomenal,

01:40:54.480 --> 01:40:56.960
in this AI age,
otherwise, it's just slop.

01:40:57.040 --> 01:41:00.280
And that's what happens, you know,
when one TikTok trend goes viral...

01:41:00.360 --> 01:41:03.160
20 people copy it,
and 20 people copy the same app.

01:41:03.240 --> 01:41:05.000
There is no differentiation.

01:41:05.080 --> 01:41:07.560
And then, you build little bit of value.

01:41:07.640 --> 01:41:10.200
But the only compounding value
is retention.

01:41:10.280 --> 01:41:12.920
Can you build a retentive product
where people come back?

01:41:13.000 --> 01:41:14.440
And that only comes with quality.

01:41:14.520 --> 01:41:17.280
Think of some products that come to mind
that have done really well

01:41:17.360 --> 01:41:19.000
at mass scale today.

01:41:20.320 --> 01:41:23.800
What do you buy often that you think
is a spectacular product

01:41:25.160 --> 01:41:26.480
from a differentiation lens?

01:41:27.720 --> 01:41:30.560
-Digital, physical, like?
-Apple?

01:41:30.640 --> 01:41:32.400
-iPhones, yeah.
-[Nikhil] Yeah.

01:41:33.360 --> 01:41:36.720
Is that because of the product
or is that because of...

01:41:36.800 --> 01:41:38.600
It's compounding advantages, right?

01:41:38.680 --> 01:41:39.880
Like it's... There's no attention.

01:41:39.960 --> 01:41:41.080
What does Apple spend money on?

01:41:41.720 --> 01:41:44.760
-Now, they spend money on... ads.
-Comparatively,

01:41:44.840 --> 01:41:48.960
compared to their gross margin profile,
their marketing spend is very low.

01:41:49.040 --> 01:41:51.000
Yeah, but I'm not
disagreeing with you at all.

01:41:51.080 --> 01:41:52.160
Yeah, and this is obviously--

01:41:52.240 --> 01:41:54.680
I think this is kind of
obviously true that you can...

01:41:54.760 --> 01:41:56.880
you need retention and you need...
-But that's changing, though.

01:41:56.960 --> 01:42:00.680
Last year, more than ever,
I have felt this changing.

01:42:01.360 --> 01:42:03.560
Where, that you think
people don't focus on...

01:42:03.640 --> 01:42:06.160
Yeah, like they look at
Mr Beast Feastables.

01:42:06.240 --> 01:42:09.560
The only reason it sells is because...
attention.

01:42:10.160 --> 01:42:11.400
The product... I've had it.

01:42:11.480 --> 01:42:13.600
It's horrible. Horrible for the kids.

01:42:13.680 --> 01:42:15.760
-It's horrible for like--
-Why did you try it?

01:42:15.840 --> 01:42:17.520
-Why?
-Because I was just curious.

01:42:17.600 --> 01:42:18.800
-Yeah.
-But, again,

01:42:18.880 --> 01:42:20.480
it's two legs to the same stool.

01:42:20.560 --> 01:42:22.560
I'm just saying there's far too much
attention on one end.

01:42:22.640 --> 01:42:24.880
Yeah. I think I'm focusing more
on discoverability.

01:42:24.960 --> 01:42:25.960
Yeah.

01:42:26.040 --> 01:42:29.280
'Cause you get to that point and then
comes the question of retention.

01:42:32.560 --> 01:42:35.680
Yeah. I mean, you need attention
because now, in a sea of the same,

01:42:35.760 --> 01:42:37.320
how do you differentiate yourself?

01:42:37.400 --> 01:42:40.880
Content will always be the differentiator,
one way or the other.

01:42:40.960 --> 01:42:44.000
But I, I think
it's gonna be a revolving door

01:42:44.080 --> 01:42:45.360
if you don't focus enough on the product.

01:42:45.440 --> 01:42:49.520
The pendulum is swung on the other side
is what I'm trying to argue,

01:42:49.600 --> 01:42:52.240
where I think it can go
back to, like, we need both.

01:42:52.320 --> 01:42:53.440
Can't have one or the other.

01:42:53.520 --> 01:42:59.320
I'm looking at the last five-year bucket
as the bucket of performance marketing,

01:42:59.400 --> 01:43:03.440
where you gave Google money
to show your product in different places

01:43:03.520 --> 01:43:05.720
-and you paid for the number of clicks.
-Sure. Yeah.

01:43:05.800 --> 01:43:08.120
And I'm looking at
what is the next transition from that.

01:43:08.880 --> 01:43:11.920
Yeah, I mean, discoverability, especially
like consumers, it's all TikTok.

01:43:12.000 --> 01:43:14.120
Because it's the only free channel left,

01:43:14.200 --> 01:43:18.840
where if you build something that grabs
attention, you get a lot of attention.

01:43:19.640 --> 01:43:21.040
Everything else has become paid to play.

01:43:21.120 --> 01:43:22.640
-It's known.
-Should we-- Yeah.

01:43:22.720 --> 01:43:23.960
Should we rate this?

01:43:24.040 --> 01:43:27.720
Content. Importance of content
in building a business. Niko?

01:43:28.920 --> 01:43:32.920
For anything that's, like, you know,
consumer-facing or prosumer facing,

01:43:33.640 --> 01:43:36.560
discoverability,
it's like a, it's a 10.

01:43:37.160 --> 01:43:38.680
-Deedy?
-Yeah.

01:43:38.760 --> 01:43:44.160
Without that caveat, and I would say,
like eight or nine, fairly important.

01:43:44.240 --> 01:43:46.040
Not the only thing.

01:43:46.120 --> 01:43:47.280
-[Nikhil] Nikunj?
-Say seven.

01:43:47.360 --> 01:43:49.920
Important, but not the only thing
that's needed.

01:43:50.000 --> 01:43:53.600
Do you guys see a world where
David is winning against Goliath?

01:43:53.680 --> 01:43:56.200
People don't want to buy
from corporations,

01:43:56.280 --> 01:43:58.160
but they want to buy
from individual brands?

01:44:00.400 --> 01:44:04.320
Yeah. We have to believe that,
we're in the business of backing Davids.

01:44:05.960 --> 01:44:07.120
Yeah.

01:44:07.200 --> 01:44:10.240
I think this is happening more and more
with offline experiences.

01:44:11.480 --> 01:44:15.240
Where you wanna-- Like in the universe
of, like, tourists, right?

01:44:15.320 --> 01:44:20.680
You want to have
the bespoke local artisanal guide,

01:44:20.760 --> 01:44:24.680
or, like, the hotel
that has its own story,

01:44:24.760 --> 01:44:28.040
or go to the restaurant
that's mom and pop, you know?

01:44:28.120 --> 01:44:32.320
Do you feel like this happened
because the last 10, 20 years,

01:44:32.400 --> 01:44:37.320
we bought products behind a corporation

01:44:37.400 --> 01:44:42.600
'cause trust was so deficit in society
that we didn't know what went into it.

01:44:42.680 --> 01:44:48.400
Today, we care less about trust,
and we are buying artisanal, handmade,

01:44:48.480 --> 01:44:52.160
we are buying into individuality again
and is that a trend that's here to stay?

01:44:54.160 --> 01:44:56.600
I do like how you framed it,

01:44:56.680 --> 01:45:00.160
and it depends on the society
that you live in

01:45:00.240 --> 01:45:03.000
and your economic participant.

01:45:03.080 --> 01:45:09.440
I would also add that,
very often, you don't want to be

01:45:09.520 --> 01:45:12.800
buying the same brands
that your parents were buying.

01:45:12.880 --> 01:45:15.600
It might be the case for detergent,
but to go to the same,

01:45:15.680 --> 01:45:18.200
you know, the hotel chain that they went,

01:45:18.280 --> 01:45:19.720
it's not as cool for you.

01:45:19.800 --> 01:45:24.280
So, like, every generation
has its own cool...

01:45:24.360 --> 01:45:28.320
brands, experiences
that they resonate with.

01:45:28.400 --> 01:45:33.840
And a lot of the large corporations,
at least in the West, have had like...

01:45:33.920 --> 01:45:36.960
they've lost a lot of their brand equity
with the youth.

01:45:38.440 --> 01:45:41.160
I mean, generally the question
of David versus Goliath,

01:45:41.240 --> 01:45:43.800
you always... not, mean,
not in every situation,

01:45:43.880 --> 01:45:45.920
but Davids are a great bet to make.

01:45:46.000 --> 01:45:48.800
Because Goliaths are
usually bigger businesses,

01:45:48.880 --> 01:45:50.400
they have established practices,

01:45:50.480 --> 01:45:52.560
they lose their eye on the ball,

01:45:52.640 --> 01:45:55.080
they're focused on
managing things at scale,

01:45:55.160 --> 01:45:59.080
sometimes reducing costs,
so maybe not just the hotel example,

01:45:59.160 --> 01:46:01.280
but even for many other cases,

01:46:01.360 --> 01:46:05.280
most businesses do not have
any systemic effects of scale

01:46:05.360 --> 01:46:07.360
that can't be disrupted in other ways.

01:46:07.440 --> 01:46:10.320
So, yeah, in many cases
I would definitely bet

01:46:10.400 --> 01:46:13.160
against, on the David
versus the Goliath, of course,

01:46:13.240 --> 01:46:15.960
there are other cases
where that is not a good bet.

01:46:16.040 --> 01:46:22.320
But, yeah, older businesses will get
disrupted, generally, for most industries.

01:46:22.400 --> 01:46:24.440
-Nikunj, thoughts?
-Yeah.

01:46:24.520 --> 01:46:27.120
Cycle of life will continue.

01:46:27.200 --> 01:46:32.200
Big gets too big, too horizontal,
not enough depth, small has that.

01:46:32.280 --> 01:46:35.440
And then,
from a consumption perspective,

01:46:35.520 --> 01:46:38.080
I think people will continue
to stay way-in,

01:46:38.160 --> 01:46:39.320
which means they want the new thing.

01:46:39.400 --> 01:46:41.280
They want to differentiate themselves,

01:46:41.360 --> 01:46:45.400
and that will continue to want them to do
whatever version of artisanal work.

01:46:47.520 --> 01:46:48.640
Perfect, I'm gonna read this?

01:46:48.720 --> 01:46:50.120
I just have like four more,

01:46:50.200 --> 01:46:52.680
and then I'll tell you
how much you rated which one,

01:46:52.760 --> 01:46:56.080
and which is probably a good sector
to focus on for the next decade.

01:46:56.760 --> 01:46:57.960
David versus Goliath, Nikunj?

01:46:58.040 --> 01:47:02.320
The ten is pro-David
and zero is pro-Goliath, correct?

01:47:02.400 --> 01:47:03.600
-Niko?
-Yeah.

01:47:03.680 --> 01:47:06.240
I'm like an eight.

01:47:07.720 --> 01:47:09.920
I would say a seven,
'cause there are some places

01:47:10.000 --> 01:47:13.720
where scale definitely matters,
but then, many cases they don't.

01:47:13.800 --> 01:47:16.520
-One good example is in tech...
-Mm-hmm.

01:47:16.600 --> 01:47:19.520
...where you see something
like six, seven companies

01:47:19.600 --> 01:47:21.680
that created the bulk of the market cap,

01:47:21.760 --> 01:47:23.400
if that's a way to measure it,

01:47:25.080 --> 01:47:29.320
over everyone else the last 30 years.

01:47:29.400 --> 01:47:32.480
So I had this thesis two years ago

01:47:32.560 --> 01:47:37.040
that by virtue of cost
per mile or kilometre,

01:47:37.120 --> 01:47:43.840
most vehicles will become
EV or hydrogen-focused

01:47:43.920 --> 01:47:45.800
in a very short period of time.

01:47:45.880 --> 01:47:49.200
So, I spent two years
investing in everything

01:47:49.280 --> 01:47:53.560
from electric scooters,
electric buses, trucks,

01:47:53.640 --> 01:47:56.320
even a flying electric taxi company.

01:47:57.880 --> 01:48:02.160
When I look back at it now,
a lot of these bets did play off,

01:48:02.240 --> 01:48:06.320
but the adoption to EV
seems to be slowing down,

01:48:07.080 --> 01:48:10.280
and subsidies are being taken away
not just in the US,

01:48:10.360 --> 01:48:12.840
but also in countries like India
and other places.

01:48:13.680 --> 01:48:17.360
What do you think
is the future there for 2035?

01:48:17.440 --> 01:48:21.360
Adoption of electric vehicles
and hydrogen versus IC.

01:48:21.440 --> 01:48:26.960
I think for somebody to buy a vehicle,
and let's pick a neutral country, right?

01:48:27.040 --> 01:48:29.880
That's not the US. It's not China.

01:48:29.960 --> 01:48:34.600
Like one in Latin America,
or like a smaller country in Europe.

01:48:35.360 --> 01:48:38.120
The consideration you know
would be, what is the cost?

01:48:38.200 --> 01:48:42.440
-Price.
-How often would I need to maintain it?

01:48:42.520 --> 01:48:44.040
What's the cost of ownership?

01:48:46.280 --> 01:48:51.760
And you actually do see that a number
of the Chinese car manufacturers

01:48:51.840 --> 01:48:55.240
that make EVs that, here in the US
you don't see on the street,

01:48:55.320 --> 01:48:56.560
are actually winning.

01:48:56.640 --> 01:48:57.760
They're far ahead.

01:48:57.840 --> 01:49:03.360
Because the price and the total cost
of ownership is pretty awesome.

01:49:03.440 --> 01:49:06.240
So when I visited,
you know, different, you know,

01:49:06.320 --> 01:49:09.120
such countries over the last few...

01:49:09.200 --> 01:49:13.240
over the last year, like, in Columbia,
or, like, in Portugal,

01:49:13.320 --> 01:49:15.760
or, like, in Greece,

01:49:15.840 --> 01:49:19.680
I was seeing car-make brands
that I had never seen before.

01:49:19.760 --> 01:49:22.160
And I was googling them,
and they're, like, massive.

01:49:23.240 --> 01:49:26.680
So do I think this is a trend
that will continue?

01:49:27.560 --> 01:49:29.840
Yes, I think it's a trend
that will continue.

01:49:29.920 --> 01:49:32.840
Might not be everywhere, but
in a lot of, you know, countries,

01:49:33.560 --> 01:49:35.640
because people want to have a car.

01:49:35.720 --> 01:49:39.440
It's a means for them
to unlock more productivity

01:49:39.520 --> 01:49:42.560
and get to work
and make more money,

01:49:43.920 --> 01:49:46.240
I think it's a trend
that's not going to stop.

01:49:46.920 --> 01:49:48.960
I'll give you the number in India.

01:49:49.040 --> 01:49:52.920
If you buy an EV scooter,
it costs about $2,000.

01:49:53.000 --> 01:49:55.120
-[Niko] Mm-hmm.
-If you buy an IC scooter,

01:49:55.200 --> 01:49:56.920
it costs you about $1,000.

01:49:57.840 --> 01:50:00.960
But if you ride this scooter
for 40 kilometres a day,

01:50:02.080 --> 01:50:05.160
on an EV scooter, you save $500 a year.

01:50:06.480 --> 01:50:07.480
Cost of running.

01:50:08.240 --> 01:50:14.080
And much easier to maintain, 'cause the
number of parts are exponentially lesser.

01:50:15.040 --> 01:50:17.120
But still, adoption is not that high.

01:50:18.040 --> 01:50:24.160
Why do you think adoption numbers have
slowed as much as they have in the US?

01:50:24.240 --> 01:50:28.040
Can it just be because the Chinese
are making spectacular EVs,

01:50:28.120 --> 01:50:29.800
which are years ahead of them,

01:50:29.880 --> 01:50:32.880
and they don't want to even
compete in that market anymore?

01:50:32.960 --> 01:50:35.600
What is it? Why did the subsidies go away?

01:50:35.680 --> 01:50:39.200
I don't think you can buy any of
the Chinese EV cars here, right?

01:50:39.280 --> 01:50:40.600
-No, you can't.
-That's the biggest issue.

01:50:40.680 --> 01:50:43.600
If we were to truly operate
like a free market,

01:50:43.680 --> 01:50:46.040
I think they would be doing really well.

01:50:46.120 --> 01:50:48.800
The same in India.
Like, you can't buy Chinese vehicles.

01:50:48.880 --> 01:50:54.040
But are Americans not buying American EVs
because they can't buy Chinese EVs?

01:50:55.320 --> 01:50:57.160
-[Nikunj] It's just a cost thing.
-[overlapping conversation]

01:50:57.240 --> 01:50:59.440
As Niko said, it's cost and convenience.

01:50:59.520 --> 01:51:02.800
There's not enough chargers,
and it costs too much.

01:51:02.880 --> 01:51:05.560
If the cheapest car was an EV,
everyone would buy an EV.

01:51:06.640 --> 01:51:08.840
Do you think that'll change
in the next ten years?

01:51:09.840 --> 01:51:13.160
What percentage of cars on the road
in ten years will be EVs?

01:51:13.240 --> 01:51:16.440
In America, I think it'll change.
And that's primarily because of Tesla.

01:51:16.520 --> 01:51:18.360
That's the only car company
that moves fast.

01:51:18.440 --> 01:51:22.000
And so if that's the only car company
that is allowed to operate, then, yeah.

01:51:22.720 --> 01:51:25.280
Then they will figure out how to get
the cost down, one way or the other.

01:51:25.360 --> 01:51:27.720
Do you say 100% of cars
will be EV in ten years?

01:51:27.800 --> 01:51:28.920
I don't know, 100%,

01:51:29.000 --> 01:51:33.920
but I would say like, it would...
a majority of cars will be EV in 10 years

01:51:34.000 --> 01:51:35.240
in my mind.

01:51:35.320 --> 01:51:38.440
A good proxy would be like
what percent of cars

01:51:38.520 --> 01:51:40.840
that are getting sold today are EV, right?

01:51:40.920 --> 01:51:43.920
And this could kind of tell you
how the future might look like.

01:51:44.000 --> 01:51:49.120
-Like, around 20%, sub-20%.
-Is it? I don't know. But...

01:51:50.200 --> 01:51:52.760
So, yeah, if that number
is accelerating...

01:51:53.640 --> 01:51:55.440
It was accelerating,

01:51:55.520 --> 01:51:58.000
but the pace of acceleration
has slowed down.

01:51:58.080 --> 01:52:01.760
Yes, and part of it is the incentives.
Part of it is the economic cycle.

01:52:01.840 --> 01:52:05.480
So whenever there is
a slowdown in the economy,

01:52:05.560 --> 01:52:10.400
the used car market is doing much better
than the new car market.

01:52:10.480 --> 01:52:14.560
Or like, you know, when we had the
disruption with COVID in the supply chain,

01:52:14.640 --> 01:52:19.320
new cars became more expensive
and harder, you know, to buy

01:52:19.400 --> 01:52:22.080
because you would
have to wait for longer.

01:52:22.160 --> 01:52:23.480
So, there's these factors, too.

01:52:23.560 --> 01:52:29.200
But do I think that, like, EVs,
anywhere in the world, are going to be

01:52:29.280 --> 01:52:32.920
the majority of cars
over the next 10 to 15 years?

01:52:33.000 --> 01:52:34.800
Yes, I do think so, yeah.

01:52:35.440 --> 01:52:41.200
I think we dramatically overestimate
how fast people will adopt new things,

01:52:41.280 --> 01:52:43.480
and cars are a big asset in the country.

01:52:43.560 --> 01:52:47.680
It's like saying America
will build ten million homes.

01:52:47.760 --> 01:52:49.520
We won't. It's just harder.

01:52:49.600 --> 01:52:53.160
And US, especially, from a market
perspective, used car market is massive.

01:52:53.240 --> 01:52:55.440
Always has been boom or bust.

01:52:55.520 --> 01:52:58.720
And it's very hard to just change it.

01:52:58.800 --> 01:53:03.080
Like, new cars will be built,
but they're far more expensive.

01:53:03.160 --> 01:53:05.800
And so, I actually think that
without the incentives and...

01:53:05.880 --> 01:53:08.640
In ten years, one could argue
they won't be, like, more expensive.

01:53:08.720 --> 01:53:10.720
They're probably cheaper.
They're likely to be cheaper.

01:53:11.440 --> 01:53:15.680
This is where, like, if the free market--
depends on where you're sourcing it from.

01:53:15.760 --> 01:53:19.680
Does have to be US-made? Then, no.
I can still source from a free market.

01:53:19.760 --> 01:53:22.280
If free market existed,
I would be very pro,

01:53:22.360 --> 01:53:25.120
and I have two EV cars at home,
just to be clear.

01:53:25.200 --> 01:53:29.400
Like, I would be very pro, like,
"Oh, we'd see 10% of the market be EV."

01:53:29.480 --> 01:53:32.720
But otherwise, it'll be a slow trickle
till these cars go out of...

01:53:32.800 --> 01:53:35.760
Yeah, another vector to consider, perhaps,

01:53:35.840 --> 01:53:40.160
is in places where we have a lot
of autonomous vehicles adoption,

01:53:40.240 --> 01:53:43.200
if, indeed, the total cost of operation

01:53:43.280 --> 01:53:47.720
for, like, an autonomous vehicle
is you've got to be EV first,

01:53:49.160 --> 01:53:53.000
then, you know, that's another market
that's going to be growing very quickly.

01:53:53.080 --> 01:53:54.320
-Right?
-[Nikunj] Yeah. Yeah.

01:53:54.400 --> 01:53:56.960
Want to rate it? Niko?

01:53:57.040 --> 01:54:00.760
Yeah. I think I'm like a seven,
you know, or an eight.

01:54:00.840 --> 01:54:02.920
Yeah. Seven. Seven.

01:54:03.000 --> 01:54:08.920
Seven to the statement that, by 2035,
majority of cars will be EV?

01:54:09.000 --> 01:54:10.440
Yeah.

01:54:10.520 --> 01:54:11.920
In America?

01:54:12.000 --> 01:54:15.200
-No, worldwide.
-Oh, seven.

01:54:16.600 --> 01:54:17.640
Probably less.

01:54:17.720 --> 01:54:22.400
I mean, it's, like, it depends on,
like, China, India, Nigeria, Brazil.

01:54:22.480 --> 01:54:23.760
-Right? Like, Indonesia.
-[Deedy] Yeah.

01:54:23.840 --> 01:54:28.960
I think those countries will adapt faster
because of efficiency.

01:54:29.040 --> 01:54:30.280
The amount of energy lost

01:54:30.360 --> 01:54:35.280
between generation and endpoint usage
is lower in EVs.

01:54:36.120 --> 01:54:40.680
And people will adopt there because
the cost to travel per mile will be lower.

01:54:40.760 --> 01:54:43.600
Yeah. And what if I would say to you,
not in India,

01:54:43.680 --> 01:54:46.360
but, in China, huger pollution problem.

01:54:46.440 --> 01:54:49.280
The Chinese government
says, "Hey, guys,

01:54:49.360 --> 01:54:52.680
from now on,
you wanna buy, like, a gasoline car?

01:54:52.760 --> 01:54:55.560
No problem. It's going to be
like 50% more expensive."

01:54:55.640 --> 01:54:57.240
The same is happening already.

01:54:57.320 --> 01:55:00.880
Like, in India, many cities
are saying that if you're bringing

01:55:00.960 --> 01:55:03.400
a truck into the city,
if it's not EV, it's not allowed.

01:55:03.480 --> 01:55:06.480
Oh, there you go. So that's, again,
another vector that pushes demand

01:55:06.560 --> 01:55:08.920
-even further, right?
-But then, why only seven?

01:55:10.560 --> 01:55:13.680
Because I'm not as fluent
in the exact numbers.

01:55:13.760 --> 01:55:18.480
And it depends on, like, this four or five
big, very populous countries, right?

01:55:18.560 --> 01:55:20.720
Right. Right. Nikunj?

01:55:20.800 --> 01:55:23.880
I think if it's new cars, like,
on what percentage of new cars--

01:55:23.960 --> 01:55:25.920
-New cars.
-Oh, new cars. In 2035, yeah.

01:55:26.000 --> 01:55:28.000
That'd be, like, a seven.

01:55:28.080 --> 01:55:30.000
-All right.
-Oh, it's for new cars?

01:55:30.080 --> 01:55:31.240
I was thinking, like, total cars.

01:55:31.320 --> 01:55:33.680
-That's what, yeah, yeah.
-Let's say for new cars.

01:55:33.760 --> 01:55:35.840
[overlapping conversation]

01:55:35.920 --> 01:55:37.200
Yeah, I'm like, nine. Yeah.

01:55:37.280 --> 01:55:38.520
-[Deedy] Yes.
-Same?

01:55:38.600 --> 01:55:39.600
[Niko] Yeah, like...

01:55:39.680 --> 01:55:42.800
Because I was thinking,
you know, the average lifetime

01:55:42.880 --> 01:55:45.760
of a car in a bunch of countries,
like, you know, 12 years.

01:55:45.840 --> 01:55:47.440
-I was trying to do that math.
-Yeah.

01:55:47.520 --> 01:55:50.520
-That was, like, VC math in your head.
-[laughter]

01:55:50.600 --> 01:55:52.360
-Nine as well?
-I think, eight,

01:55:52.440 --> 01:55:55.480
primarily because I think,
especially in the US, like,

01:55:55.560 --> 01:55:59.040
with the conservative government,
like oil and gas is not going anywhere.

01:55:59.120 --> 01:56:02.360
It'll take a long time
for us to, like, move...

01:56:02.440 --> 01:56:04.160
Like, from a politics perspective,

01:56:04.240 --> 01:56:08.040
EV force is not gonna be very popular
for the next six years.

01:56:08.120 --> 01:56:12.560
But from a cost perspective,
the cost of everything else

01:56:12.640 --> 01:56:15.360
compared to fossil
is falling so quickly.

01:56:15.440 --> 01:56:18.240
But the problem is batteries--
Again, it's, like, American choice.

01:56:18.320 --> 01:56:21.520
Like, you know, it's, like, "I can go
fill up my petrol wherever I want.

01:56:21.600 --> 01:56:23.080
I can go to a gas station.

01:56:24.000 --> 01:56:27.600
I can kind of, like, have this--
I don't want to wait for 45 minutes."

01:56:27.680 --> 01:56:30.360
Convenience-- battery technology
is not evolving fast enough.

01:56:30.440 --> 01:56:32.000
I'll give you an example.

01:56:32.080 --> 01:56:35.120
We invested in this electric truck company

01:56:35.200 --> 01:56:39.800
which has interchangeable batteries,
like, battery swap.

01:56:39.880 --> 01:56:42.800
The largest company
which does battery swap in the world

01:56:42.880 --> 01:56:44.880
is called SANY in China.

01:56:45.760 --> 01:56:47.720
So, these trucks drive

01:56:47.800 --> 01:56:49.880
-with two batteries at a time.
-[Nikunj] Yeah.

01:56:49.960 --> 01:56:53.640
They go to something which is
as small as one container box,

01:56:53.720 --> 01:56:57.040
and the batteries are swapped
in the same amount of time

01:56:57.120 --> 01:56:59.720
that it would take for you
to stop at a gas station

01:56:59.800 --> 01:57:01.360
-and fill fuel.
-Yeah.

01:57:01.440 --> 01:57:02.880
Each battery gives you a range

01:57:02.960 --> 01:57:04.760
-of 700 kilometres.
-Yeah.

01:57:04.840 --> 01:57:08.680
So, two batteries together let you drive
1400 kilometres.

01:57:08.760 --> 01:57:09.760
Yeah.

01:57:09.840 --> 01:57:15.040
India, end to end, let's say is,
I don't know, 4,000, 5,000 kilometres.

01:57:15.840 --> 01:57:19.000
What that means is
the number of petrol stations

01:57:19.080 --> 01:57:22.160
that you require in itself
come down exponentially.

01:57:22.240 --> 01:57:27.000
You probably only need
50 container-sized stations

01:57:27.080 --> 01:57:29.480
across the country
to get these trucks to go

01:57:29.560 --> 01:57:31.880
across the length
and breadth of the country.

01:57:31.960 --> 01:57:34.560
I think the model is changing
significantly,

01:57:34.640 --> 01:57:37.400
even for a country
as broad and wide as India.

01:57:39.000 --> 01:57:42.200
I think the replacement,
as you mentioned, like eight,

01:57:42.280 --> 01:57:45.280
is... I won't be a ten
because there'll still be choice,

01:57:45.360 --> 01:57:48.000
and people will--
It takes a while to flow in.

01:57:48.080 --> 01:57:50.360
Like, even today,
I disagree with Deedy,

01:57:50.440 --> 01:57:51.920
like charging stations are good enough.

01:57:52.000 --> 01:57:55.120
Like, every... in America,
infrastructure is already there.

01:57:55.200 --> 01:57:57.880
People are still voting
to not buy EV cars,

01:57:57.960 --> 01:57:59.880
even though they're cost-appropriate.

01:57:59.960 --> 01:58:02.000
It just takes time for people to change.

01:58:02.080 --> 01:58:03.240
Right. Right.

01:58:03.320 --> 01:58:05.440
OK. Point number eight of ten.

01:58:05.520 --> 01:58:07.560
Beauty as a category.

01:58:08.520 --> 01:58:10.760
-Beauty products.
-Ten.

01:58:12.080 --> 01:58:13.760
-Yeah?
-[Niko] Same.

01:58:13.840 --> 01:58:14.880
-[Nikhil] Yeah?
-Yeah.

01:58:14.960 --> 01:58:17.560
And beauty and content
are in line with each other, I think.

01:58:17.640 --> 01:58:21.240
Look who are the wealthiest people
outside of tech.

01:58:21.320 --> 01:58:22.960
Anyone who's in beauty and luxury.

01:58:23.040 --> 01:58:24.760
Yeah. Luxury.

01:58:24.840 --> 01:58:26.720
-It's luxury.
-Beauty and luxury. Yeah.

01:58:26.800 --> 01:58:29.800
-Luxury also ten?
-Yeah.

01:58:29.880 --> 01:58:32.680
-I was saying, who are the wealthiest...
-Besides tech.

01:58:32.760 --> 01:58:37.320
...you know, like, uh, individuals
or families outside of technology?

01:58:37.400 --> 01:58:40.040
Anyone who's in beauty or in luxury goods.

01:58:42.400 --> 01:58:44.800
Should I just add them and make them one?
Beauty, luxury.

01:58:44.880 --> 01:58:48.680
And then, like, if we want to take
a glimpse into the future,

01:58:48.760 --> 01:58:52.320
we would go into South Korea,

01:58:52.400 --> 01:58:55.400
where indeed they have one of
the lowest fertility rates in the world,

01:58:55.480 --> 01:58:57.640
but they are
massive exporters of culture.

01:58:57.720 --> 01:59:00.160
And over there, if you're a man,

01:59:00.240 --> 01:59:06.560
there is more than 50% chance that
they use beauty products every single day.

01:59:07.520 --> 01:59:08.760
[Nikhil] Yeah.

01:59:08.840 --> 01:59:13.040
So, like, again, you know, those guys'
population, you know, will shrink.

01:59:13.120 --> 01:59:16.960
But if everyone was, like, 80 years old,
looks like a 50 year old,

01:59:17.040 --> 01:59:20.680
-that's a good trade for most people.
-And the surgeries in South Korea.

01:59:20.760 --> 01:59:23.080
We've been ideating
what to build in beauty.

01:59:23.160 --> 01:59:24.800
We're trying to come up with something.

01:59:24.880 --> 01:59:29.360
Any ideas?
What could work as a product category?

01:59:29.440 --> 01:59:31.400
-In beauty?
-[Nikhil] Yeah, now.

01:59:33.680 --> 01:59:36.520
Like, beauty gives you confidence, right?

01:59:36.600 --> 01:59:39.520
No, but if I want to build a brand
in beauty, like we have a team

01:59:39.600 --> 01:59:43.880
which does a lot of consumer brands
that we run, not just invest in.

01:59:43.960 --> 01:59:48.360
If we build for beauty, what do you think
could work in today's day cycle?

01:59:48.440 --> 01:59:51.640
-Can you help me eliminate my wrinkles?
-Right.

01:59:51.720 --> 01:59:53.040
I would pay for that.

01:59:53.120 --> 01:59:54.400
I think male beauty...

01:59:54.480 --> 01:59:57.720
Could you make Botox,
you know, 90% cheaper?

01:59:57.800 --> 02:00:00.400
-I would pay for that.
-Right.

02:00:00.480 --> 02:00:01.520
Anti-ageing?

02:00:01.600 --> 02:00:05.040
Anything anti-ageing that's more easily
to get to...

02:00:05.120 --> 02:00:06.560
-[Nikhil] Men's.
-...and cheaper? Yeah.

02:00:06.640 --> 02:00:11.080
I think make-- for men to make it more
accessible and cooler with content,

02:00:11.160 --> 02:00:12.200
you could do that.

02:00:12.280 --> 02:00:13.600
-[Niko] You could do that, too.
-Yeah.

02:00:13.680 --> 02:00:15.800
I have the opposite take,
I think I would build, like,

02:00:15.880 --> 02:00:22.680
a very high end luxurious brand for,
like, the top 10% of Indian males.

02:00:23.920 --> 02:00:27.320
-For Indian males.
-We're talking about India, right?

02:00:27.400 --> 02:00:28.800
No, not necessarily.

02:00:28.880 --> 02:00:32.360
I'd take the opposite route,
which is like I'll take...

02:00:33.960 --> 02:00:35.160
take hard problems, like anti-ageing.

02:00:35.240 --> 02:00:38.000
I'm guessing you fall into the top 10%,
so would you buy?

02:00:38.080 --> 02:00:40.040
-Yeah.
-What would you buy?

02:00:40.120 --> 02:00:41.840
-Whatever.
-Would you buy like make up?

02:00:42.520 --> 02:00:44.080
I think this is where--

02:00:44.160 --> 02:00:46.360
So, the other aspect
of it's, like, invisible.

02:00:46.440 --> 02:00:48.880
-Right.
-What is invisible today?

02:00:48.960 --> 02:00:52.520
Is there, like, an invisible foundation
that makes me look five years younger?

02:00:52.600 --> 02:00:53.840
-You would?
-Yeah.

02:00:53.920 --> 02:00:57.440
-You would, too?
-I know nothing about beauty, but I mean,

02:00:57.520 --> 02:00:59.720
I think there's...
All of these things are credible.

02:00:59.800 --> 02:01:02.320
I think there is a gap in male beauty,

02:01:02.400 --> 02:01:05.880
but I think women are obviously
the primary consumers of beauty products.

02:01:05.960 --> 02:01:07.280
So, there's a lot you can do there.

02:01:08.280 --> 02:01:09.960
I just-- I know nothing about that.

02:01:10.040 --> 02:01:11.480
I mean, look into Ozempic, you know.

02:01:11.560 --> 02:01:12.680
-[Nikhil] Yeah.
-Most people take it.

02:01:12.760 --> 02:01:14.200
-It is beauty.
-[Niko] Every week.

02:01:14.280 --> 02:01:16.640
Because they don't want
to ever fucking be on a diet.

02:01:16.720 --> 02:01:18.120
Yeah.

02:01:18.200 --> 02:01:21.160
-I know a lot of people like us...
-Yeah.

02:01:21.240 --> 02:01:22.560
...who are in their 30s or 40s.

02:01:22.640 --> 02:01:25.640
They've never had any issues
with their weight,

02:01:26.600 --> 02:01:28.680
but they don't wanna be on a diet.
They wanna eat everything.

02:01:28.760 --> 02:01:30.160
They take Ozempic. It's a beauty product.

02:01:30.240 --> 02:01:33.680
I'm guessing longevity and wellness
you guys will rank highly as well.

02:01:33.760 --> 02:01:35.600
-Yeah.
-Tens?

02:01:37.360 --> 02:01:40.080
Yeah, it's a question of affordability,
so it would be a 9, you know.

02:01:40.160 --> 02:01:42.240
-Longevity and wellness?
-[Niko] Yeah.

02:01:42.320 --> 02:01:43.680
For you?

02:01:44.800 --> 02:01:45.920
Yeah. I think like...

02:01:47.400 --> 02:01:49.040
At what price point matters,

02:01:49.120 --> 02:01:51.080
-but... as a category, yeah.
-Nine?

02:01:51.160 --> 02:01:53.320
-Nine?
-I'm more of an eight.

02:01:53.400 --> 02:01:54.440
It's like anti-recession.

02:01:54.520 --> 02:01:56.480
I mean, have you guys
ever, like, taken a flight

02:01:56.560 --> 02:01:59.040
that's connecting through
Istanbul and Turkey?

02:01:59.120 --> 02:02:00.120
Of course.

02:02:00.200 --> 02:02:02.000
-What do you see there?
-A great airport.

02:02:02.080 --> 02:02:03.840
-[Nikhil] Hair.
-Great airport.

02:02:03.920 --> 02:02:05.760
-Yeah. Isn't that freaking insane?
-Yeah.

02:02:05.840 --> 02:02:08.240
Where was that industry,
like, 10 years ago?

02:02:08.320 --> 02:02:10.160
-It wasn't there.
-Yeah.

02:02:10.240 --> 02:02:13.880
And now, thanks to TikTok and content,
it has become like...

02:02:14.880 --> 02:02:16.600
...a global destination.

02:02:16.680 --> 02:02:17.960
Live events.

02:02:18.800 --> 02:02:21.960
Concerts, theatres, plays.

02:02:23.640 --> 02:02:26.280
I would even put something like...

02:02:26.360 --> 02:02:28.960
a high-end restaurant as a live event.

02:02:29.040 --> 02:02:32.240
I think the nature
of live events is shifting to...

02:02:32.320 --> 02:02:35.480
people want to advertise that

02:02:35.560 --> 02:02:38.440
they were at a live event
on their Instagram, predominantly.

02:02:38.520 --> 02:02:44.120
I think that's the main purpose
for most people that go to live events.

02:02:44.200 --> 02:02:46.160
Or others do it, you know, on your behalf,

02:02:46.240 --> 02:02:49.360
and you lose your job,
as the whole world learned last week.

02:02:50.880 --> 02:02:53.320
Everyone wants to go to
a good Coldplay concert, you know?

02:02:53.400 --> 02:02:55.080
Um, so...

02:02:55.160 --> 02:02:59.400
But, generally,
I'm more neutral on live events

02:02:59.480 --> 02:03:02.440
because I do think
attention capture is going to be

02:03:02.520 --> 02:03:04.720
more massive on digital.

02:03:04.800 --> 02:03:09.520
And so, there's going to be
a smaller set of people in my mind

02:03:09.600 --> 02:03:11.640
that want to go to live events.

02:03:12.440 --> 02:03:13.440
Yeah?

02:03:13.520 --> 02:03:14.760
Net volume...

02:03:14.840 --> 02:03:19.320
Not, maybe not a number, but the net
volume of time spent at a live event,

02:03:19.400 --> 02:03:22.560
I don't really have a strong view
that it goes up.

02:03:22.640 --> 02:03:24.640
I actually don't know.

02:03:24.720 --> 02:03:26.280
Niko, what do you think?

02:03:26.360 --> 02:03:29.560
I think most live events, historically,
have been like shit businesses to run.

02:03:29.640 --> 02:03:33.920
But in a world where the offline
experiences become the scars,

02:03:34.000 --> 02:03:37.200
in a world where
we get tired of being online,

02:03:37.280 --> 02:03:39.640
in front of our screens for 14 hours,

02:03:39.720 --> 02:03:41.040
there's going to be a premium.

02:03:41.120 --> 02:03:42.600
You mentioned Taylor Swift.

02:03:42.680 --> 02:03:44.720
There's a reason why she's a billionaire.

02:03:44.800 --> 02:03:48.600
She's figured out how to make
so much money from her super fans.

02:03:49.360 --> 02:03:52.120
And to the extent
more and more Taylor Swifts exists,

02:03:52.200 --> 02:03:54.560
which, I think, will be the case

02:03:54.640 --> 02:03:58.880
in the individualistic, driven,
you know, society

02:03:58.960 --> 02:04:01.720
that we live in today,

02:04:01.800 --> 02:04:07.400
live, live offline experiences
will do really well.

02:04:07.480 --> 02:04:08.920
And it could be a restaurant.
You know, like,

02:04:09.000 --> 02:04:12.280
what if, you know,
the Japanese sushi chef you mentioned

02:04:12.360 --> 02:04:15.560
was more capitalist-driven?

02:04:15.640 --> 02:04:18.920
Wouldn't you want to do it
in front of like a massive arena,

02:04:19.000 --> 02:04:20.080
or tour the world and do it?

02:04:20.160 --> 02:04:21.760
I don't know, scarcity matters, though.

02:04:21.840 --> 02:04:23.600
I think it's... Scarcity is...

02:04:23.680 --> 02:04:25.320
[Niko] You bring up to a good point, yeah.

02:04:25.400 --> 02:04:27.000
Scarcity will never go away.

02:04:27.080 --> 02:04:30.520
-Desirability comes from scarcity.
-[Niko] Right.

02:04:30.600 --> 02:04:32.400
Wanna rate live events?

02:04:33.200 --> 02:04:34.320
Niko?

02:04:34.400 --> 02:04:39.160
-I'm like, you know, like, an eight.
-[Nikhil] OK.

02:04:39.240 --> 02:04:40.360
Five.

02:04:40.440 --> 02:04:41.480
OK.

02:04:41.560 --> 02:04:43.440
Yeah, I think, philosophically,
I want more live events.

02:04:43.520 --> 02:04:45.520
But I'm with Deedy here, short-term.

02:04:45.600 --> 02:04:48.640
It's, like, six. Like,
where we'll move towards live events.

02:04:48.720 --> 02:04:50.240
Six.

02:04:50.320 --> 02:04:53.240
Again, you know, like,
they're mostly shit businesses,

02:04:53.320 --> 02:04:56.400
but, like, looking to, like,
what happened with the World Cup,

02:04:56.480 --> 02:04:59.200
for, like, the clubs
for soccer in the US.

02:05:00.160 --> 02:05:02.920
Like, this was a brand new
revenue stream out of nowhere.

02:05:03.000 --> 02:05:06.680
Like, the winner pocketed over
100 million, you know, dollars.

02:05:06.760 --> 02:05:07.800
Chelsea.

02:05:08.920 --> 02:05:12.160
We, the Europeans, you know,
are snobs, and we don't care about it.

02:05:12.240 --> 02:05:15.560
But if the numbers, you know, go up,
which is likely in the future,

02:05:15.640 --> 02:05:18.320
would you pay attention to it?
Probably you would.

02:05:18.400 --> 02:05:22.040
But I'll bet still that
digital coverage of soccer

02:05:22.120 --> 02:05:26.680
will have a higher percentage from
an eyeballs and viewership perspective,

02:05:26.760 --> 02:05:28.440
percentage of time perspective
than live events.

02:05:28.520 --> 02:05:30.280
But supply and demand
comes in there, right?

02:05:30.360 --> 02:05:32.600
Like, the supply of digital
is for everyone.

02:05:33.480 --> 02:05:34.840
But novelty of live is...

02:05:34.920 --> 02:05:37.360
Yeah, but I think
that's what we're betting on.

02:05:37.440 --> 02:05:40.920
My way of giving a score is, like,
what do I think percentage of time

02:05:41.000 --> 02:05:43.360
goes up in live events versus digital?

02:05:43.440 --> 02:05:46.360
I would bet screen time goes up higher
than live event time.

02:05:46.440 --> 02:05:48.880
-That's fair.
-And then, my response to you, Niko,

02:05:48.960 --> 02:05:51.040
I think there is more concentration
in live events,

02:05:51.120 --> 02:05:53.000
but not necessarily net volume increase.

02:05:53.080 --> 02:05:55.520
I think more people gravitate
to the Coldplay concerts,

02:05:55.600 --> 02:05:57.080
to the Taylor Swift concerts.

02:05:57.160 --> 02:05:58.920
-That is fair.
-And the Chelsea game.

02:05:59.000 --> 02:06:00.920
But I think most events

02:06:01.000 --> 02:06:04.120
that are not places you want to be seen
are not that interesting.

02:06:04.200 --> 02:06:06.640
That's why when you look
into most ticketing businesses

02:06:06.720 --> 02:06:09.000
that serve the long tail,
they are really shit.

02:06:09.080 --> 02:06:13.120
They can't make money,
nobody shows up, people don't pay.

02:06:14.280 --> 02:06:16.080
OK, last one. Climate tech.

02:06:18.240 --> 02:06:19.960
What is climate tech?

02:06:20.040 --> 02:06:21.280
What's the definition?

02:06:22.360 --> 02:06:23.960
Carbon capture.

02:06:25.480 --> 02:06:28.880
The thesis behind the statement is,
someday soon,

02:06:28.960 --> 02:06:31.560
I mean, it could be carbon credit trading.

02:06:32.720 --> 02:06:35.920
If there were one large event,

02:06:36.000 --> 02:06:38.880
where say 10,000 people die,
say there's a flood in Miami,

02:06:38.960 --> 02:06:40.880
the water levels keep rising.

02:06:41.800 --> 02:06:43.480
Suddenly, everybody...

02:06:44.800 --> 02:06:48.360
will go back to climate
and start taking it very seriously.

02:06:49.000 --> 02:06:51.040
Like, climate tech could even be software.

02:06:51.120 --> 02:06:52.160
Like, I was at this...

02:06:52.240 --> 02:06:54.920
I'm part of this group
called the Gates Pledge,

02:06:55.000 --> 02:06:56.920
where, I think, your colleagues,

02:06:57.000 --> 02:06:59.600
a couple of them are there,
one of them is there.

02:06:59.680 --> 02:07:03.720
And there was this professor this year
who was showing a model that he had built,

02:07:03.800 --> 02:07:08.560
where the base case is world's temperature
will rise by 1.6 degrees by 2100,

02:07:08.640 --> 02:07:10.560
and what can you tweak in the software

02:07:10.640 --> 02:07:11.960
which changes it.

02:07:12.040 --> 02:07:13.440
Is it a carbon tax?

02:07:13.520 --> 02:07:15.320
Is it lesser amount of coal?

02:07:15.400 --> 02:07:17.800
Is it more allocation to nuclear?

02:07:19.160 --> 02:07:22.560
There are funds like Breakthrough Energy,
which are working on this.

02:07:22.640 --> 02:07:25.200
So, all of this somehow
comes into climate tech.

02:07:27.560 --> 02:07:30.520
Yeah, I mean, we need to do
something about it.

02:07:30.600 --> 02:07:33.560
The challenge is, for many humans,
it's hard to relate.

02:07:33.640 --> 02:07:38.080
Even if I live in Miami, and there's
a huge flood, and I lose my home,

02:07:38.160 --> 02:07:40.640
then I might move somewhere else,
and I might forget about it.

02:07:40.720 --> 02:07:42.960
Or my local politician, you know,

02:07:43.040 --> 02:07:46.800
who was responsible for coming up
with subsidies or incentives,

02:07:48.080 --> 02:07:52.400
that stuff, like, doesn't get them
necessarily re-elected in the next cycle.

02:07:52.480 --> 02:07:53.520
Actually, fair point.

02:07:53.600 --> 02:07:56.080
There was a fire here in California,
and everyone's forgotten about it.

02:07:56.160 --> 02:07:57.320
Yes.

02:07:58.440 --> 02:08:00.280
We forget. It's pretty unfortunate.

02:08:02.200 --> 02:08:05.520
I mean, same applies to health stuff.
Like, you know, we had COVID.

02:08:05.600 --> 02:08:08.040
-Yeah, nobody remembers COVID.
-[Niko] No.

02:08:08.960 --> 02:08:11.400
-I think, you know, Niko...
-Moderna remembers.

02:08:11.480 --> 02:08:14.280
Their stock price is down from 400 to 31.

02:08:15.960 --> 02:08:17.440
God bless those guys.

02:08:18.360 --> 02:08:20.600
I think climate tech is a overloaded term,

02:08:20.680 --> 02:08:21.920
'cause it means so many things,

02:08:22.000 --> 02:08:23.840
and a lot of it is a bad word,

02:08:23.920 --> 02:08:26.800
especially in venture
for a bunch of historical reasons.

02:08:26.880 --> 02:08:30.920
But, energy, I think,
unambiguously positive,

02:08:31.000 --> 02:08:33.400
and energy is a big part of climate.

02:08:33.480 --> 02:08:36.120
-So, and...
-You mean, like, renewable energy?

02:08:36.200 --> 02:08:37.240
All energy.

02:08:37.320 --> 02:08:43.160
How do we get cheaper, better,
more sustainable energy?

02:08:43.240 --> 02:08:44.680
Yes.

02:08:44.760 --> 02:08:49.280
So, everything from nuclear
to solar to geothermal.

02:08:49.360 --> 02:08:50.360
I mean, different...

02:08:50.440 --> 02:08:51.920
