02:20:33.640 --> 02:20:37.480
I actually... ChatGPT knows me
probably better than anybody else in life.

02:20:37.560 --> 02:20:39.760
-Wow. Including the wife?
-[Nikhil] Is that a good thing?

02:20:39.840 --> 02:20:41.000
No.

02:20:41.080 --> 02:20:45.560
It has to, because you spend
so much time, sharing your thoughts.

02:20:45.640 --> 02:20:48.520
Everything I write, everything
I talk about, everything.

02:20:48.600 --> 02:20:50.720
-Like, every thought goes through it.
-[Deedy] Wow.

02:20:50.800 --> 02:20:52.680
-I'm fully bionic, that way.
-[Deedy] Wow.

02:20:52.760 --> 02:20:54.200
-Yeah.
-Yeah. I mean, same.

02:20:54.280 --> 02:20:56.280
It says... Oh, I hate the last one.

02:20:56.360 --> 02:20:59.400
But it says, "Analytical,
proactive, visionary".

02:20:59.480 --> 02:21:03.080
I don't think the last agrees,
but the other two, probably true.

02:21:03.160 --> 02:21:05.080
That's great. New LinkedIn headline.

02:21:05.160 --> 02:21:07.320
Now, tell ChatGPT, "Tell me the truth."

02:21:09.240 --> 02:21:11.120
"Tell me the real truth."

02:21:12.000 --> 02:21:13.000
Let's see.

02:21:13.800 --> 02:21:15.080
[Deedy] That's funny.

02:21:15.160 --> 02:21:17.920
This is the real podcast. I love this.

02:21:21.160 --> 02:21:23.160
"Assessing the real truth", let's see.

02:21:23.240 --> 02:21:27.600
Normally, I'm, like,
a little bit more probing.

02:21:27.680 --> 02:21:29.120
-[Deedy] Mm.
-But, today, we're so many people,

02:21:29.200 --> 02:21:31.360
and we're talking about something
I want to get out of the way.

02:21:31.440 --> 02:21:33.280
Mm. Yeah, fair enough.

02:21:34.200 --> 02:21:35.400
"Superpowers.

02:21:35.480 --> 02:21:38.920
Patent spotter, relentless editor,
agency amplifier."

02:21:39.000 --> 02:21:40.160
Can I write this one?

02:21:40.240 --> 02:21:41.600
Yeah, go for it.

02:21:41.680 --> 02:21:43.960
-Please be funny.
-Yeah.

02:21:45.720 --> 02:21:46.920
I'm gonna write...

02:21:48.320 --> 02:21:50.120
"Speak like Jung,

02:21:51.440 --> 02:21:53.560
a therapist I really like.

02:21:56.720 --> 02:22:01.920
"What are my shadow traits
I don't want to take cognisance of?"

02:22:02.000 --> 02:22:06.560
So, Chris Pack did this thing
called "/Graham" on Deer Browser.

02:22:06.640 --> 02:22:08.600
-Did you guys see this?
-[Deedy] No, what is it?

02:22:08.680 --> 02:22:10.760
It basically psychoanalyses you.

02:22:10.840 --> 02:22:12.280
Uh, "slash" what?

02:22:12.360 --> 02:22:14.560
It's called "/Graham",
based on Graham Duncan...

02:22:14.640 --> 02:22:17.400
-[Deedy] Oh, OK.
-...who did this, basically, prompt.

02:22:17.480 --> 02:22:18.800
It's a very good prompt.

02:22:18.880 --> 02:22:22.560
It goes through your Twitter
and just psychoanalyses you.

02:22:22.640 --> 02:22:25.280
I posted mine online so you can see it,

02:22:25.360 --> 02:22:26.960
what it said about me.

02:22:27.040 --> 02:22:28.880
And so, everything
I thought through, everything...

02:22:28.960 --> 02:22:30.440
-Yeah.
-What did it say?

02:22:30.520 --> 02:22:32.280
-You could also...
-It's reflecting right now.

02:22:32.360 --> 02:22:34.000
You could also ask if he's a gambler.

02:22:34.080 --> 02:22:35.640
-You can ask, yeah.
-[Deedy chuckling]

02:22:37.000 --> 02:22:39.200
"My biggest vice is poker."

02:22:39.280 --> 02:22:41.800
"What are my biggest vices,
ChatGPT, tell me?"

02:22:41.880 --> 02:22:44.160
OK, this is getting better.

02:22:45.000 --> 02:22:47.000
Oh, my, you're an expert prompter.

02:22:47.960 --> 02:22:49.360
What does it say?

02:22:49.440 --> 02:22:51.080
"The tyrant of efficiency..."

02:22:51.160 --> 02:22:52.240
-It's true.
-Wow.

02:22:52.320 --> 02:22:56.480
"...counts seconds like coins
and curses every idle breath."

02:22:56.560 --> 02:22:57.560
That is true.

02:22:57.640 --> 02:22:59.800
"The specter of control.

02:22:59.880 --> 02:23:02.120
Fears chaos more than failure."

02:23:03.240 --> 02:23:04.520
Maybe. Yeah.

02:23:04.600 --> 02:23:06.480
"The armour of intellect.

02:23:08.120 --> 02:23:11.800
A polished exterior forged
from logic and data.

02:23:11.880 --> 02:23:14.440
Deflects feelings, both yours and others."

02:23:15.280 --> 02:23:16.280
Yeah.

02:23:16.360 --> 02:23:20.000
"The mirror of validation,
reflects only on achievement.

02:23:20.080 --> 02:23:22.960
Each milestone fades
the moment it is reached,

02:23:23.040 --> 02:23:24.720
demanding the next pry to prove?

02:23:26.200 --> 02:23:27.840
The shadow of exhaustion.

02:23:27.920 --> 02:23:29.520
Invisible at first.

02:23:30.600 --> 02:23:33.160
It whimpers that stamina is limitless.

02:23:34.240 --> 02:23:37.360
Ignore it long enough,
and it steps forward as burnout."

02:23:38.560 --> 02:23:39.560
Better.

02:23:41.000 --> 02:23:44.040
But not that different
from what you said, I mean.

02:23:44.120 --> 02:23:47.240
-Better. Like, a little bit less filtered.
-Yeah.

02:23:47.320 --> 02:23:49.280
I wrote a post called
"I'm not good enough"

02:23:49.360 --> 02:23:51.360
that talks about every failure
I've had in life.

02:23:51.440 --> 02:23:52.520
So...

02:23:52.600 --> 02:23:54.960
This is why humans are better than AI.
We're vulnerable.

02:23:55.040 --> 02:23:56.520
Yeah.

02:23:56.600 --> 02:23:59.480
You can use it, you know,
to our advantage.

02:23:59.560 --> 02:24:01.400
OK, let's rate speculations.

02:24:01.480 --> 02:24:03.840
-Like, Polymarket?
-Yeah, Polymarket.

02:24:03.920 --> 02:24:05.120
Kalshi, all that stuff.

02:24:05.200 --> 02:24:08.160
I mean, without regulation, I'm a ten.

02:24:08.240 --> 02:24:09.320
OK.

02:24:09.400 --> 02:24:11.000
I'm a nine, you know, without regulation.

02:24:12.120 --> 02:24:13.240
-OK.
-Nine.

02:24:13.320 --> 02:24:15.880
Especially if you can include...
It's a part of entertainment for me.

02:24:15.960 --> 02:24:17.120
Nice.

02:24:18.240 --> 02:24:21.360
OK, so, when we spoke
about how the world will change--

02:24:21.440 --> 02:24:24.680
Wait, let me first summarise
what got the highest marks.

02:24:24.760 --> 02:24:26.600
So, we said...

02:24:27.720 --> 02:24:32.640
beauty and luxury is like
a great sector to build in.

02:24:33.440 --> 02:24:34.920
30 out of 30.

02:24:36.680 --> 02:24:39.840
Followed by speculation and gambling.

02:24:41.000 --> 02:24:43.000
-Great sector to build it.
-All vice businesses.

02:24:43.080 --> 02:24:44.400
-[Deedy] Vanity?
-Yeah.

02:24:44.480 --> 02:24:45.760
-It's just vanity.
-Yeah.

02:24:45.840 --> 02:24:50.360
Followed, strangely, by education,
which is outcome-based.

02:24:51.200 --> 02:24:52.560
Yeah.

02:24:52.640 --> 02:24:53.800
Then came...

02:24:54.880 --> 02:25:01.440
world older-sicker, senior living,
content, EV adoption.

02:25:03.120 --> 02:25:04.240
Yeah.

02:25:04.320 --> 02:25:05.520
Those had the same number.

02:25:07.040 --> 02:25:08.720
That's interesting.
We'll put this up on a chart

02:25:08.800 --> 02:25:11.480
and we'll say what each of you said,
and why they said it.

02:25:11.560 --> 02:25:17.880
I feel like this is very useful data,
both, for capital allocators like us,

02:25:17.960 --> 02:25:21.360
but also, if I'm a young kid
looking to start something,

02:25:21.440 --> 02:25:24.520
it allows me to extrapolate
a rate of growth,

02:25:24.600 --> 02:25:27.640
so at least I have some tailwind
in the industry that I'm building.

02:25:27.720 --> 02:25:28.800
Right?

02:25:29.920 --> 02:25:30.960
So...

02:25:31.040 --> 02:25:32.720
I don't know, I would disagree
with that last bit.

02:25:32.800 --> 02:25:34.080
Yeah? Why?

02:25:34.160 --> 02:25:38.360
I think so much about building is more
about where your unfair advantage is,

02:25:38.440 --> 02:25:39.920
not where the macro is going.

02:25:40.000 --> 02:25:43.160
And so, I think, you know,
take beauty for an example.

02:25:43.240 --> 02:25:46.760
Like, I'm sure some of us have friends.
I have friends building in beauty,

02:25:46.840 --> 02:25:49.920
often, I think, you know,
not doing a great job,

02:25:50.000 --> 02:25:51.960
it's not because I don't believe
in beauty-as-a-hack thing...

02:25:52.040 --> 02:25:55.920
You don't have any unfair right to win.
You're not doing this correctly.

02:25:56.000 --> 02:26:00.840
So, I think that's a bigger part
of the equation for me, especially when,

02:26:00.920 --> 02:26:02.560
you know,
young people come to you for advice,

02:26:02.640 --> 02:26:04.160
then you're not going to say,
just because I think

02:26:04.240 --> 02:26:05.560
beauty products are going to do well,

02:26:05.640 --> 02:26:07.480
that you should go do--
build a beauty product.

02:26:07.560 --> 02:26:08.960
Those are not, you know...

02:26:09.040 --> 02:26:10.440
Are you still going to contest

02:26:10.520 --> 02:26:13.160
that your unfair advantage is distribution
because of content?

02:26:13.240 --> 02:26:15.560
-For me?
-Yeah.

02:26:15.640 --> 02:26:17.360
On what?

02:26:17.440 --> 02:26:20.440
-On anything you want to build tomorrow?
-100%. That's one of them.

02:26:20.520 --> 02:26:22.000
-Yeah.
-The main one?

02:26:22.080 --> 02:26:24.360
Probably. It's probably the rarest one.

02:26:24.440 --> 02:26:26.240
I mean, I would say
I have some unfair advantage

02:26:26.320 --> 02:26:28.040
on, like, selling to big enterprises,

02:26:28.120 --> 02:26:29.280
but so many other people do.

02:26:29.360 --> 02:26:33.640
Are you worried that you might be
perceived as a content creator

02:26:33.720 --> 02:26:37.840
versus all the other stuff that you do,
and, hence, you try and push it away?

02:26:37.920 --> 02:26:39.400
Yeah. 100%.

02:26:39.480 --> 02:26:42.240
I don't want people perceiving me as that.
I think it's a terrible tag-line.

02:26:42.320 --> 02:26:44.760
I don't want to be called an influencer
or a content creator.

02:26:44.840 --> 02:26:45.840
-Why not?
-Why not?

02:26:45.920 --> 02:26:46.960
Why not?

02:26:47.040 --> 02:26:52.240
Because this is... I think it comes
with an association that I do not enjoy.

02:26:52.320 --> 02:26:55.520
Right? Like, I do it
for a certain kind of reason.

02:26:55.600 --> 02:26:58.720
And I don't think most people who do it
do it for that same reason.

02:26:58.800 --> 02:27:04.040
And I think when you use the label,
then people interpret it for the latter.

02:27:04.120 --> 02:27:06.440
Like, they think you're doing it for fame,

02:27:06.520 --> 02:27:09.240
glory, yada, yada, yada,
and I don't think I am.

02:27:09.320 --> 02:27:12.280
And so, therefore, I don't like the label.

02:27:12.360 --> 02:27:15.760
But isn't it like a form of storytelling,
form of art?

02:27:15.840 --> 02:27:18.720
If you called it a storyteller,
I would be, like, call me that all day.

02:27:18.800 --> 02:27:19.960
There you go.

02:27:20.040 --> 02:27:23.360
But it's very different
than calling somebody...

02:27:23.440 --> 02:27:26.080
Isn't every influencer a storyteller,
at the end of the day?

02:27:26.160 --> 02:27:29.320
I don't think so.
That's definitely not true.

02:27:29.400 --> 02:27:32.640
Tell me one very popular influencer
who doesn't tell stories well.

02:27:32.720 --> 02:27:34.880
I don't want to diss on
some of these influencers.

02:27:36.760 --> 02:27:38.120
Let's say this.

02:27:38.200 --> 02:27:44.360
If you go on some
of the top Twitter profiles,

02:27:44.440 --> 02:27:48.160
on X or whatever, on X,

02:27:48.240 --> 02:27:50.520
most of them are not telling stories.

02:27:50.600 --> 02:27:52.240
They are inciting rage.

02:27:52.320 --> 02:27:55.600
That's not-- I mean, you could argue
that's some kind of story.

02:27:55.680 --> 02:27:57.200
But that's not really a story.

02:27:57.280 --> 02:27:59.200
They're not trying
to convey anything meaningful.

02:27:59.280 --> 02:28:00.520
It's rage bait.

02:28:00.600 --> 02:28:05.120
They're just taking the contrarian
narrative to the populist one, right?

02:28:05.200 --> 02:28:08.960
Some of them. I don't think--
I think there's a couple of trends.

02:28:09.040 --> 02:28:10.680
One of them is that.

02:28:10.760 --> 02:28:15.200
But a lot of people can be popular
on various different platforms,

02:28:15.280 --> 02:28:17.280
doing things
that don't involve storytelling.

02:28:17.360 --> 02:28:20.440
-What you're also saying is--
-Sharing nude photos of yourself?

02:28:20.520 --> 02:28:22.440
I mean, yeah. Exactly.

02:28:22.520 --> 02:28:24.600
-You're telling some kind of story.
-Have you done that, Niko?

02:28:24.680 --> 02:28:25.920
-You're telling some...
-[laughter]

02:28:26.000 --> 02:28:27.400
[Niko] Have I done it?

02:28:28.520 --> 02:28:30.720
Not like, you know, for popular demand.

02:28:30.800 --> 02:28:32.520
-Yeah.
-Yeah, haven't. Not yet.

02:28:32.600 --> 02:28:34.280
I suspect you're left-leaning.

02:28:35.400 --> 02:28:37.840
-Left-leaning?
-Almost socialist.

02:28:37.920 --> 02:28:39.680
-Almost socialist?
-Wow. Just 'cause he's Greek?

02:28:39.760 --> 02:28:41.240
-How so?
-I don't know.

02:28:41.320 --> 02:28:42.840
Just the things you're saying.

02:28:42.920 --> 02:28:44.400
Things I'm saying, OK.

02:28:44.480 --> 02:28:46.440
There was a distaste for capitalism

02:28:46.520 --> 02:28:48.680
which came across
when you said something earlier.

02:28:49.920 --> 02:28:53.920
Well, I've been working in the US
for the last, you know...

02:28:54.000 --> 02:28:55.840
15 years!

02:28:55.920 --> 02:28:58.160
So, clearly, I'm confused, you know?

02:28:58.240 --> 02:28:59.520
Yeah.

02:29:00.560 --> 02:29:01.920
-Fair point.
-Yeah.

02:29:02.000 --> 02:29:04.000
OK. I'm going to ask you guys
for another opinion

02:29:04.080 --> 02:29:06.080
on a company called Harvey.

02:29:06.160 --> 02:29:08.160
Harvey AI. Thoughts?

02:29:08.240 --> 02:29:10.040
Legal tech. Legal AI.

02:29:10.920 --> 02:29:12.720
Wow. These are very...

02:29:12.800 --> 02:29:15.680
These are companies
I've been meeting in the last two weeks.

02:29:15.760 --> 02:29:20.360
And I've been trying to figure out
how to, maybe, do something with them.

02:29:20.440 --> 02:29:22.240
-Allocation-wise.
-[Deedy] It's difficult to get answers

02:29:22.320 --> 02:29:24.400
out of VCs on companies like this.

02:29:24.480 --> 02:29:26.360
-Why?
-In my understanding.

02:29:26.440 --> 02:29:27.520
-Do you have exposure?
-Yeah.

02:29:27.600 --> 02:29:30.120
Because there's no incentive for us
to ever share a negative view on it.

02:29:30.200 --> 02:29:31.440
No, I think Harvey is very good.

02:29:31.520 --> 02:29:34.080
But, in general,
asking VCs about companies is bad

02:29:34.160 --> 02:29:35.960
because if they're invested,
they have to be positive,

02:29:36.040 --> 02:29:38.640
and if they're not,
they still have to kind of be positive.

02:29:38.720 --> 02:29:41.200
OK, with the caveat
that you're not invested,

02:29:41.280 --> 02:29:43.680
you can give me a more objective opinion.

02:29:43.760 --> 02:29:45.520
Not on camera.
You never get it on camera.

02:29:45.600 --> 02:29:46.680
[Deedy] You just can't.

02:29:46.760 --> 02:29:48.400
Basically, every company
you're going to ask us about,

02:29:48.480 --> 02:29:50.320
all of us are going to say great things.

02:29:50.400 --> 02:29:52.720
Like, that's what's going to happen,
almost no matter what.

02:29:52.800 --> 02:29:55.080
Unless it's a clear disaster company.

02:29:55.160 --> 02:29:56.400
Niko might.

02:29:57.280 --> 02:29:58.440
-He might say...
-I don't know, Niko.

02:29:58.520 --> 02:30:00.720
Can you say anything bad about a company?

02:30:02.720 --> 02:30:04.800
I mean, you can give some criticism,
you know?

02:30:04.880 --> 02:30:06.160
Would you go all out?

02:30:06.240 --> 02:30:07.680
-You wouldn't, right?
-Yeah.

02:30:09.720 --> 02:30:12.360
I don't know as much
about, you know, Harvey

02:30:12.440 --> 02:30:14.680
to give you an informed opinion, OK?

02:30:14.760 --> 02:30:17.120
And I'm not saying that
to sound politically correct.

02:30:17.200 --> 02:30:20.640
But do I think they're building
on the right side of history? They are.

02:30:20.720 --> 02:30:22.560
Have they been amazing

02:30:22.640 --> 02:30:26.800
at signing up a lot of the largest
law firms on the planet?

02:30:26.880 --> 02:30:27.960
They have.

02:30:28.040 --> 02:30:29.800
Has this led to them...

02:30:31.320 --> 02:30:35.160
achieving a capital, like,
fund-raising advantage?

02:30:35.240 --> 02:30:36.240
It has.

02:30:36.320 --> 02:30:40.400
Has this translated
into them recruiting amazing people?

02:30:40.480 --> 02:30:41.680
It has.

02:30:41.760 --> 02:30:44.720
Is their product the best in the space?

02:30:44.800 --> 02:30:46.960
I have no idea.
Not close, you know, to the company.

02:30:48.000 --> 02:30:51.320
But, as you know, Nikunj was saying,
the product has to be really good.

02:30:51.400 --> 02:30:54.640
You know, because attorneys,
for better or for worse,

02:30:54.720 --> 02:30:58.560
you know, after FOMO goes away,
they do care about these things.

02:30:58.640 --> 02:31:00.880
So, like, you know,
given where they are now,

02:31:00.960 --> 02:31:03.760
probably you would get
a really good, informed opinion about them

02:31:03.840 --> 02:31:06.520
if you talk to many other customers

02:31:06.600 --> 02:31:09.480
who've been bombarded
by everyone else and their mother

02:31:09.560 --> 02:31:12.600
who've been starting
AI legal tech companies.

02:31:12.680 --> 02:31:17.800
That's actually one of the spaces
we missed here that has been so busy.

02:31:17.880 --> 02:31:22.200
So, if someone is starting now, a new
legal tech company seed, Series A,

02:31:22.280 --> 02:31:24.640
probably you would say no
to, you know, in the US.

02:31:24.720 --> 02:31:26.000
It's just so busy.

02:31:27.040 --> 02:31:28.360
[Nikunj] I have the opposite take on that.

02:31:28.440 --> 02:31:30.880
-[Niko] Go for it.
-I think-- Not on Harvey,

02:31:30.960 --> 02:31:32.280
but I'm saying, in general,

02:31:32.360 --> 02:31:34.960
especially with the RL focus
and models stabilising...

02:31:35.040 --> 02:31:36.120
[Niko] Yeah.

02:31:36.200 --> 02:31:39.160
...I think the era of second-mover
advantages starts this year.

02:31:39.240 --> 02:31:41.080
-OK.
-Or it starts now, basically,

02:31:41.160 --> 02:31:45.960
where we'll start seeing
even companies started three years ago,

02:31:46.040 --> 02:31:48.200
be disrupted by a better product.

02:31:48.280 --> 02:31:52.200
Now, the David versus Goliath will be,
in just three years,

02:31:52.280 --> 02:31:55.920
can the better product
out-distribute them or not?

02:31:56.000 --> 02:31:58.720
But, for example, if somebody came in

02:31:58.800 --> 02:32:01.160
with, like, a seed,
Series A bet that takes in,

02:32:01.240 --> 02:32:05.000
like, an established giant, not Harvey,
but, in general, in any area,

02:32:05.080 --> 02:32:07.480
but they have, clearly, a better product,

02:32:07.560 --> 02:32:11.120
I would still be interested in,
at least, like, exploring that bet,

02:32:11.200 --> 02:32:13.600
even though they've been out-distributed,

02:32:14.600 --> 02:32:19.280
just because we're seeing such crazy
advances on the technology side.

02:32:19.360 --> 02:32:21.400
And the stacks are leaner.

02:32:21.480 --> 02:32:22.800
Gross margins are better.

02:32:22.880 --> 02:32:24.320
Now, the questions are
just about distribution.

02:32:24.400 --> 02:32:27.080
If it's as great as you sound,
please give us a call.

02:32:27.160 --> 02:32:29.080
[laughter]

02:32:29.160 --> 02:32:31.880
Can I ask, what is India's play
in all this?

02:32:33.160 --> 02:32:36.200
You know, I'm talking
to young entrepreneurs in India.

02:32:36.280 --> 02:32:37.440
Where does India fit in?

02:32:38.440 --> 02:32:42.080
You can be candid. Don't say, "On camera,
I won't say this, that, and the other."

02:32:42.160 --> 02:32:48.920
I think a big problem
in many parts of life is

02:32:49.720 --> 02:32:52.040
when we don't recognise
that there is a problem.

02:32:52.120 --> 02:32:54.920
I don't think you can find a solution
if you don't first get there.

02:32:55.000 --> 02:32:56.040
Yeah.

02:32:56.120 --> 02:32:59.520
And that's where I think
what you mentioned before is important.

02:32:59.600 --> 02:33:04.280
Like, having a knowledge
of where the trends are happening,

02:33:04.360 --> 02:33:06.120
and where, you know,
the growth is going to be.

02:33:06.200 --> 02:33:10.200
Sure. You always want to play,
you know, for your strengths.

02:33:10.280 --> 02:33:13.960
But isn't it even more amazing
when you can play, you know,

02:33:14.040 --> 02:33:17.600
towards your strengths
in the biggest market opportunities?

02:33:17.680 --> 02:33:21.480
Like, I find myself incredibly lucky
that, you know,

02:33:21.560 --> 02:33:24.440
17 years ago, I said, "I'm going to go
and have a career in tech."

02:33:24.520 --> 02:33:28.680
Because none of my friends, the people
I grew up with, you know, did that.

02:33:28.760 --> 02:33:31.760
And it's just a lucky accident,
you know, for me.

02:33:31.840 --> 02:33:35.880
So, like, just knowing
where the trends are heading to

02:33:35.960 --> 02:33:37.840
is important for, like, the youth.

02:33:37.920 --> 02:33:39.280
Yeah.

02:33:42.000 --> 02:33:46.520
I mean, I can give a couple of thoughts
on India and AI.

02:33:48.520 --> 02:33:51.960
And, in general, I've been
somewhat public about this, too.

02:33:52.040 --> 02:33:54.440
And some people have not liked it.

02:33:54.520 --> 02:33:57.000
But, I think...

02:33:57.080 --> 02:34:01.440
unlike other things,
other kinds of technology in the past,

02:34:01.520 --> 02:34:05.360
where you could create a local economy
with that technology,

02:34:05.440 --> 02:34:08.280
I mean, for example, you have your,

02:34:08.360 --> 02:34:13.120
even sharing services
and the gig working booms, OYO,

02:34:13.200 --> 02:34:15.960
you know, existed in India,
just like when Airbnb were,

02:34:16.040 --> 02:34:18.520
or you have an Ola, just like an Uber,

02:34:18.600 --> 02:34:23.560
you can create local versions of those
businesses that work for that area,

02:34:23.640 --> 02:34:26.760
and you're not really competing
unless that other company comes

02:34:26.840 --> 02:34:28.760
and tries to compete in that area.

02:34:28.840 --> 02:34:34.640
On AI, I don't think there is
any local advantage.

02:34:34.720 --> 02:34:38.200
So, I think everyone is competing
on the same playing field.

02:34:38.280 --> 02:34:41.520
And there are a couple of common things
that come up that people say, "Hey,

02:34:41.600 --> 02:34:43.600
these could potentially
be local advantages."

02:34:43.680 --> 02:34:48.720
Like, one is, let's get data
for languages in India.

02:34:48.800 --> 02:34:52.800
Like, yeah, that's great.
I think that's perfectly valid,

02:34:52.880 --> 02:34:56.160
if Google doesn't pour more resources
and try to get the same thing

02:34:56.240 --> 02:34:58.520
and you have an advantage,
that makes sense.

02:34:58.600 --> 02:35:00.080
I like that view.

02:35:00.160 --> 02:35:04.960
But for most other things,
I think I would love to see, I would say,

02:35:05.040 --> 02:35:10.760
India try to compete on that global scale,
and that needs capital, that needs talent,

02:35:10.840 --> 02:35:16.440
that needs just a desire
to want to be on the cutting edge.

02:35:16.520 --> 02:35:19.400
And, in my mind, it's not there yet.

02:35:19.480 --> 02:35:20.760
I mean, I think that's empirical.

02:35:20.840 --> 02:35:24.400
None of the top models are Indian models.
They're American, and they're Chinese.

02:35:25.920 --> 02:35:29.040
In any field, I mean, audio, video, image.

02:35:29.120 --> 02:35:32.880
So, I would say
in the global playing field of AI,

02:35:32.960 --> 02:35:35.720
I mean, the most prominent Indian figures
are probably, like,

02:35:35.800 --> 02:35:37.720
somebody like an Aravind at Perplexity,

02:35:37.800 --> 02:35:42.280
or maybe some of the researchers at
some of these labs and things like that.

02:35:42.360 --> 02:35:44.200
So, therefore, in my opinion,

02:35:44.280 --> 02:35:48.600
today, I wouldn't say
they're competing at a global level.

02:35:48.680 --> 02:35:52.480
I don't know if they have-- people
on the ground have ambition to,

02:35:52.560 --> 02:35:55.520
but I think there's a couple of gaps
to be filled.

02:35:55.600 --> 02:35:56.680
What can they change?

02:35:56.760 --> 02:35:58.720
I mean, the ambition is definitely there.

02:35:58.800 --> 02:36:03.360
What can India do
to get competitive in this realm?

02:36:04.160 --> 02:36:08.000
I think one of the things that is...

02:36:08.080 --> 02:36:10.360
I'll say an observation first,
and I'll answer the question.

02:36:10.440 --> 02:36:13.120
One of the observations I have,
in general,

02:36:13.200 --> 02:36:17.200
about how India reacts to technology is,

02:36:17.280 --> 02:36:20.680
India reacted to AI, like,
"I want to be a part of this,"

02:36:20.760 --> 02:36:22.640
well after this was a thing.

02:36:22.720 --> 02:36:26.520
And that general mindset will
rarely make you win at a thing.

02:36:27.800 --> 02:36:32.680
And so, if you compare that
to China, for example,

02:36:32.760 --> 02:36:35.200
I mean, there are many differences,

02:36:35.280 --> 02:36:38.560
I mean, China has had
so much local talent,

02:36:38.640 --> 02:36:41.800
so much development in math,
so much research in AI

02:36:41.880 --> 02:36:43.960
for many, many years, pre-LLMs,

02:36:44.040 --> 02:36:45.960
that allowed them
to then capitalise on that

02:36:46.040 --> 02:36:48.760
and go like, "OK, look, we can
probably do something here, too.

02:36:48.840 --> 02:36:50.720
We have the base built out."

02:36:50.800 --> 02:36:54.480
And, I think, for India
to do something in AI, like,

02:36:54.560 --> 02:36:56.880
I don't know
if a lot of that base is built up.

02:36:56.960 --> 02:36:58.600
There's a huge talent leakage problem.

02:36:58.680 --> 02:37:02.000
Most of the top AI talent in India
is here, right?

02:37:02.080 --> 02:37:04.960
And literally a three square mile radius
from where we are.

02:37:05.960 --> 02:37:08.480
There's a talent problem,
there's a comp problem.

02:37:08.560 --> 02:37:11.880
Why would a AI researcher want
to be paid in rupees? I don't.

02:37:11.960 --> 02:37:14.200
I want to be paid a million dollars
or a hundred million dollars

02:37:14.280 --> 02:37:15.320
like they're getting paid here.

02:37:16.360 --> 02:37:19.360
And then, there's a general,
systemic problem on,

02:37:19.440 --> 02:37:22.160
like, just capital is
a little bit harder to get.

02:37:22.240 --> 02:37:23.920
And then, resources are harder to get.

02:37:24.000 --> 02:37:26.680
And then, people haven't done work
on GPUs in India.

02:37:26.760 --> 02:37:29.560
If you go into Bangalore today,

02:37:29.640 --> 02:37:31.800
how many people
have ever programmed a GPU?

02:37:31.880 --> 02:37:35.000
Very hard to do anything in AI
if you've never programmed a GPU.

02:37:35.080 --> 02:37:37.320
If you're starting from scratch,
you're gonna have to catch up.

02:37:37.400 --> 02:37:39.000
So, I think there's a lot
of systemic factors.

02:37:39.080 --> 02:37:42.160
And then, to solve that problem,
invest in core research,

02:37:42.240 --> 02:37:44.880
figure out how to keep talent
in the country.

02:37:44.960 --> 02:37:47.520
And you would have to do it a long time

02:37:47.600 --> 02:37:51.120
before something picks up for you
to be able to take advantage of that.

02:37:51.200 --> 02:37:53.840
There's no accident that China
was able to take advantage of that.

02:37:53.920 --> 02:37:57.000
They had a lot of foundation
built in many, many ways.

02:37:57.080 --> 02:37:59.040
So, that's my take.

02:37:59.840 --> 02:38:04.280
I've spent half my life here,
most of my professional life.

02:38:04.360 --> 02:38:06.960
All my professional life. So, I don't
have a view in the India market.

02:38:07.040 --> 02:38:09.560
I mean, a lot of things Deedy says,
I echo.

02:38:09.640 --> 02:38:13.320
But I do think we have to
kind of... The best...

02:38:13.400 --> 02:38:20.360
I think India has a two-decade advantage
from a pure median age perspective.

02:38:20.440 --> 02:38:23.360
Like, the youngest talent
in the world is in India right now.

02:38:23.440 --> 02:38:26.920
And I feel like if you don't capture it
in the next two decades,

02:38:27.000 --> 02:38:29.920
like, that shifts to Africa
or shifts to the next country.

02:38:30.000 --> 02:38:32.640
And I feel-- I don't know
what the answer is,

02:38:32.720 --> 02:38:35.400
but I would love to see us
capture the advantage there,

02:38:35.480 --> 02:38:38.440
at least from a pure,
being in the prime perspective,

02:38:38.520 --> 02:38:41.800
India is in its prime
from a population standpoint.

02:38:41.880 --> 02:38:45.560
And the depth of talent
and the depth of young people.

02:38:45.640 --> 02:38:47.160
So, that's one.

02:38:47.240 --> 02:38:48.560
That's the optimistic side.

02:38:48.640 --> 02:38:52.560
Now, what you do with it
is the main problem.

02:38:52.640 --> 02:38:55.080
But I kind of echo it differently
than Deedy.

02:38:55.160 --> 02:38:57.560
Like, you don't need
the best AI researcher.

02:38:57.640 --> 02:38:59.720
I mean, it would be great if India had
a lot of great AI researchers,

02:38:59.800 --> 02:39:00.840
and they all stayed there,

02:39:00.920 --> 02:39:03.560
but the brain-drain problem has
been true for the past 50 years,

02:39:03.640 --> 02:39:05.360
and that'll continue to stay true.

02:39:05.440 --> 02:39:08.200
All the best Indian entrepreneurs I know
are trying to move here.

02:39:09.120 --> 02:39:12.800
But you try to figure out
where in the playing field do you play.

02:39:12.880 --> 02:39:14.920
Like, you know,
Freshworks is a great example,

02:39:15.000 --> 02:39:19.440
where they took a product that--
and figured out the right markets for it.

02:39:19.520 --> 02:39:22.480
Is there products
in this new AI application era,

02:39:22.560 --> 02:39:24.240
or are there products
in the biotech space?

02:39:24.320 --> 02:39:28.320
India has insane amount of talent
and hospitals and vaccines,

02:39:28.400 --> 02:39:30.640
like, centres are there,
like, manufacturing side.

02:39:30.720 --> 02:39:32.240
Take manufacturing as a sector.

02:39:32.320 --> 02:39:36.760
Like, you know, the China and Plus One
model can really benefit India.

02:39:36.840 --> 02:39:39.720
So, take the sectors
it's going to be phenomenal at,

02:39:39.800 --> 02:39:42.000
and then go from the very bottom
up to the top,

02:39:42.080 --> 02:39:47.280
and see how can you allocate capital,
people, training to win those markets,

02:39:47.360 --> 02:39:49.040
versus play the "me too" movement.

02:39:49.120 --> 02:39:51.360
I feel like a lot of Indians
I meet in India,

02:39:51.440 --> 02:39:53.760
just, like, have this envy,
and they look at the US market,

02:39:53.840 --> 02:39:55.600
and they want to be in the US market

02:39:55.680 --> 02:39:59.600
versus play the games
you're going to be excellent at,

02:39:59.680 --> 02:40:01.280
-and then find ways to...
-Which are?

02:40:01.360 --> 02:40:02.840
-Which are?
-I mean, the things I mentioned.

02:40:02.920 --> 02:40:04.920
Again, but I don't know
the India market as well.

02:40:05.000 --> 02:40:08.720
But I do believe, like,
the China and Plus One is happening.

02:40:08.800 --> 02:40:11.040
Like, it's for 100% happening
from manufacturing...

02:40:11.120 --> 02:40:12.920
-Not in AI.
-Not in AI.

02:40:13.000 --> 02:40:16.240
But that's what I'm saying,
don't miss the AI boat,

02:40:16.320 --> 02:40:17.760
but play on the application level,

02:40:17.840 --> 02:40:20.600
which, I think, India still
has fantastic product engineers

02:40:20.680 --> 02:40:22.960
and designers who can go build that.

02:40:23.040 --> 02:40:26.520
That's a talent that is easily portable
from the pre-AI era,

02:40:26.600 --> 02:40:29.000
and then pick the markets
where it's going to be excellent at.

02:40:29.080 --> 02:40:31.080
I don't know if that's minerals.
I don't know if that's mining.

02:40:31.160 --> 02:40:33.240
I don't know if that's robotics.

02:40:33.320 --> 02:40:36.680
I don't know the India market,
but instead of playing the "me too" side,

02:40:36.760 --> 02:40:39.400
like, "Hey, I want to do this also,"
find it's going to be excellent at,

02:40:39.480 --> 02:40:41.880
and then,
concentrate capital and people there.

02:40:41.960 --> 02:40:46.080
Wouldn't you guys just say that now is
probably the best time it's ever been

02:40:46.160 --> 02:40:53.160
for a young prospective founder
to ever become active in India?

02:40:54.040 --> 02:40:56.760
-Yeah.
-Because, you know, access to knowledge.

02:40:56.840 --> 02:40:58.720
-[Nikhil] Relatively.
-Relatively, yeah.

02:40:58.800 --> 02:41:00.320
-To our own powers.
-Exactly.

02:41:00.400 --> 02:41:05.040
So, access to knowledge,
thanks to your podcast

02:41:05.120 --> 02:41:10.120
and everyone, you know, being part
of the global Internet generation,

02:41:10.200 --> 02:41:11.360
is no longer a problem.

02:41:11.440 --> 02:41:15.640
-Yeah.
-The size of the local market,

02:41:15.720 --> 02:41:18.640
it's been, you know,
larger than it's ever been.

02:41:19.480 --> 02:41:22.840
There are enough, you know,
India for the world companies

02:41:22.920 --> 02:41:26.040
that are now setting the bar pretty high.

02:41:26.120 --> 02:41:29.280
There are enough very successful founders
on the ground,

02:41:29.360 --> 02:41:33.280
like yourself or, like,
over here in the US

02:41:33.360 --> 02:41:35.840
that anyone can look up to.

02:41:35.920 --> 02:41:40.400
Like, I would be, you know, very excited

02:41:40.480 --> 02:41:42.920
to not even consider, you know,

02:41:43.000 --> 02:41:45.600
moving to the US or maybe come here
for a couple of years

02:41:45.680 --> 02:41:47.120
and then go back and build.

02:41:47.200 --> 02:41:49.720
By the way, just on that previous point,
I want to say,

02:41:49.800 --> 02:41:51.640
I was just talking
about foundational AI layer.

02:41:51.720 --> 02:41:53.600
For apps and other,
everything else in the AI layer...

02:41:53.680 --> 02:41:55.880
100%. Many reasons to do stuff in India.

02:41:56.880 --> 02:41:58.720
Could that be the bigger market?

02:41:58.800 --> 02:42:00.640
-Well, 100%.
-[Nikunj] It is.

02:42:00.720 --> 02:42:02.720
-[Nikunj] Already.
-Yeah.

02:42:02.800 --> 02:42:04.000
I mean, I didn't understand, for example,

02:42:04.080 --> 02:42:07.440
why India doesn't have more amazing
gaming companies, you know,

02:42:07.520 --> 02:42:09.360
that could be global leaders
for the world.

02:42:09.440 --> 02:42:11.120
Because of the amount
of money required to build, like,

02:42:11.200 --> 02:42:13.520
a triple-A game is substantial,

02:42:13.600 --> 02:42:15.720
and the risk capital for that
is not there.

02:42:15.800 --> 02:42:18.240
-But you don't need triple-A games.
-But I think it... Exactly.

02:42:18.320 --> 02:42:21.360
I think the future of gaming is
largely not going to be triple-A.

02:42:21.440 --> 02:42:25.800
Like, in a world where everyone is
part of the Internet generation,

02:42:25.880 --> 02:42:27.520
the more brains you have online,

02:42:27.600 --> 02:42:29.880
and the more creativity
you can unlock with AI,

02:42:29.960 --> 02:42:31.960
everyone has superpowers.

02:42:32.040 --> 02:42:34.200
Can we have, you know,
next generation of, like,

02:42:34.280 --> 02:42:36.560
you know, TikTok games,
whatever that means,

02:42:36.640 --> 02:42:41.760
from, like, somebody who is 15 years old
and they've been making stuff online

02:42:41.840 --> 02:42:44.320
for the previous seven years
somewhere in India?

02:42:44.400 --> 02:42:47.840
-That's more likely than ever before.
-You know, I've thought about this a lot.

02:42:47.920 --> 02:42:49.880
And I've tried to arrive
at what the answer

02:42:49.960 --> 02:42:52.400
to that particular question
should be, could be.

02:42:52.480 --> 02:42:55.080
-[Niko] Yeah.
-I think it's cultural.

02:42:56.080 --> 02:43:01.440
We, as Indians, from a very young age,

02:43:02.680 --> 02:43:06.480
are taught to run away from risk.

02:43:07.200 --> 02:43:11.800
We are trained not
to depict any form of rebellion.

02:43:11.880 --> 02:43:13.520
Our teachers are not our teachers.

02:43:13.600 --> 02:43:18.560
Our teachers are like our gods, where
questioning them is almost offending them.

02:43:18.640 --> 02:43:22.120
Religion plays a huge part
in our cultural biases as well.

02:43:22.920 --> 02:43:25.840
So, we have, to some extent--
Nobody's going to like this answer,

02:43:25.920 --> 02:43:28.680
but, we have, to some extent,
become a society

02:43:28.760 --> 02:43:31.800
which does not cherish

02:43:31.880 --> 02:43:36.400
or encourage contesting
the norms of the day.

02:43:36.480 --> 02:43:38.040
And I think that's bad for innovation.

02:43:38.120 --> 02:43:39.360
Is it changing?

02:43:42.400 --> 02:43:44.320
I hope it is. I hope it is.

02:43:44.400 --> 02:43:46.240
I don't know if evidence depicts that.

02:43:46.320 --> 02:43:48.240
But I hope it is
because it will have to change.

02:43:48.320 --> 02:43:50.440
No, with access to education...

02:43:50.520 --> 02:43:52.840
I mean, ChatGPT's number one market
is now India.

02:43:52.920 --> 02:43:55.120
Like, those kind of...

02:43:55.200 --> 02:43:57.000
Like, with Jio...

02:43:57.080 --> 02:44:00.280
Like, kind of everybody
having access to the Internet.

02:44:00.360 --> 02:44:02.520
Like, now it's, like, you know,
fact-checking

02:44:02.600 --> 02:44:04.160
and, you know, people say something.

02:44:04.240 --> 02:44:05.480
I'm curious.

02:44:05.560 --> 02:44:08.040
No, I think the Internet teaches you
many things,

02:44:08.120 --> 02:44:11.720
but I think culture is more
of a factor of our schools

02:44:11.800 --> 02:44:14.400
and what we see in our homes.

02:44:14.480 --> 02:44:15.640
Fair enough.

02:44:16.400 --> 02:44:17.840
Can patriotism be sold?

02:44:18.640 --> 02:44:23.840
Like you mentioned earlier,
there are a lot of brilliant Indian minds

02:44:23.920 --> 02:44:29.480
who are in the US
who are post the financial event.

02:44:29.560 --> 02:44:30.960
Yeah.

02:44:31.040 --> 02:44:34.000
Where, I don't truly believe him
that it has nothing to do with money,

02:44:34.080 --> 02:44:37.520
but they might also want to project
a similar thing.

02:44:37.600 --> 02:44:40.560
And, for them, coming back to India
and starting something

02:44:40.640 --> 02:44:45.720
and adding patriotism to that same
projection could make a lot of sense.

02:44:45.800 --> 02:44:48.200
How can you make patriotism...

02:44:48.280 --> 02:44:51.000
How can you make this,
you know, be like really cool?

02:44:51.080 --> 02:44:52.600
-Patriotism?
-[Niko] Yeah.

02:44:52.680 --> 02:44:55.840
Like what we were saying before, you know,
having kids had become really cool.

02:44:55.920 --> 02:44:59.240
Being a patriot and doing the right thing
for your country should be really cool.

02:44:59.320 --> 02:45:02.400
Like, it was after the Second World War
in the Western society, right?

02:45:02.480 --> 02:45:04.800
I mean, for a funny bit,
Doge kind of did that

02:45:04.880 --> 02:45:06.360
for the government in the US.

02:45:06.440 --> 02:45:08.160
You know, they've got, like,
really smart people.

02:45:08.240 --> 02:45:10.640
There are some of them,
some of our peers are still there.

02:45:10.720 --> 02:45:14.000
I think there will have to be unfair
advantages back home in India.

02:45:14.080 --> 02:45:16.840
Like, I've not thought about this enough,
but say...

02:45:18.600 --> 02:45:22.720
you're a patriotic Indian
who paid X amount of tax

02:45:22.800 --> 02:45:27.320
or you came back to India
just for the patriotic pursuit

02:45:27.400 --> 02:45:29.640
by giving up something substantial,

02:45:29.720 --> 02:45:32.840
maybe there's a toll line on a road,
and you have a separate line.

02:45:32.920 --> 02:45:34.120
Yeah.

02:45:34.200 --> 02:45:36.880
Maybe you have a card
which treats you differently

02:45:36.960 --> 02:45:38.880
with a government agency.

02:45:38.960 --> 02:45:42.080
I think some kind of unfair advantage
has to be weaved into the narrative

02:45:42.160 --> 02:45:45.200
to make this work,
but if at all it is plausible,

02:45:45.280 --> 02:45:47.320
it would be a great thing to attempt.

02:45:47.400 --> 02:45:51.120
Like Nikunj said earlier,
there's two stools...

02:45:51.200 --> 02:45:53.160
-Yeah.
-[Nikunj] Yeah.

02:45:53.240 --> 02:45:55.560
You can get people to be excited
about coming back to India,

02:45:55.640 --> 02:45:57.760
which is, a lot of people are,

02:45:57.840 --> 02:46:01.480
retaining them when they're back
in India is challenging, I mean...

02:46:01.560 --> 02:46:04.600
I think if you could build,
like, a separate city.

02:46:04.680 --> 02:46:07.720
See, the one great thing
India has going for it,

02:46:07.800 --> 02:46:10.080
I think, personally,
is the labour arbitrage.

02:46:10.840 --> 02:46:14.080
A kid living in a hacker house
in San Francisco

02:46:14.160 --> 02:46:16.640
is living a certain quality of life.

02:46:16.720 --> 02:46:19.680
If I take him back, give him two cars,
two drivers, a cook,

02:46:19.760 --> 02:46:22.000
and this and that and the other,

02:46:22.080 --> 02:46:26.160
and he's working essentially online
all day long and he still gets to spend,

02:46:26.240 --> 02:46:29.640
I don't know, 150 days a year here
while building there,

02:46:29.720 --> 02:46:32.280
maybe there's a use case
which works for both.

02:46:32.360 --> 02:46:35.720
NRI City. Let's make it happen.

02:46:35.800 --> 02:46:37.320
And no air pollution.

02:46:37.400 --> 02:46:39.720
Yeah, it doesn't have to be near
any of the big cities.

02:46:39.800 --> 02:46:41.480
-Yeah.
-Yeah.

02:46:42.680 --> 02:46:45.600
This is why, like,
a lot of people move to SF and,

02:46:45.680 --> 02:46:48.760
especially, like, people
who are used to the quality of life

02:46:48.840 --> 02:46:50.160
of India and others and...

02:46:50.240 --> 02:46:52.960
I mean, the quality of life in SF
is horrible.

02:46:53.040 --> 02:46:55.000
Yeah, but the reason...

02:46:55.080 --> 02:46:56.920
-Like, depending on what...
-Depending on how you...

02:46:57.000 --> 02:46:58.320
how you quantify it.

02:46:58.400 --> 02:47:00.520
Like, many of the people
that all of us here are meeting,

02:47:00.600 --> 02:47:04.280
the 20-year-olds who just moved here
three weeks ago, three months ago,

02:47:04.360 --> 02:47:05.760
two years ago,

02:47:05.840 --> 02:47:07.440
they're over the moon.

02:47:07.520 --> 02:47:09.680
It's as if, you know, they're doing drugs

02:47:09.760 --> 02:47:14.480
and their head is, like, exploding
from joy every single moment.

02:47:14.560 --> 02:47:16.520
It's because the most common thing
young people,

02:47:16.600 --> 02:47:18.280
Niko, you guys both know this,

02:47:18.360 --> 02:47:22.520
is, "I have never felt surrounded
by like-minded people in my life,

02:47:22.600 --> 02:47:26.440
and now the nerds are here, and they want
to talk about what I want to talk about.

02:47:26.520 --> 02:47:28.920
Not like the bullshit that everybody else
wants to talk about."

02:47:29.000 --> 02:47:32.720
And that's why people love SF.
That's quality of life.

02:47:32.800 --> 02:47:35.920
It's not like walking on the street
or having a maid and driver.

02:47:36.000 --> 02:47:38.760
So, for this project to work,
critical mass has to be achieved.

02:47:38.840 --> 02:47:41.360
-Yes.
-But I don't know what critical mass is.

02:47:41.440 --> 02:47:44.200
What is that number? Do you want to be
surrounded by a hundred nerdy kids?

02:47:44.280 --> 02:47:46.720
That could be possible.
Is it 10,000? I don't know.

02:47:46.800 --> 02:47:49.200
But it depends
what you're solving for, right?

02:47:49.280 --> 02:47:52.520
Because if I'm a nerdy kid
that was bullied my entire life,

02:47:52.600 --> 02:47:56.560
I come here, I have
the highest status in this society.

02:47:56.640 --> 02:48:00.440
Because here, you know, you're a nerd,
you're, like, top of the line.

02:48:00.520 --> 02:48:02.680
It's like, you have your own,
what you said, you know,

02:48:02.760 --> 02:48:04.680
your own lane in the highway.

02:48:04.760 --> 02:48:07.960
And when you want to pay the tolls,
it's just you, nobody else.

02:48:08.040 --> 02:48:11.840
And then, everyone around you
who is a nerd understands you.

02:48:11.920 --> 02:48:13.880
You're like, "Oh, my God,
people believe in me."

02:48:13.960 --> 02:48:15.800
-Yeah.
-Until now, I was bullied.

02:48:15.880 --> 02:48:17.800
This is like insane, you know?

02:48:17.880 --> 02:48:22.120
It's like being like a slave
and getting liberated.

02:48:22.200 --> 02:48:23.600
[Nikhil] Yeah.

02:48:23.680 --> 02:48:28.920
The example I give everybody is,
like, only in SF, in the entire world,

02:48:29.000 --> 02:48:33.000
when you quit your job,
everybody says congratulations.

02:48:33.080 --> 02:48:34.600
-Yeah. Absolutely.
-That's a great point.

02:48:34.680 --> 02:48:36.320
Only city in the world.

02:48:36.400 --> 02:48:38.360
This doesn't happen anywhere else.

02:48:38.440 --> 02:48:40.120
In India, you're whacked, probably.

02:48:40.200 --> 02:48:42.400
Like, your parents are like,
you know, "What are you doing?"

02:48:42.480 --> 02:48:45.720
Like, in any other country, it's like,
"Oh, my God, I'm so sorry for you."

02:48:45.800 --> 02:48:47.720
Here Niko meets a kid,
he's, like, left the job,

02:48:47.800 --> 02:48:50.120
he's like, "Congratulations.
Here's your term sheet."

02:48:50.200 --> 02:48:53.040
And again, you know, like,
I think the good news is

02:48:53.120 --> 02:48:56.360
that this internet culture for,
like, the young generation

02:48:56.440 --> 02:49:00.920
that's chronically online is
becoming a global phenomenon.

02:49:01.000 --> 02:49:02.120
Yeah.

02:49:02.200 --> 02:49:04.560
And this, where like, you know,
talent is universal,

02:49:04.640 --> 02:49:07.840
but opportunity is not,
like, it's raising all boats, right?

02:49:07.920 --> 02:49:13.760
So, like, critical mass, you can now
have online in a world of abundance.

02:49:13.840 --> 02:49:17.400
Offline, even in a big city, you know?

02:49:17.480 --> 02:49:21.000
It's harder to find those people,
if not everyone, you know, is a nerd.

02:49:21.080 --> 02:49:23.840
I disagree, though.
I mean, COVID was a great reset.

02:49:23.920 --> 02:49:25.920
But it moved right back.

02:49:26.000 --> 02:49:28.800
There were a couple of years
that New York City in the US,

02:49:28.880 --> 02:49:30.720
in terms of seed states,
was looking back--

02:49:30.800 --> 02:49:34.440
Yeah, any neighbourhood in New York,
or like anywhere else you can find it,

02:49:34.520 --> 02:49:37.440
but it's just like a magnet effect.

02:49:37.520 --> 02:49:39.920
-It is a magnet effect, yeah.
-It's just everybody gets around...

02:49:40.000 --> 02:49:43.240
Like, for the past 50 years,
Silicon Valley has done this again

02:49:43.320 --> 02:49:44.600
and again and again and again...

02:49:44.680 --> 02:49:47.560
It is hard to disrupt network events.
It is hard.

02:49:47.640 --> 02:49:51.320
And I'll tell a story about one of my
really, really close friends

02:49:51.400 --> 02:49:54.160
from New York. We've, like,
been friends for 12 years.

02:49:54.240 --> 02:49:57.360
He moved this year,
and he's lived in maybe, like,

02:49:57.440 --> 02:50:00.040
five, six different cities in America.

02:50:00.120 --> 02:50:02.800
He came,
and in month three or something,

02:50:02.880 --> 02:50:04.760
He's like, "Dude, I found my people."

02:50:04.840 --> 02:50:07.080
-Yeah.
-"Where were these people?

02:50:07.160 --> 02:50:10.880
Like, this is why I wasn't enjoying
my time in Miami, in New York.

02:50:10.960 --> 02:50:13.200
It's like, I don't want to talk
about all that.

02:50:13.280 --> 02:50:14.600
I don't want to do all of that."

02:50:14.680 --> 02:50:18.000
And it's like, sure, he did it offline
or, like, online as well,

02:50:18.080 --> 02:50:21.520
but I think it's just
a different sensation when you're like,

02:50:21.600 --> 02:50:23.640
"Shit, man, these are, like,
real people around me

02:50:23.720 --> 02:50:26.160
who actually want
to just explore curiosity."

02:50:26.240 --> 02:50:29.120
I mean, here are some other things
that we take for granted now,

02:50:29.200 --> 02:50:31.560
but no one talks about wealth in SF.

02:50:31.640 --> 02:50:32.800
Mm. I disagree.

02:50:32.880 --> 02:50:34.680
In some circles, yeah, sure.

02:50:34.760 --> 02:50:38.040
But, I mean, compare that to India,
where it's, like, so in-your-face.

02:50:38.120 --> 02:50:41.000
Like, how rich somebody is
is so in-your-face.

02:50:41.080 --> 02:50:43.920
Here, people don't have to drive
a fancy car to show they're rich,

02:50:44.000 --> 02:50:46.440
they don't have to wear fancy clothes
to show they're rich.

02:50:46.520 --> 02:50:48.280
-That's one.
-That's great. That's great.

02:50:48.360 --> 02:50:51.120
People make economically absurd decisions.

02:50:51.200 --> 02:50:54.400
People will reject offers to make
millions and millions of dollars a year

02:50:54.480 --> 02:50:56.000
because they believe.

02:50:56.080 --> 02:50:58.240
And, like, that just doesn't
happen anywhere else.

02:50:58.320 --> 02:51:01.000
God bless all those people,
especially the founding engineers.

02:51:01.080 --> 02:51:02.520
God bless them.

02:51:02.600 --> 02:51:05.920
We wouldn't do well
if our founders wouldn't do well.

02:51:06.000 --> 02:51:10.720
If there's a unique class of people,
founding engineers or founding talent

02:51:10.800 --> 02:51:15.280
that show up a day after your company
gets funded or gets started,

02:51:15.360 --> 02:51:18.320
then they get, like, one-thirtieth
of the equity that you get.

02:51:18.400 --> 02:51:19.760
God bless those people.

02:51:19.840 --> 02:51:21.880
-They're the foundation of...
-The true champions of the industry.

02:51:21.960 --> 02:51:24.360
...the start up
and venture capital industry.

02:51:25.280 --> 02:51:27.680
Well, I think that's a good note
to end tonight on.

02:51:27.760 --> 02:51:31.200
I think we spoke
for a fairly long amount of time.

02:51:31.280 --> 02:51:33.440
Almost three hours.

02:51:33.520 --> 02:51:35.200
But thank you guys for doing this.

02:51:35.280 --> 02:51:37.440
-Sorry I troubled you a little bit.
-That's OK.

02:51:37.520 --> 02:51:39.920
If you were alone with me,
I would have troubled you a lot more...

02:51:40.000 --> 02:51:41.720
[Nikunj] More than welcome to.

02:51:41.800 --> 02:51:44.560
-You could have dug ten times deeper.
-Yeah.

02:51:44.640 --> 02:51:46.120
Maybe the Internet will dig.

02:51:48.040 --> 02:51:50.240
OK, thank you, guys. This was fun.
-[Nikunj] Thank you, Nikhil.

02:51:50.320 --> 02:51:52.960
-[Niko] Thank you. Thank you.
-[Deedy] This was very enjoyable.

02:51:53.040 --> 02:51:55.000
So, I was going to ask you,
have you seen the reel of yourself...

02:51:55.080 --> 02:51:56.600
-I have.
-...imitating you on podcast?

02:51:56.680 --> 02:51:57.880
